<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Balloon Quest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Flight team works to overcome problems as final countdown nears
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Balloon's tentative launch time is 5 a.m. local time on Jan. 1
(1930 GMT Dec. 31) &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ASP101-102
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALICE SPRINGS, Australia (AP) _ Engineers made final adjustments
Thursday to a football stadium-sized balloon designed to carry
three men to record heights and hopefully nonstop around the world.
	   Specialists were preparing to attach the giant, fragile balloon
to the capsule that will carry the three around the earth at
altitudes near the edge of space.
	   But the final countdown for the mission has not yet started and
may again be delayed by dangerously strong winds blowing over the
launch zone in the Australian Outback.
	   Denver real estate magnate Dave Liniger, Albuquerque, New
Mexico, journalist Bob Martin and Australian balloonist John
Wallington will decide after a weather briefing later Thursday
whether to start the countdown clock or hold off for another 24
hours.
	   ``We're just tying up loose ends, the pilots are making some
last-minute adjustments'' said Dan Pedersen, the former U.S. Navy
captain and test fighter pilot who is the team's mission control
director.
	   ``But you can't control the wind.''
	   Engineers and scientists worked late into Wednesday night after
a weight distribution problem was found in the six steel cables
that will connect the fragile balloon with the spaceship-like
capsule upon which the pilots' lives will depend.
	   Temperatures soared to almost 100 F (38 Celsius) at the
Australian Balloon Launch Center Wednesday as more than 60 people
continued final preparations for the Team Re/Max International bid.
	   But winds strong enough to make a launch too dangerous continued
to buffet the desert launch zone near Alice Springs, in central
Australia.
	   The team's own forecasters say weather conditions are looking
good for a dawn takeoff on New Year's Day local time (1930 GMT Dec.
31). The next weather forecast was due at 3 p.m. Thursday local
time (0530 GMT).
	   Until launch, the team were ``checking and rechecking every
circuit, every life support component,'' of the capsule, the
balloon and the radio guidance systems on the ground, Liniger said.
	   The 7-ft. by 8-ft. (2.1-meter by 2.4-meter) capsule will hang
below a balloon made of lunch wrap-thin polyethylene plastic that
when fully inflated is 460 feet (138 meters) in diameter and 700
feet (210 meters) high _ large enough to envelope the Houston
Astrodome or two 747 jet liners nose-to-nose.
	   More than a dozen previous attempts to circle the planet
non-stop by balloon have failed, often when the balloon was forced
down by bad weather.
	   The team hopes to avoid adverse weather by flying in the
stratosphere about 25 miles (40 kilometers) above the earth.
	   That's higher than any previous manned balloon flight.
	   ``There's no question that it's more dangerous than the other
missions,'' which flew at altitudes no greater than 40,000 feet
(12,000 meters), Liniger said.
	   ``The other people, if they get in trouble they can slowly go
down and sit down in the ocean. If we get into trouble, we're 25
miles up.''
</TEXT>
