<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,0446 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After months of deadlock, Mexican Congress agrees on 1999 budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with lower house passing tax part of bill. &QL; 
 &UR; By ADOLFO GARZA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ With only hours to spare, the Congress
finally began approving the 1999 budget narrowly saving Mexico from
a constitutional crisis.
	   The months-old deadlock between the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party and four opposition groups was broken late
Wednesday when the House of Deputies approved the package's tax
bill by a 349-131 vote.
	   Still being debated overnight were the package's expenditure and
other bills, but congressmen said an overall compromise was reached
earlier between the ruling party, known as the PRI, and the
conservative National Action Party.
	   The leftist Democratic Revolution Party, the second largest bloc
in the House of Deputies, voted against the tax bill along with the
tiny Labor and Green parties. Some of the legislation now becomes
law, but other items in the package must still be approved by the
Senate, where the PRI still holds a majority.
	   After 69 years, the PRI lost its House majority in mid-term
elections last year. The deadline for approving the budget was Dec.
31, but the constitution does not specify what will happen if it is
not approved.
	   At the root of the dispute was a pressing need to finance a dlrs
2.86 billion shortfall, due mostly to low world prices for crude
oil of which Mexico is a major exporter. Up until last year, export
revenues by the state petroleum monopoly had financed two-thirds of
the budget.
	   President Ernesto Zedillo had proposed a series of tax
increases, including a 15 percent telephone surcharge on top of the
current 15 percent sales tax. Opposition parties, who now have the
majority in the lower house, opposed the plan, as did business and
civic groups.
	   Zedillo had warned that a budget deficit bigger than 1.25
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) would unleash major
inflation, shoot up interest rates, reduce jobs and disrupt markets
and the economy.
	   The compromise worked out Wednesday made up for the shortfall by
including at least dlrs 1.4 billion in spending cuts, a higher
corporate income tax rate than Zedillo had proposed, and higher
diesel fuel prices charged by the state-owned oil monopoly.
	   The revised dlrs 103 billion budget also calls for higher
tariffs on goods from countries with which Mexico doesn't have free
trade agreements. Those tariffs will not affect major trading
partners such as the United States, Canada or much of Latin
America.
</TEXT>
