w1581 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Japan-UpontheRoof     12-31 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Japan-Up on the Roof,0787 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Future of Tokyo neighborhoods may be up on a rooftop
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY315 of Dec. 21 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN FACKLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The Tomihisa neighborhood suffers from many of the
same problems afflicting inner city areas all over the world.
	   Graffiti and trash clutter abandoned buildings. Homeless sleep
in shelters fashioned from cardboard boxes. High school kids huddle
in a vacant lot while one keeps watch on the street.
	   But Yoshiko Masuda has a plan to save Tomihisa.
	   The Tokyo architect wants to tear the neighborhood down and
rebuild it, narrow back alleys, tree-studded parks, shrine and all
_ on top of a new seven-story building.
	   As outlandish as her idea might sound, city planners see
Masuda's project as a possible blueprint for the future.
	   ``This could serve as a precedent,'' says Seigo Maruta, an
official at the Housing and Urban Development Corp.
	   The neighborhood is a microcosm of the problems that have
befallen urban Japan since the land development craze that swept
over much of the country during the booming 1980s.
	   A quiet neighborhood of two-story wooden houses clustered in an
area the size of a New York City block, Tomihisa became the site of
particularly frenzied buying because of its proximity to a major
entertainment and office area.
	   At the boom's peak in 1992, developers with briefcases full of
cash knocked on doors offering to buy houses on the spot. Residents
sold out as lots that cost the equivalent of dlrs 375 in the 1950s
were snapped up for dlrs 5.6 million, says Hiroichi Shoji, head of
the Tomihisa neighborhood association.
	   When the bust came, development plans evaporated and Tomihisa
was left with weed-filled lots, vacant buildings and a growing
crime rate. Almost half the neighborhood sits unused six years
later.
	   ``Our town became a slum,'' says Shoji, who's lived in Tomihisa
for 50 years.
	   Masuda wants to lift Tomihisa above all that.
	   Moving residents into new houses built on a rooftop 92 feet (28
meters) above the street will make security easier to manage: The
only entry will be elevators and stairwells fitted with locks.
	   The architect's design also aims to stem the flight of residents
to the suburbs by adding new amenities, including a community
center complete with day care, a nursing home and a gym.
	   Masuda says the project makes economic sense, too.
	   Renting out space in the building beneath as offices and regular
apartments is expected to cover the dlrs 60 million to dlrs 70
million construction cost and provide extra income for Tomihisa
residents as they retire.
	   ``I was looking for a way to make the community last,'' she
says.
	   While penthouse dwellings on rooftops have a long history in
urban architecture, no one's ever attempted to build _ much less
transplant _ a neighborhood to the top of a building.
	   Experts caution that similar, more modest projects in the past,
such as putting parks atop urban buildings, have generally not been
well received by the public.
	   ``Given the choice, people prefer to go about their private
lives on the ground and ascend buildings only to work,'' says
Terunobu Fujimori, a professor of architecture at the University of
Tokyo.
	   But architects agree Masuda's design could be different.
	   At 2.5 acres (1.01 hectares), the roof would large enough for
life in Tomihisa to feel like it did on the ground. There would be
plenty of room to toss a ball, take a stroll down a shaded lane,
even enjoy a picnic.
	   Residents have given the neighborhood association near unanimous
support to pursue the project, but some admit to unease.
	   ``I've never wanted to live in a building with an elevator,''
says one middle-aged woman, who asks to remain anonymous to avoid
angering neighbors.
	   The most formidable hurdle has proved to be buying up the vacant
lots and abandoned buildings.
	   The banks that took over the properties from defunct developers
refused to sell to avoid recording the loss. Then there was the
hefty price tag: dlrs 25 million even at today's vastly deflated
prices.
	   Japan's recession has actually provided a breakthrough, however.
	   Since June, the government has been pumping billions of dollars
into urban renewal projects in an effort to boost its stagnant
economy. Some of that may flow to Tomihisa.
	   Persistent lobbying has put the neighborhood near the top of the
government's list of projects to finance, and money could be
available in 1999, says Maruta at the Housing and Urban Development
Corp.
	   Once construction starts, Masuda says she can get the project
done in about two years.
	   ``Tomihisa will just be the first,'' she says. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Japan-Up on the Roof; CT:i; 
