w1589 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKorea-Bank     12-31 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Bank </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korea to sell Korea First Bank to U.S. financial firms
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Planned

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea agreed Thursday to sell
heavily indebted Korea First Bank to an American financial
consortium in a bid to boost foreign investors' confidence in its
crisis-hit economy.
	   The Newbridge Capital-GE Capital Services consortium outbid HSBC
Holdings PLC of Britain to take over 51 percent of Korea First
Bank, which is currently owned by the government, said bank
officials.
	   They refused to divulge further details until the government's
Financial Supervisory Commission makes a formal announcement later
Thursday.
	   But the national Yonhap News Agency, quoting commission
officials, reported that Newbridge and GE Capital will raise its
stake to 75.5 percent next year.
	   Thursday's sale is part of a promise by South Korea to
restructure its financial sector and open it to foreign investment
in return for a record dlrs 58 billion economic bailout package
announced by the International Monetary Fund a year ago.
	   When the economy slowed down and companies began collapsing last
year, Korea First and other banks were left with mountains of bad
loans, triggering a sudden loss of international confidence that
led to the country's financial crisis.
	   So far, the government has poured 3.6 trillion won (dlrs 3
billion) into Korea First Bank to write off half of its bad loans.
It also bought 94 percent of the bank's shares.
	   The bank has shed 2,900 workers, or 38 percent of its total work
force, and closed down 74 of its 413 retail branches across the
country in a restructuring program aimed at wooing foreign
investors.
	   President Kim Dae-jung has considered bank reform crucial to
restoring investors's confidence in the country.
	   South Korea so far has shut down 16 merchant banks and four
insurance companies and forced five small commercial banks to be
merged with bigger banks.
	   Major commercial banks are discussing more mergers as the
government is offering tax benefits and debt write-offs as
incentives.
	   Foreign banks are allowed to open retail branches, but the cost
of matching the vast number of branches owned by existing South
Korean banks would be prohibitive. That makes the takeover of an
existing bank especially attractive, experts say.
	   GE Capital is a unit of General Electric Of the United States.
Newbridge Capital Ltd. is a Texas-based investment fund.
</TEXT>
