<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-World Junior Championship,0501 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sweden advances to semifinals
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) _ Henrik Sedin scored three goals to
help Sweden clinch first place in the B Pool at the world junior
hockey championship with a 5-4 victory Wednesday over Belarus.
	   In other games, Slovakia defeated the United States 3-2,
Kazakstan shut out Switzerland 3-0, and Canada topped the Czech
Republic 2-0.
	   The victory gave the Swedes a 3-0-0 record, with one game left
against Kazakstan (1-1-1) in the round-robin portion of the
competition. Russia, second in the five-team pool with a 2-1-0
record, plays Switzerland (1-2-0) Thursday night.
	   The top three teams from each of the two pools advance to the
medal round, with the first-place squad getting a bye to the
semifinals. The second-place team in one pool plays the third-place
team from the other pool in quarterfinal action Saturday.
	   Slovakia remained atop the A Pool, finishing with a 3-0-1
record. Canada (2-0-1) takes on the United States (0-3-0) Thursday
night, while Finland (1-2-0) goes against the Czechs (1-2-0) in a
battle for third place in the pool. A win by the Canadians would
give them first place in their pool.
	   The Swedes almost wasted a 5-1 lead against Belarus.
	   Sedin, who has been tabbed as a potential top-five NHL draft
pick along with his brother, Daniel, scored twice in the first
period.
	   Christian Berglund and Marcus Kristoffersson made it 4-0 by 7:04
of the second period before Kanstantsin Kaltsou broke the shutout.
	   Sedin made it 5-1 at 3:58 of the third, but Pavel Bely scored
for Belarus at 5:06, Kaltsou scored again just eight seconds later
and Aliaksei Andreyeu made it a one-goal game at 6:28.
	   The Swedes were forced to kill back-to-back minor penalties in
the final minutes of the game to survive with the win.
	   Berglund also had three assists and Daniel Sedin two assists.
	   Kaltsou took over the lead among tournament scorers with four
goals and two assists.
	   Nikolay Antropov had one goal and an assist for Kazakstan in the
victory over Switzerland. Rostam Yessirkenov and Nikolay
Zarzhytskiy, shorthanded, also scored for Kazakstan.
	   The Slovaks _ the big surprise of the tournament _ did all they
could to put themselves in position for a bye to the semifinals.
	   Michal Hudec scored with 24 seconds left in the third period to
give the Slovaks the victory over the United States in a
penalty-filled contest. More than a dozen minors were called.
	   Miroslav Zalesak and Brian Gionta exchanged goals in the second
period.
	   Douglas Janik gave the Americans a 2-1 lead 3:24 into the second
period, but Roman Macoszek tied the game at 7:24.
	   Brian Campbell and Daniel Tkaczuk scored for Canada in the
victory over the Czech Republic. Goaltender Roberto Luongo made 29
saves for his second shutout of the tournament. Canada has allowed
just four goals in three games, matched only by Russia.
</TEXT>
