<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-NHL Roundup,0681 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dackell's overtime goal gives Senators victory over Sabres
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUFFALO, New York (AP) _ Andreas Dackell scored 2:24 into
overtime to give the Ottawa Senators a 3-2 victory over Dominik
Hasek and the Buffalo Sabres on Wednesday night.
	   Dackell, who added two assists, snuck the puck past Hasek for
his seventh goal of the season.
	   Shawn McEachern scored two goals for Ottawa, including the tying
goal in the third period.
	   Hasek made 41 saves for the Sabres, who lost their second
straight home game. The Sabres' last two-game losing streak at home
was in 1997.
	   Damian Rhodes, making his fourth start of December and first in
six games after battling the flu, stopped 21 shots for Ottawa, who
snapped their three-game road losing streak.
 &UR; Devils 3, Capitals 2
	   In Washington, Bobby Holik scored with 12:46 remaining to extend
New Jersey's unbeaten road streak to seven (6-0-1).
	   Washington, the defending Eastern Conference champions but mired
with the second-worst record in the conference this season, was
trying to win back-to-back games for only the second time this
season.
	   Vadim Sharifijanov and Brian Rolston also scored for the Devils.
	   Michael Pivonka, who missed the first 29 games recovering from
shoulder surgery, scored his first of the year for the Capitals.
 &UR; Penguins 7, Panthers 4
	   In Pittsburgh, Kip Miller scored two goals for the first time in
eight years to lead Pittsburgh to an easy victory.
	   Robert Lang and Martin Straka also scored twice as the Penguins
won despite allowing a pair of shorthanded goals.
	   Radek Dvorak scored two goals for Florida, including the team's
first shorthanded tally. Viktor Kozlov also scored shorthanded.
 &UR; Maple Leafs 4, Mighty Ducks 1
	   In Toronto, defenseman Jason Smith had a goal and an assist and
Tannick Tremblay scored his first of the season in Toronto's win.
	   Tie Domi and Fredrik Modin also scored for Toronto, which took
39 shots on Anaheim goalie Guy Hebert.
	   The Leafs ended a seven-game homestand with a 4-3 record. The
loss ended Anaheim's three-game road unbeaten string.
	   Anaheim's Paul Kariya, who entered the game second in the NHL in
goals, had an assist but went his sixth consecutive game without a
goal. He has just one goal in his last 13 contests.
	   Teemu Selanne spoiled Curtis Joseph's shutout bid at 6:50 of the
third period.
 &UR; Bruins 5, Predators 2
	   In Nashville, Tennessee, Sergei Samsonov's goal helped Boston
snap a season-high, three-game losing streak.
	   It was the Predators' first home loss since Dec. 5. The win gave
the Bruins a record of 14-1-3 against 1990s expansion teams in
their first seasons of play. Boston is 10-5-2 in its last 17 games.
	   Anson Carter, Peter Ferraro and Steve Heinze added goals for the
Bruins.
	   Sebastien Bordeleau spoiled Boston goaltender Rob Tallas'
shutout bid midway through the final period, tipping Patrick Cote's
pass from the left corner past him.
 &UR; Coyotes 3, Rangers 1
	   In Phoenix, Rick Tocchet's goal at 18:16 of the second period
helped Phoenix win despite the absence of Keith Tkachuk and Jeremy
Roenick.
	   Nikolai Khabibulin turned back 28 shots for the Coyotes.
	   Daniel Briere and Bob Corkum also scored for Phoenix, whose top
two players were out with injuries. The Coyotes also were minus
Dallas Drake, serving a suspension.
	   Niklas Sundstrom scored the lone goal for the Rangers, who have
lost six of their last eight games.
 &UR; Hurricanes 4, Lightning 3
	   In Greensboro, North Carolina, Kevin Dineen, Gary Roberts and
Ron Francis each scored third-period goals to rally Carolina.
	   Dineen and Roberts scored 53 seconds apart early in the third
period while Francis beat Bill Ranford with 1:07 left.
	   Wendel Clark scored three goals for the Lightning.
	   Paul Coffey, acquired Tuesday night from Chicago, didn't score
in his Carolina debut.
	   The loss by Tampa Bay denied Jacques Demers his 400th NHL
coaching victory.
</TEXT>
