w1600 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Pakistan-Hanging     12-31 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Hanging,0275 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan hangs first person sentenced to death by military court in
</HEADLINE>
Karachi &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ Authorities on Thursday executed the
first person sentenced to death by a special anti-terrorism
military court in the southern port city of Karachi.
	   Ashraf Irani, in his early 30's, who was convicted in the second
week of December of killing a policeman, was hanged at the Karachi
Central Prison early Thursday, prison officials said. President
Rafiq Tarar rejected his mercy appeal on Wednesday night.
	   Three other people convicted in the same case received prison
sentences ranging from 10 to 14 years.
	   Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has recommended that the president
not issue any pardons to people sentenced by the military courts,
the English-language daily, The News, reported Thursday.
	   The government set up military courts last month to try persons
responsible for ''violence and terrorism'' in Karachi, where more
than 1,000 people have been killed in political and religious
violence in 1998.
	   In October, the government imposed direct federal rule in Sindh
province of which Karachi is the capital. The government suspended
civil rights in Sindh and ordered the army to help curb the
violence in Karachi.
	   Opposition parties and human rights groups have bitterly
criticized the government's moves. They have accused it of
violating the constitution and undermining the judiciary by setting
up the military courts.
	   But Sharif says these steps are needed to restore order in
Karachi _ the main commercial hub and the only port city of
Pakistan.
</TEXT>
