r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-US-Fighters     12-31 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-US-Fighters </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thailand negotiates with U.S. to upgrade fighters
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MICOOL BROOKE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand is negotiating with the United
States to upgrade Thai air force fighter jets following the
termination of a contract to buy eight F/A-18s due to the economic
crisis, a U.S. official said.
	   The U.S. Embassy official said Wednesday that the talks were
part of an ongoing dialogue on Thailand's defense needs but were
``still in the preliminary stages.''
	   ``It would therefore be premature to identify any weapons
systems that Thailand might procure from the United States,'' the
spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
	   But a Bangkok-based U.S. arms dealer familiar with the
negotiations said on condition of anonymity that the talks may
concern the sale of used F-16 fighters and upgrades to enable the
planes to carry the advanced AIM-120 medium-range air-to-air
missiles.
	   The sophisticated missiles are currently not used by any air
force in the region, but Thailand's southern neighbor, Malaysia,
has bought Russian-built MiG-29 fighters, which carry an equivalent
missile.
	   Southeast Asia was in the midst of a mini-arms race before the
economic crisis led to recession and defense cutbacks across the
region.
	   Thai officers say an arms race is financially impossible now.
	   Lt. Gen. Somsak Salyakmtorn, director of the Thai armed forces'
civil affairs office, said that the country was not worried about
the Russian hardware going to Malaysia.
	   ``We are all working toward the same goal of developing the same
defense capability, which is to be conducted in a transparent
manner in order to maintain trust and a balance of power in the
region,'' Somsak said.
	   In an unusual move aimed at easing Thailand's burden, President
Clinton allowed Thailand to terminate a contract to buy F/A-18s and
lose only the dlrs 74.5 million down payment.
	   The contract had called for dlrs 317 million more to be paid for
delivery of the jets or a penalty of dlrs 250 million to cancel it.
	   The Bangkok Post reported Wednesday that Thailand hopes to trade
dlrs 40 million in F/A-18 spare parts already delivered to help pay
for used F-16s.
	   Thai military officers visited Washington in Decemeber to
discuss F-16 prices, reportedly about dlrs 8 million for a used
model. A follow up visit is planned in February, Thai generals say.
</TEXT>
