<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-Pacific </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gridiron bombs in the Pacific
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT KEITH-REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SUVA, Fiji (AP) _ As college football titles and the Super Bowl
approaches, efforts by an American promoter to establish gridiron,
or American football, in the rugby union-mad Pacific Islands
appears to have bombed badly.
	   An inaugural match due to have been played in the Fiji capital
of Suva on Tuesday between Fiji and Tonga didn't happen because the
Tongan team didn't show up.
	   Disappointed spectators seeking a refund for their 5 Fijian
dollars (U.S. dlrs 2.50) ticket were told by Fiji Gridiron
Association manager Aisake Seru that there had been difficulties
getting the Tongan team flown to Fiji since the airline had wanted
ticket money up front.
	   He promised games would be played on the weekend or next
Tuesday.
	   A local travel company which organizers said had arranged travel
for the Tongans denied having done so when contacted by The
Associated Press.
	   In the Cook Islands, games scheduled to begin 10 days ago were
also delayed.
	   Local organizer John Teao said the delay was cause by ``backing
American companies being tied up in hotel deals in Tonga.''
	   Local newspaper The Cook Island News reported that no airline
bookings had been made for a 40-player gridiron squad asked to go
to New Zealand.
	   American promoter Isiah Cater, describing himself as ``Director
of Football for the U.S. National Professional Minor League
Football Conference,'' said the organization was ready to invest
money in establishing gridiron in Fiji, Tonga, Samoa, Papua New
Guinea, Vanuatu, the Cook Islands Australia, New Zealand and
perhaps Nauru.
	   He claimed that a Pacific championship between 14 teams would be
played during June to August 1999.
	   Cater said about 144,000 Fijian dollars (U.S. dlrs 72,000) had
been spent teaching Fijian ruby union players to play gridiron.
	   After's Tuesday's flop, Cater told a Fiji radio station he
``might have to pack up and leave if things don't fall into
place.''
	   ``We'll treat it like a business and take it as a loss,'' he
said.
	   Alice Tabete, chief executive of the Fiji Sports Council, said
ground maintenance staff had been called back from Christmas
vacation to prepare the national stadium in Suva, which had been
closed for repairs.
	   Fiji's Sports Minister Jonetani Kaukimoce directed that the
stadium be prepared for gridiron.
	   Tabete said the association wanted a 5,000 Fijian dollars (U.S.
dlrs 2,500) deposit from the gridiron promoters before considering
another date for the Tonga-Fiji match. (rkr-rs/djp)	   
</TEXT>
