</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Australia-England </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pitch could favor returning Warne
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Shane Warne can expect a receptive
pitch for his test comeback with the Sydney Cricket Ground wicket
expected to aid spinners in the latter stages of the fifth test
against England beginning Saturday.
	   However, Sydney Cricket and Sportsground Trust chief executive
Noel Neate on Thursday predicted the test strip would also offer
early assistance for pacemen.
	   Warne, hoping to play his first test in eight months following
shoulder surgery, collected two expensive wickets for Victoria in
his last Sheffield Shield outing against New South Wales earlier
this month.
	   ``The pitch looks to be good, obviously we would expect it to
turn in the latter part of the game, but there should be a bit in
it for the quicks in the early part,'' Neate said.
	   ``The ground has come up superbly, it's as we expected and if
the players can pull a good one out of the bag, I don't think the
ground will have a bearing on the game.''
	   Warne was included as one of three spinners in the Australian 12
along with fellow legspinner Stuart MacGill and Colin Miller, with
some reports suggesting Warne was third in line to start.
	   However, Warne's likely return, along with England's fourth-test
victory in Melbourne, has sparked an upsurge in ticket sales with a
bumper crowd expected for the opening day on Saturday.
	   ``Obviously the result in Melbourne has rekindled a bit of
interest,'' Neate said. ``I think we're looking for the best first
day of a test match that we've had for quite some time, I wouldn't
be at all surprised to see it nudge up towards the 40,000 mark.''
	   (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
