w1642 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge 1stLd-Writethru   12-31 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede PHNOM PENH
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Khmer Rouge leaders enjoy beach holiday; UN probes possible trial
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES thruout with Khmer Rouge leaders checking
into beach resort; ADDS details, background; CHANGES byline.
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SIHANOUKVILLE, Cambodia (AP) _ Two Khmer Rouge leaders under
controversial government protection checked into a secluded
Cambodian beach hotel for a holiday Thursday as U.N. officials
pondered dwindling options for bringing them to justice for
genocide.
	   After basking in red-carpet treatment in Phnom Penh for two
days, Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea began a tour of the country they
helped turn into a bloody slave-labor camp when the leftist Khmer
Rouge movement held power from 1975 to 1979.
	   Escorted by military police providing tight security, the two
drove with their families in luxury vehicles to the seaside town of
Sihanoukville, the first leg of a tour that will take them to the
ancient Angkor temple complex and their home provinces.
	   Along the roads, they will pass memorials stacked with the bones
and skulls of thousands of their victims, irrigation ditches dug by
hand under the murderous eye of Khmer Rouge overseers and fields
strewn with mines from years of civil war.
	   The two guerrilla chiefs, who share blame for the deaths of up
to 2 million Cambodians under the Khmer Rouge, emerged from years
in the jungles last week and sealed a defection deal with Prime
Minister Hun Sen that included assurances they would not face
trial.
	   They told a news conference Tuesday that they were ``very
sorry'' for the reign of terror but refused to accept personal
responsibility, inviting survivors to ``let bygones be bygones.''
	   They did not speak to reporters Thursday on arriving at the best
hotel in Sihanoukville, where they had rooms with a view of the
Gulf of Thailand 50 meters (yards) away across sparkling sands.
	   The de facto pardon they are receiving from Hun Sen, which
contradicted earlier pronouncements by him that remaining Khmer
Rouge leaders would stand trial if captured, has shaken hopes that
the architects of their murderous rule will ever face justice.
	   At the request of Cambodia's leaders, the United Nations sent
legal experts to Cambodia last month to assess evidence against
senior Khmer Rouge members and offer recommendations for a
tribunal, either overseas or in Cambodia.
	   ``The defection of Noun Chea and Khieu Samphan does not change
the plans,'' said Thomas Hammarberg, the U.N.'s top human rights
officer for Cambodia, from his home in Sweden.
	   ``We intend to present their recommendations as soon as possible
to the government and hope for a constructive discussion,''
Hammarberg said.
	   King Norodom Sihanouk, who initially voiced support for Hun
Sen's defection deal, said Wednesday he would in fact not provide
amnesties for Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea because of ``undeniable
discontent'' among a majority of Cambodians in seeing them go free.
	   Hun Sen has since been silent, but as Cambodia's most powerful
man he can easily pressure the pliant courts to ensure there is no
trial.
	   Hopes for prosecution now seem to rest with the United Nations,
which can pass resolutions to try Khmer Rouge leaders overseas
through an as yet non-existent international tribunal.
	   Sihanouk voiced his support for that option when he said the
international community had ``the perfect right to take up the case
of genocide in Cambodia'' because it was a crime against humanity.
	   However, Hun Sen's cooperation would be needed to arrest them.
	   Several possibilities are being considered by the U.N. team,
according to Hammarberg, who said it was necessary to send a
message to future generations in Cambodia that atrocities must be
punished.
	   ``Considering the scale and the brutality of the Khmer Rouge
crimes, genuine healing in Cambodia will be extremely difficult
without a justice process,'' Hammarberg said.
	   The Khmer Rouge won a civil war in 1975 and forced the
population to toil in Maoist-inspired agricultural collectives. One
Cambodian in five died of overwork, starvation, disease and
systematic executions.
	   The revolutionaries were overthrown in 1979 by a Vietnamese
invasion, but fought a guerrilla war from the jungles.
	   In 1996, Sihanouk granted amnesty to one leader, Ieng Sary, who
led thousands of fighters to peace. The Khmer Rouge has since
dwindled to near-extinction and poses no threat to the central
government.
	   Many in Cambodia dispute Hun Sen's assertion that amnesty is
needed for Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea to prevent renewed war.
Pressure is growing for someone to be held accountable for Khmer
Rouge crimes. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
