<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Prison Breaks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0404 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sixteen inmates escape in three Chiapas prison breaks, four
</HEADLINE>
wounded &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: NEW to some points. Fixes overline to CORRECT number of
escapees to 16, recasts lead to clarify that of five inmates
recaptured, four of them were wounded; EDITS. &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEJANDRO RUIZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Sixteen inmates
escaped in three separate prison breaks in southeastern Chiapas
state, a top official said. Five of them were recaptured, including
four who were wounded by gunfire.
	   State attorney general Eduardo Montoya Lievano said the escapes
Wednesday in the towns of Simojovel, Playas de Catazaja and
Ocosingo _ which included a prison disturbance _ were unrelated.
	   In a telephone interview, Montoya blamed negligence or possible
complicity by guards in the three prisons. He said a number of
guards were detained for questioning, but refused to give details.
	   All the fleeing inmates were serving time for homicide and other
major felonies. Prisons in the state are generally overcrowded.
	   The first break occurred early Wednesday when two inmates
serving time for murder fled the jail in Simojovel, in the northern
part of the state.
	   Montoya said the guards there initially told investigators 10
armed men wearing ski masks, like those used by Zapatista National
Liberation Army rebels, freed the two prisoners. But he added that
account proved untrue later, but gave no further details.
	   ``There is no indication they were involved, it appears there
was negligence by the guards,'' he said.
	   Friday marks the fifth anniversary of a brief uprising by the
Zapatistas, who took up arms Jan. 1, 1994, and fought the army for
12 days until a ceasefire was called. About 145 people were killed
in the fighting then.
	   Later in the day, nine convicts serving time for homicide
escaped during a prison mutiny in Playas de Catazaja. The prisoners
rioted to protest the lack of drinking water.
	   Montoya said the guards opened fire, wounding four inmates. The
four and another inmate were later recaptured. He said the
disturbance was quelled, but several guards are being questioned.
	   At about the same time, five inmates walked out of the prison in
Ososingo, a town in the jungle in the southern part of the state,
without anyone doing anything to stop them, Montoya said. 	   
</TEXT>
