<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Opposition, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police in Singapore charge politician for public speech
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES to INSERT new 4th-5th grafs with comments from Chee.

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Police in Singapore charged an opposition party
leader Thursday for allegedly giving a political speech without a
permit earlier this week, and served him a court summons at his
home.
	   Chee Soon Juan, secretary-general of the 200-member Singapore
Democratic Party, was ordered to appear in Subordinate Court on
Monday. If convicted, he faces a fine of 5,000 Singapore dollars
(dlrs 3,030).
	   Chee, 36, had addressed a crowd of more than 250 people during
the lunch hour Tuesday on a lawn at Raffles Place in Singapore's
business district. He criticized the government's economic, human
rights and foreign affairs policies.
	   In a statement faxed to the news media Thursday, Chee said the
charge against him ``for speaking in public is another attempt by
the government to silence me and stifle the growing voice of
democracy in Singapore.
	   ``This is a clear violation of my fundamental rights to freedoms
of speech, assembly, and association guaranteed in the constitution
of Singapore,'' he said. ``I will attend court and face my accusers
with a conscience and conviction to continue to speak up for my
rights, and in so doing, the rights of my fellow citizens.''
	   The Singapore Police Force had earlier issued a press statement
saying the summons had been served on Chee at his home Wednesday
night. ``The investigation revealed that Dr. Chee has committed an
offense of giving a talk in public place without a license under
Section 18 (1) (a) of the Public Entertainment Act,'' said the
police statement.
	   Chee had ignored three warnings from uniformed police who told
him not to speak. He announced to the crowd that if he could, he
would appear again at the same time and place on Jan. 5.
	   The unusual public speech was his only way of disseminating
information, Chee said, because the government had banned his
party's political video, blocked information from being posted on
the Internet about candidates during the last election, refused or
delayed until the last minute issuing permits for public lectures,
and fined him for trying to sell his book on Asian human rights
violations.
	   The People's Action Party has ruled Singapore for 38 years, and
holds 81 of the 84 elected seats in Parliament. 	   
</TEXT>
