<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Sri Lanka </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup champions prepare for defense of title
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PERTH, Australia (AP) _ Defending World Cup-champion Sri Lanka
will look to this month's triangular limited-overs series with
Australia and England to overcome poor form in advance of the 1999
championships.
	   With their aging team in a form slump and on a five-match losing
streak in limited-overs cricket, the tour gives the Sri Lankans a
welcome chance to sharpen up their one-day skills and bring in some
new faces.
	   They lost all four games at their most recent tournament in
Sharjah, including twin losses to Zimbabwe.
	   In the 1998 calendar year, they won 11 and lost 12 of 23 one-day
games to rank fifth in the world.
	   The previous year, they won 19 and lost only seven of 28
matches.
	   Team manager Ranjith Fernando admitted Thursday his side was
struggling for form, but said their focus was now on the 1999 World
Cup, to be held in England.
	   ``We are the World Cup champions and that carries a heavy
burden,'' he said. ``There is a lot of pressure and the
expectations are high, but it is not always possible to maintain
winning momentum in the one-day game.
	   ``Australia is going to be a hard tour, but we've always come
through when the going is tough and we're very confident of
ourselves.''
	   Sri Lankan captain Arjuna Ranatunga echoed Fernando's thoughts
and said the triangular series would help identify the best talent
for the World Cup.
	   ``We have been looking at some of the younger players and we are
building a side now,'' Rantunga said.
	   ``There are a couple of young players on this tour and we have
to get the best possible combination for the World Cup.''
	   Sri Lanka plays Australia A in a day-night match on Sunday in
Perth, and the same teams meet again in Adelaide on Tuesday.
	   The limited-overs tournament begins on Jan. 10 when England
plays Australia in a day-nighter at Brisbane's Gabba, followed by
England against Sri Lanka at the same venue the next night. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
