w1651 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Violence     12-31 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Violence </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian military searches for three kidnapped soldiers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALI KOTARUMALOS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) - Attacks on the Indonesian military
have escalated in a northern province where hundreds of troops
searched Thursday for three kidnapped soldiers.
	   Suspected rebels abducted the soldiers Wednesday in Aceh
province, one day after a mob of villagers armed with machetes
pulled soldiers off a bus and killed seven of them.
	   The armed forces recently ended a decade-long campaign against
separatist guerrillas in Aceh, but many residents remain bitter
about atrocities committed by the military.
	   Violence this week jeopardized Jakarta's efforts to ease
tensions in the Sumatra island province by withdrawing troops and
handing over security affairs to community leaders. The more
conciliatory approach followed the ouster of former authoritarian
President Suharto in May.
	   Several hundred troops have returned to Aceh, at least
temporarily, and military chief Gen. Wiranto warned he will not
tolerate attacks on his forces.
	   Two marines and an army sergeant were being held by an
unidentified group in the village of Blang Panjang, the military
said.
	   The daily Kompas newspaper reported that assailants had seized a
soldier and offered to turn him over to the military. When four
officers arrived, the kidnappers abducted them also but two later
escaped, Kompas said.
	   Blang Panjang lies on the outskirts of the coastal city of
Lhokseumawe, where a mob on Wednesday attacked a police station and
burned two police cars.
	   Some 25 people have been arrested in the killings of seven
off-duty soldiers in the Aceh village of Lhok Nibung. Another 10
soldiers who were forced off the bus managed to escape.
	   Fearing more violence, residents stayed off the streets of
Lhokseumawe on Thursday. A day earlier, mobs stopped vehicles and
asked for identification along a main highway leading out of the
city.
	   Aceh, about 1,750 kilometers (1,100 miles) northwest of Jakarta,
is a staunchly Muslim province where rebels have been fighting for
an Islamic state for decades.
	   The military says 760 people died in fighting since the late
1980s, but human rights groups put the death toll higher. Mass
graves have been uncovered and some women allege they were raped by
soldiers. 	   
</TEXT>
