<SLUG> BC-China-Dissidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police accused of harassing prominent Chinese dissident's wife
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHARLES HUTZLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ The wife of a prominent dissident in China said
Thursday that police have been making harassing phone calls to her
home and have refused to allow visits with her jailed husband.
	   The humiliating treatment given democracy campaigner Xu Wenli
and his wife underscores the uncompromising mood of the ruling
Communist Party in pressing its widest crackdown on dissent in at
least three years.
	   He Xintong said she went to Beijing's Half-step Bridge detention
center Wednesday, but police refused to let her see Xu or leave a
change of clean winter clothes, his first since being arrested Nov.
30.
	   She has met with Xu only once in the past month, immediately
after a Beijing court convicted and sentenced him to 13 years in
prison for subversion on Dec. 21.
	   Xu passed a note to her Monday via his lawyer. In it, he
defiantly labeled his conviction ``political persecution'' and said
he would not appeal.
	   At the meeting with the lawyer, Xu was in handcuffs, a treatment
He said was normally given to convicted murderers. She said other
dissidents held in the detention center have described it as
overcrowded, with inmates being made to sleep on the floor, even in
the harsh cold of winter.
	   Despite Xu's jailing, police have kept He under surveillance,
with officers posted outside her home, she said. She has been
receiving frequent nuisance calls, up to 20 an hour. When she picks
up the receiver no one answers.
	   ``Yesterday I disconnected the phone. As soon as I plugged it
back in the phone calls immediately started again,'' He said.
``This is really senseless.''
	   Xu's 13-year sentence was the longest given a dissident in three
years, a backhanded testament to his reputation as a potent
organizer in the dissident community. He was put on trial for his
leading role in trying to organize an opposition political party.
	   Two other influential figures in the China Democracy Party, Qin
Yongmin and Wang Youcai, were also sentenced at separate trials to
12 and 11 years in prison. All three were charged with the same
crime, inciting the subversion of state power.
	   Two other dissidents active in the party, Shi Wanbao and Liu
Xianbin, have been placed under house arrest in two cities in
southwestern Sichuan province, the Hong Kong-based Information
Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China reported
Thursday.
	   One other dissident was convicted of subversion in November:
writer Ma Zhe got 7 years in southern Guizhou province, apparently
for trying to publish an independent literary journal, the
Information Center said.
	   The Communist Party crackdown has prompted dissidents in China
and in exile to protest and demand the release of the democracy
campaigners.
	   One prominent exile, Wang Xizhe, is now in the fourth day of a
hunger strike outside the United Nations in New York. He was
drinking only water, and his supporters said his health, already
bad from years of imprisonment in China was weakening.
	   Twenty-three writers, actors and other artists and intellectuals
planned to stage a symbolic 24-hour hunger strike on New Year's Day
to press for the release of Xu, Qin, Wang, writer Ma and others. 	   
</TEXT>
