<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-Patriots-Bledsoe Out,0532 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
It's official: Zolak to face Jaguars
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HOWARD ULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FOXBORO, Massachusetts (AP) _ His fractured finger has been
X-rayed repeatedly, encased in a bandage and held together by a pin
that sticks out the top. For at least one more game, though, it
won't be guiding any passes to receivers.
	   The expected became official Wednesday when Drew Bledsoe was
declared out of the New England Patriots' playoff game Sunday at
the Jacksonville Jaguars.
	   ``It is extremely disappointing,'' he said after coach Pete
Carroll announced he wouldn't play. ``You go through a year's worth
of hard work and games with the goal of getting a shot in the
playoffs. When you are not on the field, it's tough to deal with.''
	   For the third straight game, Scott Zolak will be on the field in
his place, hoping to improve on a poor performance in last Sunday's
31-10 loss to the New York Jets that ended the regular season.
	   ``As the weeks progress, I feel more and more comfortable,'' he
said. ``I'm excited about playing in the playoff. Let's get this
thing going.''
	   Zolak, an eight-year veteran, will make his first playoff
appearance. A little more than two weeks ago, he made his first
start in three years in a 24-21 upset win over San Francisco that
clinched a playoff berth.
	   He played well then and welcomes the chance to bounce back from
the Jets' game in which he completed 14-of-31 passes for 127 yards.
	   ``I don't wish that he (Bledsoe) was hurt,'' Zolak said. ``On
the other hand, you don't want to go out on a note like last week.
You want another chance to redeem yourself and prove some people
wrong.''
	   If the Patriots win, they'll play in Denver the following Sunday
and Bledsoe, a three-time Pro Bowl player, could return if his
right index finger has healed sufficiently.
	   ``It'll be something we'll evaluate next week,'' he said.
	   Bledsoe fractured his finger Nov. 23 against Miami when his hand
hit defensive lineman Shane Burton on a follow-through late in the
fourth quarter. But he led the Patriots to last-minute wins in that
game and the following week against Buffalo and directed a 23-9
victory over Pittsburgh.
	   But the following week, two pins put in the finger for
protection shifted and were replaced during the game by a single
pin intended to promote healing. He was ineffective and the
Patriots lost to St. Louis 32-18.
	   Now, nearly three weeks later, that pin is part of the reason he
can't play.
	   If it stays in, it could break if he plays, doing further damage
to the finger that might require major surgery to remove the
pieces, he said. If it comes out so he could play, the healing
process would be set back.
	   Meanwhile, he feels he can help Zolak in practice this week and
in the game Sunday.
	   ``I know Scott real well and I know what he likes to throw and
doesn't like to throw,'' Bledsoe said. ``I also have taken a more
active role with our receiving corps during practice, pointing out
little things that I can see.''
	   On Sunday, it will be up to Zolak to get the ball to those
receivers.
</TEXT>
