<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Bank, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korea to sell Korea First Bank to U.S. financial firms
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES 8th-9th grafs with details.
 &UR; By SANG-HUN CHOE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 
 &UR; AP Photos Planned

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea agreed Thursday to sell
heavily indebted Korea First Bank to an American financial
consortium in a bid to boost foreign confidence in its crisis-hit
economy.
	   The consortium, led by Texas-based investment fund Newbridge
Capital Ltd., outbid HSBC Holdings PLC of Britain to take over 51
percent of Korea First Bank, which is currently owned by the
government.
	   The deal marked the first takeover of a major Korean commercial
bank by foreign investors. Members of the Newbridge consortium
include GE Capital Services, a unit of General Electric of the
United States, and several other investors.
	   ``It will help boost the country's credibility abroad,'' said
Chun Joo-sung, an economist at Seoul's Ewha Woman's University.
``The deal is significant in that it could trigger an influx of
foreign investment in the domestic bank industry.''
	   President Kim Dae-jung's government has insisted on selling
Korea First Bank to foreigners to demonstrate its willingness to
restructure and open the cloistered domestic financial sector to
foreign investors.
	   The government first bought a 94 percent stake in the bank by
investing 1.5 trillion won (dlrs 1.2 billion). It then poured 3.6
trillion won (dlrs 3 billion) to write off half of the bank's bad
loans.
	   The bank also was forced to shed 2,900 workers, or 38 percent of
its total work force, and closed down 74 of its 413 retail branches
across the country this year in a restructuring program aimed at
wooing foreign investors.
	   Lee Hun-jai, head of the Financial Supervisory Commission, said
in a news conference that to help the deal go through, the
government also promised Newbridge that it would take over all
existing non-performing loans and any loans that go bad over the
next year.
	   The government hopes to recoup some of its money at some point
in the future by selling off part of its minority stake when the
bank's rock-bottom share price rebounds.
	   Newbridge will complete the purchase of its stake in Korea First
Bank by May, Lee said. Other details will be worked out later, he
added.
	   When the economy slowed down and companies began collapsing last
year, Korea First and other banks were left with mountains of bad
loans, triggering a sudden loss of international confidence that
led to the country's financial crisis.
	   Bank reform was a key condition of the record dlrs 58 billion
economic bailout package announced by the International Monetary
Fund a year ago.
	   Lee said South Korea will sell another ailing bank owned by the
government, Seoulbank, to foreigners in January.
	   South Korea so far has shut down 16 merchant banks and four
insurance companies and forced five small commercial banks to be
merged with bigger banks. Major commercial banks are discussing
more mergers.
	   Foreign banks are allowed to open retail branches, but the cost
of matching the vast number of branches owned by existing South
Korean banks would be prohibitive. That, say analysts, makes the
takeover of an existing bank especially attractive for overseas
banks.
	   Newbridge is affiliated with Texas Pacific Group, a closely held
U.S. investment firm based in Fort Worth, Texas. 	   
</TEXT>
