<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Satellite </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia launches three global navigation satellites
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's Defense Ministry successfully launched
three global positioning satellites from a space center in the
Central Asian nation of Kazakstan, a news report said Thursday.
	   The three GLONASS satellites blasted off from the Baikonur
cosmodrome atop a Proton booster rocket at 9:36 p.m. Moscow time on
Wednesday night, the Interfax news agency said.
	   GLONASS, short for Global Navigation Satellite System, was
developed by the Russian military to enable ships, planes and
ground troops to pinpoint their position anywhere on earth to
within 15 meters (50 feet).
	   Like the United States' satellite network, called the Global
Positioning System (GPS), the Russian network can be used by
civilians who have the proper equipment. The location devices are
not yet widely available in Russia.
	   GLONASS will eventually consist of 24 satellites, like the US
version. Twenty-one were in orbit following Wednesday's launch.
	   (nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
