<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping,1054 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hostages rest, receive luggage, as bodies of dead examined
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADEN, Yemen (AP) _ Survivors of a bloody rescue operation that
killed four Western kidnap victims tried to cope with their tragedy
Thursday, collecting luggage scattered in their abduction and
recovering at an Aden hotel.
	   Their two-day ordeal at the hands of militant Islamic captors
still haunts them.
	   ``That's my wife's,'' a tearful Laurence Whitehouse, a
54-year-old schoolteacher from Hampshire, England, said in the
hotel's elevator Thursday as a porter carried his and his slain
wife's luggage to his room.
	   Margaret Whitehouse, 52, was among the hostages killed.
	   Whitehouse said his wife tried to help a wounded Australian
hostage, Andrew Colin Thirsk, who later died.
	   ``A kidnapper wanted Margaret to protect him, but she kept
trying to help Andrew. She was kneeling beside him, talking to him
and he was hit again,'' Whitehouse added.
	   ``Then a bullet caught her in the leg ... I tried to move her,
but another kidnapper clung on to me and kept the machine gun dug
into my neck. Then I saw a bullet hit Margaret in the head. She was
dead the instant it hit her. She never stood a chance.
	   ``They wouldn't let me go to her and she just lay there,
bleeding in the dirt,'' Whitehouse told Britain's Press
Association.
	   Tension was visible on another freed hostage, Briton David
Holmes.
	   ``No passports, no cameras, no money, nothing,'' he said in the
hotel lobby, complaining that the luggage retrieved from the battle
scene was missing some items stolen by the kidnappers before their
retreat under army fire.
	   In the nearby Al-Jamhuriya Hospital, the bodies of the four
slain hostages _ three Britons and an Australian _ were examined by
an American Embassy doctor Wednesday night. They were being
prepared to be transported out of the country.
	   Yemeni security officers arrived at the hotel Thursday to
interview the former hostages before the Westerners leave this
southern port for the capital of San`a in the northern mountains
later in the day. The former hostages were expected to fly home on
Friday.
	   Some hostages have disputed the Yemeni government's claim that
security forces opened fire ``after the kidnappers had already
started killing the hostages.'' The soldiers were only trying to
``prevent further killings,'' a government statement said.
	   Yemeni officials said its forces killed three of the kidnappers
and captured three others. They said the kidnappers belonged to
Islamic Jihad, a group of about 200 in south Yemen.
	   They had seized the hostages to demand the release of two of
their leaders and to protest the recent U.S. and British airstrikes
against Iraq, officials said. The leaders had been seized in a
crackdown on Islamic vigilantes.
	   Two wounded hostages _ an American woman, who was not
identified, with a wound to the pelvis, and a British woman who was
shot in the shoulder _ remain in the Aden hospital. Hospital
officials and British diplomats said the victims did not wish to be
interviewed.
	   British diplomat David Pearce said Wednesday that the wounded
Briton, Claire Marston, is ``in a very bad way.'' She was told that
her husband, Peter Rowe, was among the dead.
	   The British Foreign Office has confirmed three Britons were
slain _ Ruth Williamson, 34, Mrs. Whitehouse, and Rowe, a
60-year-old math lecturer from Durham University. The fourth person
killed was Thirsk, 35, of Sydney.
	   In an account Wednesday, Eric Firkins, 55, of Croydon, England,
said the abductors armed with assault rifles and grenade launchers
were leading the hostages into the mountains to a hideout. ``Then
we heard the gunfire,'' he said.
	   ``The army approached us and the nearer they got, the more tense
the situation in our group became,'' said another hostage, Brian
Smith, a 52-year-old postal worker from Peterborough, England.
	   He said the shooting then started in earnest with bullets
whizzing over their heads and shells crashing against surrounding
mountains or exploding in the air.
	   The former hostages said they were forced to stand with their
hands in the air to shield the gunmen. When the hostages staggered
back, two of them were shot dead by their captors as revenge, they
said.
	   Smith and Firkins were interviewed at their hotel in Aden, about
a three-hour drive from the town of Mawdiyah where the hostages
were held captive after being seized Monday. Mawdiyah is 175 miles
(280 kilometers) south of San`a.
	   Firkins, a chemistry professor, said the kidnappers had divided
the hostages _ 12 Britons, two Americans and two Australians _ into
two groups of 11 and five. He and Smith were in the larger group
and didn't know how the others came under attack.
	   Holmes, among the group of five hostages, also said the hostages
were used as human shields by the kidnappers.
	   ``We were standing in front of the army during the battle,'' he
said Thursday.
	   He also said that kidnappers retreating under army fire tried to
execute hostages but ``we tackled them.''
	   He could not tell how the two hostages in his group were killed.
	   ``How can a gun differentiate,'' he said.
	   This was the first time Islamic extremists had abducted
foreigners.
	   In the past, tribesmen have kidnapped scores of foreigners to
win economic concessions from the government but have usually freed
the hostages safely. On Wednesday, four Germans kidnapped by Yemeni
tribesmen on Dec. 7 were set free unharmed.
	   The Yemeni government statement said this time the kidnappers
had ``purely political motives. ... The kidnappers were
terrorists.''
	   The Yemeni Islamic Jihad group has loose ties to radical Muslim
groups elsewhere in the Arab world. The common aim of these groups
is to set up theocratic rule in their countries, and many of their
leaders fought against the Russian occupation of Afghanistan in the
1980s.
	   Brig. Mohammad Saleh al-Turaiq, the chief of security in Aden
province, said Wednesday that Yemen's resolve in dealing with the
hostage-taking should serve as a warning to other kidnap groups.
	   ``Don't they dare repeat it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
