</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Property Slump </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan moves to revive sagging property market
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNIE HUANG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Hoping to prevent the slump in Taiwan's
property market from triggering financial turmoil and further
slowing the economy, the Cabinet announced a stimulus package
Thursday to encourage more people to buy homes.
	   Mortgages totaling up to 150 billion Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs
4.6 billion) will be provided at a government-subsidized rate of
5.95 percent, compared to the current commercial rate of between 7
percent and 8 percent.
	   The preferential 20-year loans will be available for one year
beginning Friday, while new public housing projects will be
suspended for two years to reduce an oversupply of houses and
apartments, according to a government statement.
	   Critics say the stimulus plan will enable property companies to
prop up prices _ at taxpayer expense _ in a market that became
glutted when developers greedily overbuilt. Without the government
plan, the developers would have to cut housing prices further.
	   An economic slowdown fueled by Asia's financial crisis has
weakened Taiwan's property market, which now has 600,000 to 800,000
empty housing units scattered across the island.
	   The government bailout was launched after several construction
companies came to the brink of bankruptcy, prompting banks to
tighten credit as investors dumped construction shares.
	   In announcing the recovery plan, Premier Vincent Siew tried to
appease critics of the proposal.
	   ``We take these measures not to help the real estate developers
but to keep our economic and financial stability,'' Siew said,
noting the empty housing units have idled assets that cost some 1.5
trillion Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs 46 billion.)
	   ``These are measures we must take whether you like it or not,''
he said.
	   Finance Minister Paul Chiu said the housing loan subsidies would
cost the government an estimated 1.2 billion Taiwan dollars (U.S.
dlrs 37 million) a year, but will be recovered through increased
tax revenues brought in by a hoped for recovery in the property
market.
	   Despite a 7-year slump, industry sources say housing prices have
only dropped by an average of 20 percent since the boom in the late
1980s.
	   While prices have largely remained out of reach of many
potential home buyers, others complain that many large-scale
housing projects were ill-devised or built in remote areas.
	   Some economists said the government measures could help prevent
a possible collapse of property prices, which could cause a
financial crisis because about 40 percent of bank loans are
collateralized with real estate.
	   But others remain skeptical about the government scheme.
	   ``The measures will mitigate the problems, but not solve them,''
said Kuo Wen-jeng, an economist at the Chunghua Institute of
Economic Research, a private think tank.
	   ``The real estate market still needs some structural
adjustments,'' he said. ``Over the long term you need more
reasonable prices. The houses are still overpriced, and most people
with an average salary still won't buy.'' 	   
</TEXT>
