r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-Austra     12-31 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Australia-England-Giles </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Unheralded spinner could be in England side
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ England has summoned unheralded leftarm
spinner Ashley Giles and could name him to play in Saturday's fifth
Ashes test against Australia at the Sydney Cricket Ground.
	   Giles, who has bowled spin for only five years, flew into
Australia two days ago with England's limited-overs contingent but
England selectors believe his variation in spinning the ball away
from Australia's righthanders will be crucial on a turning pitch.
	   The visitors' two other slow-bowling options, Peter Such and
Robert Croft, are offspinners.
	   Giles bowled nine overs, taking 1-29, in England's one-day
victory against a Queensland country side in Brisbane on Wednesday.
	   That was his first outing since September, when he played his
last four-day game.
	   The leftarmer's main claim to fame is taking the sole wicket by
an England spinner in the five-match South African series this year
_ in his one and only test so far.
	   Giles started his first-class career with Surrey as a seamer
before taking up spin when crossing to Warwickshire four seasons
ago.
	   He said he would not be daunted by the occasion if selected for
the showdown to decide the Ashes series.
	   Australia leads 2-1 entering the final test.
	   ``Everyone will be nervous, it's a big test for England,'' Giles
said Thursday. ``Everyone is going to have a few butterflies but
you have got to try and control that and get on with the job.''
	   England captain Alec Stewart said Giles faced a difficult task
if selected.
	   ``If he does play, it will be asking a lot,'' Stewart said.
``But we feel this fellow is up to it.'' (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
