w1688 &Cx1f; wstm-
u I &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-US-Congress     12-31 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-US-Congress </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China angry about U.S. Congress allegations
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China on Thursday called a United States Congress
report that found Beijing acquired American military technology
which harmed U.S. national security ``groundless and
irresponsible.''
	   A House of Representatives committee unanimously approved a
report Wednesday that concluded Beijing aggressively sought U.S.
technology, including sensitive military secrets, and bought or
stole items that hurt national security.
	   ``The allegation is groundless and irresponsible and we express
our strong resentment over this,'' Zhu Bangzao, a spokesman for
China's Foreign Ministry, said in response to the report's claims.
	   Normal trade and technology exchanges are ``in the interest of
both sides,'' he said.
	   Beijing has long pushed Washington to lift a ban on sales of
high technology, saying high-tech exports could help redress a
trade imbalance, estimated at dlrs 60 billion in China's favor in
1998.
	   China hopes ``the U.S. can proceed from the overall development
of bilateral relations and take actual deeds to remove obstacles to
the normal development of economic and trade relations between the
two countries and not to the contrary,'' Zhu said.
	   Despite China's pique over the House report, Zhu said U.S. and
Chinese officials would meet next month in Washington to discuss
human rights, an issue that has long been an irritant in China-U.S.
ties.
	   The meeting comes in the midst of the ruling Communist Party's
widest crackdown on dissent in at least three years. In the past
two weeks, four dissidents accused of endangering state security
have been given lengthy jail terms; another three, including two
U.S.-based activists, have been sent to labor camps.
	   Zhu indicated, however, that China was in no mood to suffer
criticism of its crackdown at the upcoming meeting.
	   He said the sentenced dissidents were guilty of ``subversive
activities'' and that China hoped its view that countries should
not interfere in each others affairs would be respected.
	   ``We have all along stood for dialogue and cooperation and
opposed confrontation'' over human rights, he said. ``To revert to
the road of confrontation is against the trend of history.''
	   Three dissidents, Xu Wenli, Qin Yongmin and Wang Youcai, were
sentenced to 13, 12 and 11 years respectively for trying to set up
an opposition party to challenge Communist Party rule.
	   A labor activist, Zhang Shanguang, also was sentenced to 10
years imprisonment for telling U.S. government-funded Radio Free
Asia about farmers' protests.
	   The U.S. Embassy in Beijing has expressed deep disappointment
over what it said were ``extremely harsh sentences.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-China-US-Congress; CT:I; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
