<HEADER>
w1697 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-ChineseDisside     12-31 0246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Chinese Dissident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese dissident meets Taiwanese opposition leaders
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Exiled Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng on
Thursday praised former Taiwanese dissidents for launching a
zealous campaign that helped transform the island into a democracy.
	   At a meeting with Lin Yih-hsiung, leader of the opposition
Democratic Progressive Party, Wei said China's dissidents ``are
still treading on a tough road'' after two decades of championing
democracy.
	   ``Maybe it is because China is a big country,'' Wei said. ``It
is hard to push an elephant.''
	   Like mainland China, Taiwan saw the emergence of a dissident
movement two decades ago, but Taiwan has now become a full-blown
democracy, Wei said.
	   Lin agreed to keep supporting exiled Chinese dissidents.
	   ``After all, we are after the same goals,'' Lin said.
	   Wei was released last year from a Chinese prison where he spent
much of the last 18 years after his arrest for leading the
Democracy Wall movement, in which activists put up posters calling
for democracy.
	   Arriving in Taiwan last week for his first-ever visit, he has
met with President Lee Teng-hui and Premier Vincent Siew. He also
took time out to visit a former jail for political prisoners on
Green Island.
	   Wei was released earlier Thursday from a hospital where he had
stayed for two days for complications from a cold. Doctors urged
Wei, a chain smoker, to cut back on cigarettes. 	   
