<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,1471 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; BARBADOS: Embassy suspects Americans were beaten while in police
custody &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) _ Two Americans hospitalized with
serious injuries appear to have suffered them while in police
custody, the U.S. Embassy in Barbados says.
	   The men, both of Vega Baja, Puerto Rico, claim Barbadian police
beat them with pipes and sticks.
	   The United States has filed an official protest with the
island's government, embassy spokeswoman Jennifer Clark said
Wednesday.
	   She said police never notified U.S. officials that the men,
Antonio Mendoza, 24, and Felipe Collazo Teron, 45, had been
detained. Doctors called the embassy after police brought the two
men to Queen Elizabeth Hospital in critical condition on Dec. 20.
	   ``The consular section has statements from others who say they
in were good shape when they were picked up by police,'' Clark
said.
	   Officials at the Barbadian foreign ministry received the U.S.
complaint Wednesday but had no immediate comment, ministry
spokeswoman Gayle Francis-Vaughn said.
	   Mendoza and Collazo were in Barbados to help assemble the Alana
Coney Island, a traveling carnival, when police detained them and
other carnival workers on Dec. 18 for questioning in the Dec. 11
burglary of an automatic bank machine. Thieves had bored a hole
into the money compartment through the wall of an adjoining
laundromat.
	   Police charged none of the carnival workers in the burglary,
though one man was sentenced to three months in jail for possession
of a marijuana cigarette.
 &UR; GUYANA: Government won't complain to UN about alleged jet violation
_ yet
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Guyana says it is waiting for an
explanation from Venezuela before complaining to United Nations
supervisors about an alleged overflight by warplanes along a
disputed border.
	   The United Nations is overseeing efforts to resolve a
100-year-old border dispute in that area. Guyanese Foreign Minister
Clement Rohee said Wednesday he wants to talk to Venezuelan
officials about the alleged violation on Dec. 24 before complaining
to the international body.
	   ``We are not on a war footing and we would prefer always to work
through the diplomatic channels,'' Rohee said. ``I don't think we
need to rush to the United Nations with very limited information.''
	   The Guyanese army reported last week that two military jets flew
over northwestern Guyana without permission.
	   Venezuela has not responded to the charges. On Wednesday,
officials at the Venezuelan foreign affairs department left work
early because of the New Year's holiday and could not be reached
for comment.
	   Venezuela claims two-thirds of Guyana, a country rich in timber,
minerals, gold and oil. Guyana also has a running territorial
dispute with Suriname, its neighbor to the east.
	   Rohee said the alleged overflight ``warrants concern.''
	   ``Any incursion of one's airspace is a very serious issue both
from a foreign affairs and a national security point of view,'' he
said. ``It's not something that can be dismissed easily.''
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Fourth man arrested in alleged corruption scheme
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Prosecutors have charged a fourth
man in an alleged fraud scheme in Puerto Rico following Hurricane
Georges.
	   Federal prosecutors claim Marcos Gonzalez Reyes worked with
another contractor, Jose Orlando Figueroa, to inflate reports of
debris left by the hurricane.
	   The fraudulent reports were submitted the Federal Emergency
Management Agency in order to get more disaster funds for the city
of Toa Alta, prosecutors say. They announced the charges Wednesday.
	   They also allege he prepared blank documents and work reports
for a city worker to fill out and submit to the agency.
	   Gonzalez Reyes faces a maximum of 10 years in jail, a dlrs
250,000 fine and three years of probation on a charge of conspiring
to defraud the United States.
	   Figueroa and Toa Alta Mayor Angel Rodriguez were charged in
November with exaggerating hurricane damage and demanding dlrs 2.5
million in bribes from a Mississippi-based company, JESCO, in
exchange for a contract to collect debris.
	   Rodriguez and Figueroa have pleaded innocent to conspiracy,
extortion and bribery indictments.
	   Another contractor, Luis A. Rodriguez Sierra, was charged Dec.
15 with inflating damage estimates.
 &UR; CUBA: Government honors guerrillas who fought with Che Guevara
	   SANTA CLARA, Cuba (AP) _ The remains of 10 guerrilla fighters
who fell alongside Ernesto ``Che'' Guevara in Bolivia, including
the German woman known as Tania, have been buried with military
honors.
	   Their bodies were uncovered over the past year in Bolivia, about
three decades after they died in a failed attempt to spread an
armed Marxist revolution across the Americas _ an effort that even
Cuba today has renounced. They were interred Wednesday in central
Santa Clara.
	   But Comandante Ramiro Valdez, a former aide to Guevara, insisted
that they remained an example for those struggling against ``the
Yankee enemy'' and U.S. domination of the hemisphere.
	   ``Epochs may change. Conditions and methods also change,'' he
said, addressing the memorial service beneath a towering statue of
Guevara. ``(But) the objectives for which they battled continue to
be an objective and an aspiration for the Latin American people.''
	   ``U.S. imperialism today aspires with more force than ever,'' he
declared, saying that caused the backwardness and division of Latin
America and ensured that ``the market with its blind laws dictates
the economy and life of each country.''
	   The ceremony coincided with the 40th anniversary of Guevara's
greatest military triumph, the capture of Santa Clara, which sealed
the downfall of dictator Fulgencio Bastista and the triumph of
Fidel Castro's guerrilla forces on Jan. 1, 1959.
 &UR; GRENADA: Newspaper accuses government of corruption
	   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) _ A local newspaper is accusing
Grenada's government of corruption, saying an audit shows kickbacks
and conflicts of interest in public construction projects.
	   In this week's edition, the independent Grenada Today claims the
government gave contracts to allies of Prime Minister Keith
Mitchell and that one senator is renting a house to contractors
working on government projects at a hugely inflated price.
	   It also accuses the Carnival and Cultural Development Committee
of arranging kickbacks on contracts.
	   Prime Minister Keith Mitchell has denied all of the accusations.
	   ``The NNP and its agents have turned out to be the most corrupt
government to hold the reigns of power in Grenada since the return
of democratic government in 1984,'' the newspaper said.
	   An audit by KPMG Peat Marwick showed overspending and violations
of public bid procedures, but did not touch upon questions of
wrongdoing.
	   Grenada Today also repeated charges that Mitchell's governing
New National Party is trying to buy votes with money and gifts as
it gears up for Jan. 18 elections prompted by the defection of two
of the party's Cabinet ministers.
	   One of the defectors, Foreign Minister Raphael Fletcher, claimed
the party was ``handing out money like confetti'' in return for
votes. He and former Health Minister Grace Duncan said they were
concerned that the audit's findings indicated corruption in the
awarding of contracts.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Hess to install emissions-cleaning equipment at
refinery
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Amerada Hess's Puerto Rican
refinery will install anti-pollution equipment as part of a deal
with federal regulators over gasoline tests, the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency says.
	   The agency said the New York-based company will install cleaning
equipment over the next six months that should remove some 185 tons
of emissions annually at its Peerless Oil Corp. refinery in
southern Guayanilla.
	   In return, the company will be temporarily exempted from federal
guidelines about the cleanliness of its gasoline sold in Puerto
Rico, the agency said Wednesday.
	   The agency said it decided to allow the exemption because the
tests are based on cold wintertime conditions, when gasoline
creates more pollution as it burns.
	   ``It doesn't make sense to make Hess use a method of calculating
compliance with our regulation that is based on conditions that
never occur in Puerto Rico,'' EPA regional administrator Jeanne Fox
said in a written statement.
	   Without the pact, Hess would have had to begin refining gasoline
to the winter limits on Friday.
</TEXT>
