<SLUG> BC-Israel-US Embassy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0169 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. Embassy closed unexpectedly after threat
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPGRADES attribution throughout, UPDATES with radio stations
saying threats were aimed at embassy staff, ADDS color; ADDS
byline &QL; 
 &UR; By DANNY BEN-TAL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ The U.S. ambassador closed the U.S.
Embassy in Tel Aviv on Thursday after receiving ``credible and
specific threats,'' a U.S. official said.
	   The official, U.S. Consulate spokesman Anne Casper, would not
elaborate, but Israeli radio stations said the threats were
directed at embassy staff.
	   Outside the embassy, Israeli border police officers were seen
talking to U.S. security officials and taking notes.
	   U.S. Ambassador Ned Walker ordered the embassy closed after
receiving the threats, Casper said. U.S. officials notified the
appropriate Israeli authorities, she said.
	   Tel Aviv police spokesman Nitza Friedman said ``police are doing
what they have to do.''
</TEXT>
