w1758 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-USEmbassy 2ndLd-Writethru   12-31 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-US Embassy, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. Embassy closed unexpectedly after threat
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series, RESTORES time element in the lead,
UPDATES with embassy spokesman saying embassy building was not
searched, background &QL; 
 &UR; By DANNY BEN-TAL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ The U.S. ambassador closed the U.S.
Embassy in Tel Aviv on Thursday after receiving ``credible''
threats, an embassy spokesman said.
	   The spokesman, Larry Schwartz, would not elaborate, but an
Israeli security source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the threats were aimed at the embassy staff. Israel radio said the
life of U.S. Ambassador Ned Walker was threatened.
	   Schwartz said the embassy was not searched, apparently ruling
out a possible bomb threat.
	   He said the ``direct and credible'' threat was received
Wednesday evening and that Walker decided to shut down the embassy
and informed staff not to report to work Thursday.
	   Schwartz said he did not know how long the embassy would be
closed. On Friday, New Year's Day, the embassy would be closed
anyhow, followed by the weekend.
	   On Thursday, Israeli border police officers were seen talking to
U.S. security officials and taking notes. An Israeli border police
jeep was parked outside the building.
	   Tel Aviv police spokesman Nitza Friedman said ``police are doing
what they have to do.''
	   U.S. diplomatic missions have been on heightened security alert
since the twin bombings of the U.S. embassies in Nairobi and Dar es
Salaam on Aug. 7. The attacks killed 224 people.
	   In retaliation, the United States bombed targets in Sudan and
Afghanistan that had links to Osama Bin Laden, a Saudi millionaire
and the alleged mastermind of the embassy bombings.
	   In the Middle East, there has been growing resentment against
the United States following the attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan
and the U.S. bombing of Iraq earlier this month.
 &UR; kl	   
</TEXT>
