w1774 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Deficit     12-31 0247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Deficit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong's budget deficit gets smaller
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ The collection of capital gains taxes in
November lowered Hong Kong's budget deficit to 35.56 billion Hong
Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 4.36 billion) for the first eight months of
the fiscal year, the government said Thursday.
	   The deficit had stood at 50.16 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S.
dlrs 6.43 billion) at the end of October.
	   The Hong Kong government said it expects the deficit to keep
shrinking as more taxes are collected before the fiscal year ends
on March 31 _ but it was unclear whether the budget imbalance can
fall far enough to meet the government's target.
	   Officials are hoping to limit the full-year deficit to 21
billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 2.69 billion).
	   A statement said expenditure in the first eight months of the
fiscal year came to 148.07 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
18.9 billion), while revenue totaled 112.51 billion Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 14.42 billion).
	   Hong Kong's fiscal reserves were 430.29 billion Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 55.17 billion), a decrease of 27.26 billion Hong
Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 3.49 billion) since the end of March.
	   In the previous fiscal year, Hong Kong had an 80.9 billion Hong
Kong dollar (dlrs 10.37 billion) surplus. The territory is running
a deficit this year because of tax breaks and increased spending on
programs intended to lift the economy out of recession.
</TEXT>
