<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Slain Journalist </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Suspect indicted in killing of Turkish journalist
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Over five years after the killing of an
investigative journalist investigating ties between the state and
the underworld, the prosecutor's office on Thursday announced it
has indicted its first suspect in the case.
	   Abdullah Argun Cetin was indicted as an accomplice in the
killing of Ugur Mumcu.
	   Mumcu was investigating suspected links between the drug
underworld, right-wing terrorists and the government when bomb
under his car went off on Jan. 24, 1993.
	   Prosecutor Hamza Keles is asking for the death penalty.
	   The indictment says that Cetin has links to Mahmut Yildirim, who
worked for the state assassinating people seen as security threats.
It also says Cetin was trained in Azerbaijan using the explosive
C-4, which was in the bomb that killed Mumcu.
	   Police arrested Cetin last month after getting a tip that he was
planning the slayings of a new series of targets, including another
prominent journalist.
	   A car crash two years ago confirmed for the first time what many
Turks long suspected _ that state officials had close ties to
mobsters. A fugitive terrorist, a police chief and a deputy were
all riding in the same car.
	   The wreck set off a chain reaction of investigations and
allegations which led to the sacking of several policemen, the
trial of two deputies, including a former interior minister, and
the collapse of the government of Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz last
month.
	   (sh-cph)
</TEXT>
