<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Missing Ship </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China says missing Japanese ship found
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China confirmed Thursday that a Japanese cargo
vessel that went missing in September and which was thought to have
been hijacked has been found in a Chinese port.
	   Chinese maritime authorities have impounded the 2,600-ton Tenyu
at the request of its owner, said Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao.
	   In announcing the ship's discovery in an east China port, Zhu
denounced piracy and robbery as ``inhuman atrocities'' and promised
China's continued cooperation in efforts to fight it.
	   ``The Chinese government has all along firmly and strongly
condemned any act of piracy and robbery,'' he said.
	   Earlier, a port official had expressed doubt that the vessel in
question was the missing Tenyu, owned by Japanese shipping company
Masumoto Kisen.
	   The Tenyu disappeared Sept. 27 after leaving an Indonesian port
with a cargo of aluminum worth about 500 million yen (dlrs 4.3
million).
	   Zhu said the ship was found in Zhangjiagang port in Jiangsu
province, near Shanghai, bearing a new name and a Honduran flag.
	   ``Concerted efforts'' by Chinese maritime officials determined
that the vessel ``is in fact the missing ship MD Tenyu,'' Zhu said.
``The case is under investigation.''
	   Zhu made no mention, however, of the ship's crew.
	   South Korean maritime police said the Tenyu had been piloted by
a South Korean skipper, Shin Young-ju, and chief engineer, Park
Ha-joon, and was manned by a crew of 12 Chinese sailors.
	   In April, Chinese authorities discovered another hijacked
vessel, the Malaysian-registered Petro Ranger, on China's Hainan
Island, and detained 12 Indonesians.
	   The circumstances of that hijacking provoked a controversy, with
Chinese authorities saying the ship actually was involved in
smuggling while the Malaysian government contended the vessel had
been hijacked by Indonesians. 	   
</TEXT>
