<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Immigrants-Sinking </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At least two dead after boat carrying illegal immigrants sinks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ At least two people drowned and another
two were reportedly missing Thursday when a wooden boat carrying
illegal immigrants sank in the Aegean, rescue officials said.
	   Nearby ships and port authority vessels managed to rescue two
Greeks and 21 Pakistani, Indian and Iraqi men who had been on board
the 17-meter (56-foot), Italian-flagged Mustang, the merchant
ministry said.
	   They also recovered two bodies off the island of Nissiros, about
320 kilometers (200 miles) southeast of Athens. The nationalities
of the dead were not immediately clear.
	   A helicopter and coast guard vessels searched for other
survivors or casualties. Authorities were unsure how many people
were originally on board.
	   According to media reports, at least two men _ one Greek and one
Yugoslav _ were reported missing.
	   One Iraqi survivor said he saw at least five people drown, but
his account could not be independently confirmed, the ministry
said.
	   The Mustang began to take on water and sank at around 5:30 a.m.
(0330 GMT) seven miles west of Nissiros, located near the Turkish
coast, the ministry added.
	   The 23 people rescued were to be taken to the nearby island of
Kos, the ministry said.
	   Thousands of illegal immigrants, mostly Iraqi Kurds, attempt
each year to cross from the Turkish coast to nearby Greek islands.
Many are arrested and deported, but others apply for asylum in
Greece and are taken to refugee camps while their applications are
processed.
	   Hundreds find work clandestinely in Greece or move on to Italy
to make their way to other European countries.
	   (eb-bm) 	   
</TEXT>
