</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Indonesian Fugitive </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China draws blank on missing Indonesian fugitive
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Chinese authorities said Friday they have so far
failed to locate a missing Indonesian businessman who is said to be
running a brewery in China after having escaped from jail in 1996.
	   The Indonesian government asked its embassy in Beijing to check
the validity of a report that Eddy Tansil, who was sentenced to 20
years in prison in one of Indonesia's biggest financial scandals,
was successfully operating a business in China.
	   Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said Indonesia
had asked ``relevant countries and regions, including China'' for
assistance in locating Tansil.
	   ``China has attached great importance to this. However, so far,
the whereabouts of Eddy Tansil has not been found,'' Zhu said.
	   Tansil was convicted in 1994 of defrauding the government of
dlrs 430 million in a case that became a symbol of official
corruption in Indonesia. After serving two years of his sentence,
Tansil escaped from jail and eluded a nationwide manhunt.
	   An Indonesian watchdog group, Gempita, said this week that
Tansil owned a brewery in the southeastern Chinese province of
Fujian. Gempita is the acronym in the Indonesian language for
Movement of Concerned Citizens to Save State Assets.
	   Zhu said Indonesia could ask for Chinese help in investigating
any assets Tansil may have in China. ``China will give positive
consideration to the request,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
