w1800 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-GovernmentBusin     12-31 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Government Business </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese government departments and Communist Party give up
</HEADLINE>
businesses

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Following moves to divest the Chinese military of
its vast corporate holdings, the ruling Communist Party and
government departments are also severing their business ties, the
state-run Xinhua News Agency reported Thursday.
	   Departments of the central government and the Communist Party
have completed the process of divestiture ahead of a Jan. 1
deadline and will no longer run the array of businesses they once
owned and managed, Xinhua said.
	   During the transition, businesses were told to maintain normal
operations and ensure the stability of their work forces.
Profitable enterprises are to be kept open, while loss-makers will
be suspended or shut down, the report said.
	   China's central and local government still keeps tight links to
business through thousands of state-owned enterprises. But the
order pulls officials out of positions of corporate management and
eliminated direct government ownership stakes.
	   Chinese leaders have criticized officials' direct commercial
ties for fostering unfair competition and corrupt business
practices. The People's Liberation Army formally gave up its
business holdings earlier this year.
	   In the days of central planning, Chinese state enterprises not
only answered to government departments but were owned by them.
	   The government is trying to reform such companies, many of which
are unprofitable, to enable them to adjust better to market
competition. 	   
</TEXT>
