<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Most Russians don't expect to be any better off in 1999
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: CORRECTS day in 1st graf.

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Seven out of ten Russian don't expect their lives
to improve in 1999, despite the government's pledge to resurrect
the economy after a devastating financial crisis, according to a
poll released Thursday.
	   Eighteen percent of the 6,000 people surveyed by the Institute
of Parliamentary Sociology said they expected some improvement in
their lives, while 12 percent couldn't predict, the Interfax news
agency reported.
	   But 70 percent of those polled across Russia said their living
situation wouldn't get better in the upcoming year.
	   The report gave no margin of error for the poll.
	   Respondents said the were most likely to worry about wage
arrears and low salaries in 1999. They were also afraid that health
care and other social services would fall further into neglect.
	   Since the breakup of the Soviet Union, the government has had
trouble paying wages and pensions on time. The education and health
care systems have also been extremely hard hit.
	   These problems have been exacerbated by the country's latest
economic crisis, which hit in August.
	   (nw/gm)	   
</TEXT>
