<SLUG> BC-Chechnya-Parliament </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechnya's parliament, Islamic court agree to settle dispute
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Chechnya's parliament and its top Islamic court
have agreed to settle a dispute that arose last week when the court
suspended the legislature and accused it of failing to adhere to
Muslim practices, a report said Thursday.
	   The head of the Islamic court Bekhan Nasukhanov and parliament
chairman Ruslan Alikhadzhiyev met Wednesday evening and agreed to
negotiate a solution, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   Representatives of the clergy will work with legislators to make
sure that laws are in accordance with Shariah, or Islamic law, the
report said.
	   Chechnya, a mostly Muslim region in southern Russia, has been
running its own affairs since Russian troops left at the end of a
1994-6 war.
	   Chechnya's leadership instituted Islamic courts soon after the
war ended, but Muslim clerics say that many aspects of the
political and legal system still need to be changed.
	   The Supreme Shariah Court on Dec. 24 declared that parliament's
activities should be suspended, but the legislators objected.
	   Chechnya's leaders, including President Aslan Maskhadov, have
been unable to restore law and order following the war. Hundreds of
people have been kidnapped in recent years and armed gangs roam the
country.
	   (gm/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
