<SLUG> BC-France-Arc de Triomphe </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tourists return to Arc de Triomphe as five-day strike ends
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The Arc de Triomphe re-opened to the public on
Thursday after striking workers reached a deal with management over
wage demands and the hiring of more staff, union officials said.
	   The stone arch at the head of the Avenue des Champs-Elysees, one
of the world's most famous monuments to military glory, had been
closed since Saturday.
	   Workers said they needed better resources to handle increasingly
large crowds drawn to the Arc's splendid rooftop view: a panorama
of the Right Bank's skyline and the 12 tree-lined avenues
stretching out like spokes of a wheel.
	   Union officials said management had agreed to create five new
posts. No details were available about the salary increases.
	   Some 50 meters (about 150 feet) high and 45 meters (about 135
feet) wide, the Arc attracts about 1.4 million visitors a year.
	   Besides the rooftop view, a spacious indoor hall houses
user-friendly exhibits on French military history.
	   Recently, strikes also have hit the Orsay, Louvre and Grand
Palais museums, with employees making similar demands for more
staff. Workers also went on strike at the Eiffel Tower.
	   (parf-ip-cb)
</TEXT>
