<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-2006 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seven candidates compete for World Cup 2006
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ Germany, England, Brazil, South
Africa, Morocco, Egypt and Ghana are the official candidates to
host the 2006 World Cup finals.
	   The seven countries all notified FIFA in advance of the Thursday
night deadline of their intent to stage soccer's four-yearly
showcase. They now have until the end of July to submit their full
bid documents.
	   FIFA's 24-member executive committee will decide in March 2000.
	   FIFA President Sepp Blatter has repeatedly said the soccer
authority has a responsibility to stage the tournament in Africa,
which has never hosted the finals.
	   Despite its high crime rate, South Africa is widely considered
the front-runner. It hosted the 1995 rugby union World Cup, the
1996 African Nations Cup and the 1998 athletics World Cup.
	   Morocco lost out to France for the staging of this year's
finals.
	   The case of both Germany and England has been weakened by the
fact that they are from the same continent. The 2002 finals are
being split between Japan and South Korea _ but FIFA insists that
co-hosting will be a one-time exception.
 &UR; (cn)
</TEXT>
