w1838 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-NewYear     12-31 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-New Year </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Muslim rebels warn forces not to fire weapons to celebrate New
</HEADLINE>
Year &QL; 
 &UR; By CLARO CORTES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Muslim rebels in the Philippines on
Thursday joined a government effort to bring down the number of
people hurt during New Year's revelry by ordering their forces not
to fire guns to celebrate the start of 1999.
	   Ghazali Jaafar, deputy chairman of the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front, said the movement's fighters have been warned they will be
punished for firing their weapons to commemorate the new year.
	   ``For every bullet fired, the penalty would be equivalent to
planting at least 20 banana plants,'' Jaafar said.
	   In the MILF's main guerrilla camp, Jaafar said warnings against
firing guns outside of combat have been posted on the walls of
houses.
	   On Monday, President Joseph Estrada urged soldiers, policemen
and civilians to refrain from firing weapons. He said soldiers and
policemen will be dismissed from the service if caught, while
civilians will face criminal charges and confiscation of their
guns.
	   Manila area police chief Reynaldo Wycoco said policemen have
been ordered to clean their weapons before the new year. The guns
will be inspected again in early 1999 to determine if they were
fired.
	   ``The president's order is clear,'' Wycoco said. ``They have
nothing to gain if they violate it, but they will lose their jobs
or even get hurt if they violate it.''
	   Perhaps no nation greets the new year with more noise than the
Philippines. The fireworks tradition comes from China, but has been
elevated to new flamboyant heights by Filipinos. Many believe
firecrackers scare away bad luck and bring good fortune.
	   Television stations have joined the move to prevent injuries by
cautioning Filipinos against firing weapons during New Year's
celebrations. They have been broadcasting footage of people maimed
by gun- and fireworks-related accidents in previous years.
	   ``So far, so good,'' said Concepcion Gahol of the Department of
Health's fireworks monitoring office. She said that from Dec. 21 to
Dec. 30, 187 people have been reported wounded by firecrackers and
10 others by stray bullets. There were no deaths reported, she
added.
	   Gahol said the figure is likely to increase beginning at
midnight Thursday when the country rings in the new year.
	   The number of victims has fallen in recent years as prevention
efforts have been stepped up. During the same period last year, one
person was reported killed and 189 others were injured by
firecrackers.
	   In 1996, at least 11 people were killed during New Year's
revelry, including six hit by stray bullets, and 700 others were
injured. In 1995, more than a dozen people were killed and about
5,000 were reported hurt. 	   
