<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-NBA Lockout, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0833 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Players work on ``final'' offer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with New York Post report &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRIS SHERIDAN &QC; 
 &UR; AP Basketball Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The union for locked-out NBA players spent
Thursday finalizing its ``final'' offer and wondering whether
arbitrator John Feerick might hear another case.
	   With only eight days left before commissioner David Stern's
deadline for saving the season, the union was expected to make a
counteroffer to the owners either Thursday or Friday.
	   Union director Billy Hunter has asked to present the offer to
the owners' negotiating committee, but that may not be logistically
possible.
	   ``Billy will decide the best way to do this,'' said Jeffrey
Kessler, lead outside counsel for the union.
	   Kessler was on the phone Wednesday night trying to locate
Feerick in the hope that the arbitrator might convene an expedited
hearing in the case of Nick Van Exel and two other players who are
seeking to play in Europe for the rest of the season _ even if the
lockout ends.
	   A federal court judge in Houston rejected an injunction sought
by Van Exel, Marcus Camby and Reggie Slater for unconditional
letters of clearance from the NBA and USA Basketball but told the
plaintiffs they could submit their dispute to an arbitrator.
	   Agent James Bryant said he would do so.
	   The union then tried to contact Feerick, dean of Fordham
University law school, to set up an expedited hearing Thursday or
Friday.
	   ``In open court, the NBA's attorney stipulated that Dean Feerick
can decide the case within 24 hours,'' Bryant said.
	   Jeffrey Mishkin, chief legal officer for the NBA, said Bryant's
statement was completely untrue.
	   Stern said Monday that if the players brought him something new,
he'd present it to his negotiating committee. With that in mind,
the players are hoping their new offer will jump start talks.
	   ``I have called David Stern and requested an opportunity to
present it to the owners' labor committee as soon as they're
available, and certainly before the Jan. 7 date that Stern has set
as the owners' deadline,'' Hunter told the players.
	   Union president Patrick Ewing, meanwhile, said the owners'
``final'' offer _ which the commissioner presented earlier this
week _ would not be put to a vote of the general membership unless
a majority asked for it.
	   A handful of players, including Jayson Williams and Kevin
Willis, have called for a chance to vote.
	   ``If the majority of the players call up and say they want a
vote, then we're bound to vote,'' Ewing said. ``But yesterday we
had a conference call and we put the question to them if they want
a vote. And as of today, no one has called to demand that we put it
to a vote.''
	   Williams blamed both sides for the stalled negotiations Tuesday,
and also told reporters he was ``ashamed to be associated with the
NBA.''
	   ``I don't know what Jayson is talking about,'' Ewing told the
New York Post. ``If Jayson has any gripes, he should call the
office and get any gripes he has straightened away. If he wanted to
be on the committee, he should have called up and asked to be on
the committee. We're working for him along with everybody else.
	   ``If Jayson has anything he wants to say to me, come say it to
me face to face. I have no problem with that. If anybody has a
problem with me, come talk to me face to face. I'm tired of hearing
all this stuff and reading things in the paper.''
	   Williams stood by his comments Wednesday.
	   ``What I said is what a lot of players are thinking,'' Williams
told the Post. ``I didn't say Billy Hunter is doing an incompetent
job. Or David Stern is doing a lesser job. Basically, I said,
`Let's vote.' I said what was on my mind, and I stand by that. ...
Patrick Ewing, Alonzo (Mourning), nobody can tell me what to say.
	   ``We can put a 125-year-old man on the moon, and we can't get a
deal done? I don't agree with any of them. I don't agree with the
league or the union.''
	   Stern sent each player a copy of a letter he wrote to Hunter
asking for a vote.
	   ``While it is your prerogative to reject our proposal, the
consequences of that decision will be so catastrophic to your
members that simple fairness suggests they be given a chance to be
heard,'' Stern wrote. ``Accordingly, we request and strongly urge
that you put the NBA's final offer to a vote of the entire union
membership.''
	   Stern's letter, also sent to reporters, lists the additional
concessions the owners offered last Sunday at a negotiating session
in Denver.
	   Hunter's letter detailed areas where the sides remain in
disagreement, including changes to salary cap rules that the union
calls a ``List of Horribles.''
	   ``The negotiating committee and I do not believe the owners have
met us halfway yet, and we are not prepared to recommend that you
accept this proposal,'' Hunter wrote.
</TEXT>
