<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto-Dakar </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dakar Rally starts with preparatory stage in southern Spanish city
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GRANADA, Spain (AP) _ The 21st Dakar rally famed for pushing
riders and their vehicles to the limit, roared into gear Thursday
but didn't go anywhere.
	   The 90 cars, 163 motorcycles and 51 trucks competing in the race
due to end in Dakar, Senegal, on Jan. 17, began with a preparatory
5-kilometer (3-mile) spin around a muddy army base in this southern
Spanish city.
	   The first of the grueling rally's 16 stages scheduled for Friday
covers 520 kilometers (322.4 miles) from Granada southwest to the
coastal town of Algeciras.
	   Once the participants have crossed the narrow stretch of the
Mediterranean Sea separating Spain from North Africa, they are set
to begin their odyssey through Morocco, Mauritania, Mali and
Burkino Faso, before reaching Senegal.
	   In the rally car category defending champion Jean-Pierre
Fontenay and his Mitsubishi team start off as favorites.
	   The race looks more open for the motorcycles, particularly since
Frenchman Stephane Peterhansel, who won the title a record six
times, will be driving a car this year.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
