<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Khmer Rouge leaders enjoy beach holiday; UN probes possible trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with Khmer Rouge chief pleading for rest,
hotel glad for business.
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SIHANOUKVILLE, Cambodia (AP) _ Two Khmer Rouge leaders under
controversial government protection complained Thursday that the
media were wrecking their New Year's beach holiday.
	   The United Nations meanwhile pondered dwindling options of
bringing them to justice for genocide.
	   After basking in VIP treatment in Phnom Penh for two days, Khieu
Samphan and Nuon Chea began touring the country they helped turn
into a bloody slave-labor camp when the Khmer Rouge held power from
1975 to 1979.
	   Escorted by military police providing tight security, the two
drove with their families in luxury vehicles to the seaside town of
Sihanoukville, first leg of a tour that will take them to the
ancient Angkor temples and their home provinces.
	   Along the roads, they will pass memorials stacked with bones and
skulls of thousands of their victims, irrigation ditches dug by
hand under the murderous eye of Khmer Rouge overseers and fields
strewn with mines from years of civil war.
	   The two guerrilla chiefs, who share blame for the deaths of up
to 2 million Cambodians under the Khmer Rouge, emerged from years
in the jungles last week and sealed a defection deal with Prime
Minister Hun Sen that included assurances they would not face
trial.
	   They told a news conference Tuesday that they were ``very
sorry'' for the reign of terror but refused to accept personal
responsibility, inviting survivors to ``let bygones be bygones.''
	   They arrived Thursday at the best hotel in Sihanoukville, where
they had rooms with a view of the Gulf of Thailand 50 meters
(yards) away across sparkling sands.
	   Reporters staked out the hotel. The pair took a room-service
lunch of crab and fish and kept their shades drawn.
	   Long Norin, a spokesman, complained that the presence of
journalists was affecting their stay and that as long as the press
remained, ``They will not leave their rooms.''
	   Khieu Samphan, 67, his hair dyed black during months on the run
in an attempt at disguise, finally appeared and was taken to meet a
local official.
	   ``Excuse me please, I would like to rest a little bit,'' Khieu
Samphan said. ``I have already said what needed to be said.''
	   A receptionist said the hotel was glad for the business, since
tourism dried up after a shipment of toxic waste was discovered in
Sihanoukville a few weeks ago.
	   ``The main thing is that they pay, so we can keep the business
running,'' the receptionist said on condition of anonymity.
	   The deal the two men are receiving from Hun Sen has shaken hopes
that the architects of their murderous rule will ever face justice.
	   The United Nations sent legal experts to Cambodia last month to
assess evidence against senior Khmer Rouge members and offer
recommendations for a tribunal, either overseas or in Cambodia.
	   ``The defection of Noun Chea and Khieu Samphan does not change
the plans,'' said Thomas Hammarberg, the U.N.'s top human rights
officer for Cambodia. ``We intend to present their recommendations
as soon as possible to the government and hope for a constructive
discussion.''
	   King Norodom Sihanouk said Wednesday he would not provide
amnesties for Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea because of ``undeniable
discontent'' among a majority of Cambodians in seeing them go free.
	   Hun Sen has since been silent, but as Cambodia's most powerful
man he can pressure the pliant courts to ensure there is no trial.
	   Hopes for prosecution now seem to rest with the United Nations,
which can pass resolutions to try Khmer Rouge leaders overseas
through an as-yet-uncreated international tribunal.
	   Sihanouk said the international community had ``the perfect
right to take up the case of genocide in Cambodia'' because it was
a crime against humanity.
	   However, Hun Sen's cooperation would be needed to arrest them.
	   ``Considering the scale and the brutality of the Khmer Rouge
crimes, genuine healing in Cambodia will be extremely difficult
without a justice process,'' Hammarberg said.
	   The Khmer Rouge won a civil war in 1975 and forced the
population to toil in agricultural collectives. One Cambodian in
five died of overwork, starvation, disease and executions.
	   They were overthrown in 1979 by a Vietnamese invasion, but
fought a guerrilla war. In 1996, Sihanouk granted amnesty to one
leader, Ieng Sary, who led thousands of fighters to peace.
	   The Khmer Rouge has since dwindled to near-extinction. Many
dispute Hun Sen's assertion that further amnesties are needed to
prevent renewed war. 	   
</TEXT>
