<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Wiesenthal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World's most prominent Nazi hunter celebrates 90th birthday
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) - Simon Wiesenthal, the world's most
prominent Nazi hunter, celebrated his 90th birthday Thursday in his
small Vienna office, surrounded by countless books, files and
testimonials of the victims of the Holocaust.
	   Born Dec. 31, 1908 in what was then the Austro-Hungarian Empire,
Wiesenthal survived 12 Nazi concentration camps before American
troops freed him at the Mauthausen camp in Austria.
	   Since the war, Wiesenthal has spent the rest of his life
documenting Adolf Hitler's atrocities, hunting Nazi war criminals
and publicizing racism, often working out of his tiny Vienna office
where he spent Thursday morning at work.
	   He planned a quite celebration later in the day with his wife
Cyla, whom he married in 1936, and his daughter Pauline, who lives
in Israel.
	   Wiesenthal counts as of his most spectacular successes the 1960
capture of another Austrian, Adolf Eichmann, who was living
incognito in Argentina. Eichmann was abducted by Israeli agents and
returned to Israel, where he was tried and executed.
	   Wiesenthal was also instrumental in the 1963 arrest of Vienna
policeman Karl Silberbauer, who was responsible for the arrest in
Amsterdam of Anne Frank, the 14-year-old Jewish girl who wrote
``Anne Frank's Diary'' before her death in a German concentration
camp.
	   rr
</TEXT>
