<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Missing Ship, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China says missing Japanese ship found
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs with fears for original crew

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China confirmed Thursday that a Japanese cargo
vessel that went missing in September after a suspected hijacking
has been found in a Chinese port, although there were fears that
hijackers had killed the ship's crew.
	   Chinese maritime authorities have impounded the 2,600-ton Tenyu
at the request of its owner, said Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao.
	   In announcing the ship's discovery in an east China port, Zhu
denounced piracy and robbery as ``inhuman atrocities'' and promised
China's continued cooperation in efforts to fight it.
	   ``The Chinese government has all along firmly and strongly
condemned any act of piracy and robbery,'' he said.
	   Earlier, a port official had expressed doubt that the vessel in
question was the missing Tenyu, owned by Japanese shipping company
Masumoto Kisen. The Tenyu disappeared Sept. 27 after leaving an
Indonesian port with a cargo of aluminum worth about 500 million
yen (dlrs 4.3 million).
	   Zhu said the ship was found in Zhangjiagang port in Jiangsu
province, near Shanghai, bearing a new name and a Honduran flag.
	   ``Concerted efforts'' by Chinese maritime officials determined
that the vessel ``is in fact the missing ship MD Tenyu,'' Zhu said.
``The case is under investigation.''
	   Zhu made no mention, however, of the ship's crew. South Korean
maritime police said the Tenyu had been piloted by a South Korean
skipper, Shin Young-ju, and chief engineer, Park Ha-joon, and was
manned by a crew of 12 Chinese sailors.
	   Lloyd's List, a daily shipping newspaper published in London,
said Wednesday that the crew's disappearance raised fears that
hijackers may have murdered them.
	   ``We cannot ignore the possibility that they may have been
killed,'' the newspaper quoted Pottengal Mukundan, director of the
London-based International Maritime Bureau, as saying. ``It is for
this reason we feel it is important that the Chinese authorities
conduct a full investigation before releasing the existing crew on
board.''
	   Chinese authorities are reported to have detained 16 Indonesians
found aboard the vessel.
	   In April, Chinese authorities discovered another hijacked
vessel, the Malaysian-registered Petro Ranger, on China's Hainan
Island, and detained 12 Indonesians.
	   The circumstances of that hijacking raised controversy, with
Chinese authorities saying the ship actually was involved in
smuggling while the Malaysian government contended the vessel had
been hijacked by Indonesians. 	   
</TEXT>
