<SLUG> BC-The Euro, UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU announces rates for currencies entering the euro
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The European Commission, the 20-member
executive body of the European Union, agreed Thursday on the
irreversible rates at which the currencies of 11 EU nations will be
locked to form a new single currency.
	   Finance ministers from the 11 nations were to given a final
stamp of approval to the rates later Thursday.
	   Under the Commission's recommendation, the new common currency
would be worth 1.95583 German marks, 6.55957 French francs, 1936.27
Italian lire, 166.386 Spanish pesetas.
	   Those rates mean the euro would start trading at about dlrs
1.1665 when markets open Monday after the long New Year's weekend.
	   Four EU members are not participating in the single currency.
