<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nearly 3,000 Hutus flee eastern Congo, U.N. says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ Nearly 3,000 Hutus have fled to Uganda
from rebel-held eastern Congo in the past two weeks, U.N. officials
said Thursday.
	   The refugees fled Congo through the Ugandan town of Kisoro, 480
km (220 miles) west of the capital, Kampala, said Nino Timoko, a
spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
	   The uprooted Hutus were being transported to a refugee camp in
Hoima, 140 km (53 miles) west of Kampala.
	   A rebel coalition of ethnic Tutsis, disaffected Congolese
soldiers and opposition politicians has taken over nearly all of
eastern Congo since launching their bid Aug. 2 to oust Congolese
President Laurent Kabila.
	   Timoko did not describe the circumstances that forced the Hutus
to flee, citing only ``general insecurity in their villages.''
	   An independent Ugandan newspaper, the Monitor, reported Thursday
that the refugees had fled the eastern towns of Rushuru and Goma,
the insurgents' headquarters.
	   It was not immediately known whether those arriving Uganda were
indigenous Congolese or remnants of the hundreds of thousands of
Rwandan Hutus who fled to the former Zaire in 1994 to escape
reprisals after extremist Hutus carried out the genocide of at
least 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus in Rwanda.
	   Congolese President Laurent Kabila and the Tutsi-backed rebel
force that helped bring him to power last year have been accused of
targeting Rwandan Hutus to avenge the massacres.
	   (cn/sl)	   
</TEXT>
