<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Taiwan-Toxic Waste </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan legislator vows speedy export of mercury-tainted waste
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ A Taiwanese legislator promised
Thursday that 3,000 tons of mercury-laced waste from his country
that caused a deadly scandal in Cambodia would be removed as soon
as possible.
	   A team of experts sent by the plastics company that shipped the
waste arrived to verify previous tests that the material _ believed
to be compressed industrial ash _ is highly toxic.
	   The waste from Formosa Plastics Corp. was quietly shipped into
Cambodia and dumped near a small village 10 kilometers (6 miles)
away from the seaport town of Sihanoukville.
	   Discovery of the waste sparked outrage that escalated into riots
and panic when a dock worker mysteriously died after cleaning the
hold of the ship that transported the waste.
	   Four more people died in traffic accidents as residents of the
town fled in terror.
	   Allen Tseng, a Taiwanese legislator who has joined the
delegation because of his close contacts with the Cambodian
government, said at the Phnom Penh airport that Taiwan is committed
to ending the scandal.
	   ``We will work quickly to transfer all the mercury waste out of
the country,'' Tseng said.
	   Taiwan's government ordered Formosa Plastics to take back the
waste after tests by a Taiwanese environmental group showed it
contained mercury levels slightly above the country's safety
standards of 0.2 parts per million.
	   Two separate analyses of the waste have determined it could be
highly toxic.
	   An initial test commissioned by Cambodia's Environment Ministry
registered a mercury level of 675 parts per million, and five tests
conducted by Japan's Minamata Institute have showed levels ranging
from 97 to 3,984 parts per million.
	   Formosa Plastics and the Taiwanese Environmental Protection
agents will travel to the dump site Friday and take their own
samples.
	   Environment Minister Mok Mareth reiterated Thursday that the
Cambodian government would seek compensation for the deaths and
suspected environmental damage.
	   Mok Mareth added that the World health Organization and private
consultants will determine the amount of damage done.
	   Formosa Plastics representatives declined comment at the
airport, but delegation member Jacky Ko said the company has
expressed intent to pay some compensation.
	   Ko also said that Formosa Plastics has plans to send the waste
to either the United States or Europe to have it retreated.
	   Mok Mareth said efforts by Cambodian soldiers to pack the waste
into plastic-lined oil drums proceeded too slowly, so the
government brought in bulldozers this week to shovel the waste
directly into 50 shipping containers.
	   The cleanup operation is expected to be completed within a week.
</TEXT>
