<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-New Year-Fireworks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Goodbye 1998 _ Sydney rings out the old year with a big bang
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos staffing
 &UR; Eds: Will be led after midnight local time.
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Millions of Sydney residents bid
farewell to 1998 Thursday night by partying and watching a 2
million Australian dollars (U.S. dlrs 1.2 million) fireworks
extravaganza over the harbor.
	   The Sydney Opera House was bathed in pulses of green, red or
blue light as massive fireworks burst over the harbor in the first
of two bombardments, which began at 9 p.m. (1000 GMT Thursday.)
	   Another fireworks display was set for midnight to ring in the
new year.
	   More than a million people were expected to see Sydney's night
sky light up in person, and many of the city's other 2.5 million
viewed live TV coverage of the annual festival.
	   Sydney celebrates every major holiday and event with fireworks,
but New Year's Eve is a pyrotechnic orgy, and this year's barrage
was a dress rehearsal for upcoming sky shows to mark next year's
welcome for the year 2000, and the summer Olympic Games set for
September 2000.
	   Crowds cried ``Ooooh'' and ``Aaaaah!'' as combinations of
fireworks, some formations bigger than most downtown buildings, lit
the sultry southern summer night sky under low clouds.
	   The upper parts of some fireworks were cut off by low cloud
cover.
	   In addition to the usual starburst and mortar type fireworks,
the show was punctuated by blasts that fanned out in heart or ring
shapes, sometimes with another spherical firework in the middle to
create a Saturn-like effect.
	   Some of the ringed fireworks went off simultaneously, creating a
shape like a sketch of an atom.
	   A highlight of the show was the display rigged on the Sydney
Harbor Bridge, with cascading white sparks from the roadway
resembling a fiery waterfall, and red or white mortar blasts
spewing from the girders supporting its huge arch.
	   Smoke shrouded downtown after the 20-minute display, but was
clearing quickly, to give revellers a clear view for the midnight
finale. 	   
</TEXT>
