<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Portugal-Euro </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Portuguese Premier fears selfishness of EU member states
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said in
an interview published Thursday that resurgent national egoism
among the European Union's member states could thwart efforts to
deepen European integration after the launch of the euro.
	   Guterres was quoted as saying in the daily Publico that the
15-member EU was ``currently going through a period of some
resurgence in national egoism,''
	   This trend was ``worrying'' because it had caused ``political
hesitancy'' in forging common policies, especially in foreign
policy and security, he said.
	   Portugal is one of the 11 founder members of the euro, the new
European single currency which goes into effect Jan. 1.
	   ``The new currency .. will help to create a set of basic
conditions allowing Europe's political leaders _ if they are up to
it _ to build a serious European project,'' Guterres was quoted as
saying.
	   He said he would like to see common political institutions
governing the EU which would allow the bloc ``to play the world
role that corresponds to its economic weight.''
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
