w1885 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-ImportBarriers     12-31 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Import Barriers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China's import checks raise surplus, trade tensions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOSH CHERIN &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SHANGHAI, China (AP) _ New financial controls imposed by China
on its trading companies have cut the flow of imports and
threatened to worsen tensions with its major trading partners.
	   Imports have fallen so sharply that even though exports barely
grew in 1998 because of the Asian economic crisis, China's trade
surplus rose 11 percent to dlrs 45 billion, according to official
figures released Wednesday.
	   The new rules, imposed in July to protect Chinese foreign
currency reserves, make it harder for companies to get import
financing and licenses.
	   China's currency, the yuan, doesn't trade internationally, and
companies are allowed to buy foreign currency only for approved
imports. Dozens of people have been prosecuted in recent months for
using fake import papers to obtain millions of dollars in foreign
currency.
	   Chinese officials defend the new rules as a way to stop
smuggling and illegal currency trading.
	   ``The new controls will slow imports in the short term, but in
the long term they will restore the market,'' Jia Jun, an official
of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, told Dow
Jones Newswires.
	   The restrictions threaten to fuel complaints by trading partners
already angered at Chinese quotas and high tariffs that block most
imports of cars and consumer goods.
	   U.S. officials have warned that the trade deficit with China _
projected at dlrs 60 billion in 1998 and dlrs 70 billion in 1999 _
was politically untenable.
	   ``These steps are definitely protectionist actions that will
cause a reaction here,'' U.S. Secretary of Commerce Richard Daley
warned at a news conference in Washington on Dec. 18.
	   For all but the biggest Chinese firms, banks have begun
demanding 100 percent payment in advance for letters of credit _
the standard guarantee for trade finance. Last year, they would
accept just 30 percent in advance, with real estate pledged as
collateral for the rest.
	   Chinese trading companies complain that even with financing,
they often cannot get import licenses. The government has banned
the former widespread practice of borrowing licenses from large
state trading companies.
	   Beijing says it is taking steps to speed up trade approvals with
a new computerized network that also is intended to catch forged
documents. The system is to take effect Friday, according to state
media.
	   And for the first time, a handful of private companies have been
allowed to apply for trading licenses in a significant step away
from the state-dominated trading system.
	   But trade officials say approval is moving slowly because of the
complexity of the application process.
	   Analysts say the biggest impact will be not on small consumer
goods such as television sets, but on bulk commodities such as
metals, crude oil, fertilizer and sugar. China wants to protect its
own commodity producers from falling world prices, they say.	   
</TEXT>
