<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Immigrants-Sinking, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At least two dead after immigrant boat sinks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with at least 10 people missing,
Yugoslav rescued, CLARIFIES one body not recovered. No pickup &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ At least two people drowned and another 10
were reported missing Thursday when a wooden boat carrying illegal
immigrants sank in the Aegean, rescue officials said.
	   Nearby ships and port authority vessels managed to rescue two
Greeks, one Yugoslav and 21 Pakistani, Indian and Iraqi men who had
been on board the 17-meter (56-foot), Italian-flagged Mustang, the
merchant ministry said.
	   The boat began taking on water and sank off the island of
Nissiros, about 320 kilometers (200 miles) southeast of Athens,
authorities said.
	   A St. Vincent-flagged ship, Geline Metz, recovered one body,
while another person drowned during a rescue attempt by the
Greek-flagged tourist boat Chrisoula, the ministry said.
	   The nationalities of the dead were not immediately clear, and
the second body was not recovered.
	   A helicopter and coast guard vessels searched for another 10
people reported missing. Authorities believe the Mustang had set
sail from Turkey with 33 immigrants and a three-member crew.
	   One Iraqi survivor said he saw at least five people drown, but
his account could not be independently confirmed, the ministry
said.
	   The Mustang sank at around 5:30 a.m. (0330 GMT) seven miles west
of Nissiros, located near the Turkish coast, the ministry added.
	   The people rescued were to be taken to the nearby island of Kos,
the ministry said.
	   Tens of thousands of illegal immigrants, mostly Iraqi Kurds,
attempt each year to cross from the Turkish coast to nearby Greek
islands. Many are arrested and deported, but others apply for
asylum in Greece and are taken to refugee camps while their
applications are processed.
	   Hundreds find work clandestinely in Greece or move on to Italy
to make their way to other European countries.
	   (eb-bm) 	   
</TEXT>
