<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Obit-Forest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Creator of Barbarella dies at 68
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Jean-Claude Forest, who created the sultry sci-fi
comic strip character Barbarella and designed sets for the '60s
cult movie version starring Jane Fonda, has died, his publisher
said Thursday. He was 68.
	   ``Barbarella'' went on to inspire fashion designers, the '80s
pop group Duran Duran, who chose their name from a character in the
film, and a string of comic strip heroines leading up to today's
cyber-babe Lara Croft.
	   Forest died of a respiratory illness at a hospital outside Paris
on Wednesday morning. Funeral arrangements were pending, said Helen
Werle, spokeswoman for Editions Dargaud.
	   It was in April 1962 that Forest, after successes with the
youthful adventure comic strips ``Bicot,'' created the seductive
41st century adventuress ``to amuse myself.''
	   She first appeared that year in the gentleman's ``V Magazine''
as a futuristic barbarian, seducing androids on the planet Lythion.
	   The series, published in other languages, was censored in
France, barred from advertising or sale to minors until the early
1970s.
	   Barbarella ``was a step forward'' in the business, testing the
limits of French censorship, Guy Vidal, director of comic strips at
Dargaud, said in a telephone interview. ``There have been those who
helped unlock censorship. Forest was one of them.''
	   It wasn't until producer Dino de Laurentiis bought the film
rights to Barbarella that Barbarella gained world star status, and
helping propel Jane Fonda to silver screen fame.
	   Directed by Roger Vadim, it was released in June 1968, barely a
month after the May '68 social upheaval in France that in part
reflected the revolt against traditional French morality.
	   Forest designed most of the sets for the Franco-Italian
production, shot in Rome.
	   Film critic Leonard Maltin has described ``Barbarella'' as ``a
midnight movie favorite ... not especially funny, but watchable,
with Fonda's striptease during opening credits the principal reason
for its cult status.''
	   Fonda's shiny, form-fitting space-age outfits stirred the
imaginations of designers. Barbarella-style get-ups, created by
French fashion badboy Jean-Paul Gaultier, accented last year's film
``The Fifth Element,'' with Bruce Willis and Milla Jovovich.
	   Born Sept. 11, 1930, Forest sketched his first comic strip as a
19-year-old student at art school, titled ``La Fleche noire,'' or
``The Black Arrow.''
	   He began his career with ``Le vaisseau hante,'' or ``The Haunted
Ship,'' published by Elan. In 1950, he became illustrator for such
publications as ``Le livre de poche,'' ``Voila,'' ``Fiction'' and
``Les nouvelles litteraires.''
	   Forest's last Barbarella episode was published in 1981.
	   After years of censorship, the French government rehabilitated
Forest as one of its own, taking him on to represent the country's
comic strip artists abroad beginning in 1976.
	   Forest was honored in 1984 with the Grand Prize of Angouleme,
site of an annual comic strip festival. He received the 1986 prize
from another comic strip festival in Sierre, Switzerland, for his
lifetime work.
	   Forest is survived by his wife Petra, a sculptor who lives in
Paris, and a son, Julien, 28.
	   (cb-parf)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-France-Obit-Forest; CT:i; 
