w1904 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-WorldCu 1stLd-Writethru   12-31 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-2006, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seven candidates compete for World Cup 2006
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS comment from England &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ Germany, England, Brazil, South
Africa, Morocco, Egypt and Ghana are the official candidates to
host the 2006 World Cup finals.
	   The seven countries all notified FIFA in advance of the Thursday
night deadline of their intent to stage soccer's four-yearly
showcase. They now have until the end of July to submit their full
bid documents.
	   FIFA's 24-member executive committee will decide in March 2000.
	   FIFA President Sepp Blatter has repeatedly said the soccer
authority has a responsibility to stage the tournament in Africa,
which has never hosted the finals.
	   Morocco lost out to France for the staging of the 1998 finals.
	   Despite its high crime rate, South Africa is widely considered
the front-runner. It hosted the 1995 rugby union World Cup, the
1996 African Nations Cup and the 1998 athletics World Cup.
	   South African officials maintain they can keep crime under
control and say their infrastructure is developed enough to cope
with the demands of the tournament.
	   ``Certainly emotionally there is some support for South Africa
because their continent has never had it before,'' conceded
England's bid chief Alec McGivan on Thursday.
	   ``That is something we have to overcome.''
	   ``The question is when will an African candidate be ready to
take on what is a huge logistical exercise?'' he queried.
	   The case of both Germany and England has been weakened by the
fact that they are from the same continent. The 2002 finals are
being split between Japan and South Korea _ but FIFA insists that
co-hosting will be a one-time exception.
	   Underlining the increasing European rivalry, McGivan said in a
radio interview that Germans were envious at the amount of support
given by the British government to England's bid.
	   He told BBC Radio 5 Live that he didn't think the bribery
scandal rocking British soccer would be ``an issue at all'' in
FIFA's choice of site.
	   Hoping to boost its standing in the eyes of FIFA, European
Champions Germany recently agreed to take part in next summer's
Confederation Cup, after World Cup winners France pulled out for
scheduling reasons.
 &UR; (cn)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-2006, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
