<SLUG> BC-The Euro, UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finance ministers set rates for currencies entering the euro
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Finance ministers from 11 European
Union nations agreed Thursday on the irreversible rates at which
their currencies will be locked together to form the new single
currency known as the euro.
	   The new common currency will be worth 1.95583 German marks,
6.55957 French francs, 1936.27 Italian lire, 166.386 Spanish
pesetas.
	   The rates mean the euro will start trading at about dlrs 1.1665
when markets open Monday after the long New Year's weekend.
