<SLUG> BC-Russia-France </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia ships uranium to France for research reactors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia delivered an unspecified amount of
highly-enriched uranium to France that will be burned in two
research reactors, a news report said Thursday.
	   The shipment was the first of many uranium deliveries called for
under a 1996 technological cooperation agreement signed between
France and Russia.
	   The uranium will be used in two government research reactors,
including one in Grenoble, the Interfax news agency reported,
citing Russia's Nuclear Energy Ministry.
	   The report did not say how much uranium was delivered, or how
much France paid for it.
	   The agreement is part of an effort by the West to encourage
Russia to safely dispose of its old nuclear materials. The West
wants to keep the uranium away from states that might be trying to
develop nuclear weapons programs.
	   With the delivery, Russia will be able to raise revenues and
defray Soviet-era debts to France for energy sector equipment.
	   (nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
