<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Jordan-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egyptian cleric criticizes Saddam; pro-Iraq demonstration in
</HEADLINE>
Jordan &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Reflecting divided Arab opinions, a leading
Egyptian cleric harshly criticized Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
while Jordanian demonstrators urged lifting U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
	   Sheik Mohammed Sayed Tantawi, head of Sunni Islam's leading
center of religious study, Al-Azhar, accused Saddam of using his
power for ``evil and betrayal.''
	   The remark, printed Thursday in the pro-government daily
Al-Ahram, comes amid a trading of insults in the Egyptian and Iraqi
press after Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak criticized Saddam
earlier this week.
	   ``A leader like Saddam Hussein, who used his forces for evil and
betrayal in an arrogant way, should not be sweet-talked or appeased
by anyone,'' Tantawi was quoted as saying.
	   Al-Ahram said he spoke Wednesday to the Kuwaiti-Egyptian
Friendship Association. It was Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait the
divided the Arab world into pro- and anti-Iraq sides and set off
the Gulf War.
	   Tantawi also was quoted as expressing sorrow for the plight of
the Iraqi people whom he said ``have suffered and were distressed
because of the wars and injustices that afflicted them.''
	   In the Jordanian capital Amman, meanwhile, about 200 people
demonstrated near the U.S. Embassy after being prevented from
reaching the embassy itself by some 600 anti-riot police.
	   ``We want to announce that we do not want to see any American
here,'' the crowd chanted, protesting the U.S. and British
airstrikes on Iraq in mid-December.
	   The demonstrators demanded an immediate halt to U.N. Security
sanctions on Iraq _ imposed after the invasion of Kuwait _ and
shouted support for Osama bin Laden, the Saudi dissident blamed for
bombing attacks on U.S. embassies in Africa last August.
	   ``We are trying to express our views against the massacre of the
Iraqi people and, as you see, we are forbidden from doing so,''
said opposition figure Toujan Faisal, pointing at police blocking
the road to the embassy.
	   Jordanian officials had said earlier they would ban the protest
since Iraqi officials had planned to attend. But police made no
move to stop the protest, only kept it away from the embassy. The
crowd dispersed peacefully in under an hour.
 &UR; bm-ash-jah-ggl
</TEXT>
