<HEADLINE>
Indonesian leader promises to fight corruption, promote reform in
</HEADLINE>
1999

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesian President B.J. Habibie on
Thursday assured citizens of the recession-hit Southeast Asian
nation that his government will work hard in the new year to fight
corruption and promote reform.
	   ``We will continue with efforts to create a clean, respectable
and capable government which is free from corruption, collusion and
nepotism,'' Habibie said in a year-end speech.
	   He also expressed hope for an improvement in areas such as human
rights.
	   Habibie came to power in May after his one-time mentor,
ex-President Suharto, resigned amid widespread protests against his
32-year authoritarian rule.
	   In a speech broadcasted nationwide by all radio and television
stations, the new Indonesian president reiterated a pledge to bring
about widescale political and economic reform.
	   Habibie said a Parliamentary election scheduled for June 7 would
usher in a new era of democratic rule.
	   ``There is no intention from the government to maintain
political status-quo because all will be decided by the democracy
mechanism in accordance with the principles of people's sovereignty
adopted by the 1945 constitution.''
	   He called on Indonesians to remain optimistic about their
country's prospects in 1999 despite recent economic and social
turmoil. 	   
</TEXT>
