<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Serb premier </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnian Serb president names new premier-designate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IRENA GAJIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ In an effort to end a
political deadlock, the Bosnian Serb president Thursday named a
moderate as the new premier-designate, after a previous hardline
candidate failed to win parliamentary approval.
	   Brane Miljus is a member of the Party of Independent Social
Democrats, a pro-Western party run by current Bosnian Serb Premier
Milorad Dodik. The decision to select Miljus is likely to be
welcomed by international officials in Bosnia, who have sought to
maintain a moderate government in the Serb-controlled half of
Bosnia.
	   Miljus' appointment still must be approved by parliament. No
date for the vote has been set.
	   The announcement by President Nikola Poplasen followed months of
political dispute between Bosnian Serb moderates and hard-liners
over the premier's post. Neither of the two bitterly opposed camps
gained a majority in parliament following September general
elections.
	   Poplasen, a hard-liner, first named Dragan Kalinic premier, but
Kalinic failed to win parliamentary approval. Kalinic is a close
aide to Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb wartime leader indicted
by the international war crimes tribunal.
	   Moderates insisted that Dodik remain premier, which the
hard-liners refused. Miljus's selection is seen as a compromise.
	   The hardline Serb Democratic Party, formerly run by Karadzic,
has announced its support of Miljus. The moderate coalition, headed
by Dodik and former Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic, has yet
to comment on the selection.
	   International officials have threatened to cut financial aid to
Bosnian Serbs if a hard-liner becomes premier.
	   Miljus, from the disputed town of Brcko, pledged in a statement
Thursday to maintain close ties with the international community
and honor the US-brokered Dayton peace agreements for Bosnia,
signed in 1995.
	   The peace accords, which ended more than three years of
fighting, divided Bosnia roughly in two, with Serbs controlling one
half and the Muslim-Croat controlling the other. The country has
joint central institutions.
	   (ig/jg/scl)
</TEXT>
