<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-START II </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deputy prime minister pushes for early ratification of START II
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A senior Cabinet member called on the Russian
parliament Thursday to quickly ratify the START II arms reduction
treaty with the United States.
	   ``START II is no less advantageous to Russia than it is to the
United States,'' First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov said
through his spokesman.
	   He called on the Communist-dominated parliament's lower house,
the State Duma, to consider ratification of the treaty in late
January or early February, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Russia and the United States signed START II in 1993, and the
U.S. Senate approved it in 1996. The Duma has delayed ratification,
claiming the treaty will damage Russia's security.
	   Some members of parliament insist that Russia should maintain
its current nuclear arsenal despite its huge cost, which is well
beyond the means of the cash-strapped government.
	   Lawmakers appeared ready to approve the treaty earlier this
month, but again put off ratification to protest U.S. and British
air strikes against Iraq.
	   On Wednesday, President Boris Yeltsin pledged in a telephone
conversation with U.S. President Bill Clinton to push for START II
ratification.
	   Russia's top military brass has also supported the treaty,
saying that by 2007 _ the START II deadline for halving Russian and
U.S. arsenals to 3,000-3,500 warheads each _ Russia's aging heavy
missiles will have to be decommissioned anyway.
	   Maslyukov said ratification of START II would clear the way for
START III, which would further cut U.S. and Russian nuclear
arsenals to 2,000-2,500 warheads each.
	   (vi/nw/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
