	   EDITORS: The following stories have moved or will move on the
European circuits of The Associated Press by 1600 GMT unless
otherwise noted:
	   BRUSSELS _ Europe's dream of monetary union became reality
Thursday when 11 nations irrevocably locked their currencies
together to form the euro and create an economic giant whose
boundaries stretch from beyond the Arctic Circle to the shores of
the Mediterranean. THE EURO.
	   WITH:
	   GERMANY-INTEREST RATES. German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine
again hints he favors further interest rate cuts by the European
Central Bank.
	   FRANCE-EURO. France's finance minister said Thursday that
European Central Bank chief Wim Duisenberg should honor a
commitment to step down after four years to make way for the
candidate France had backed for the post.
	   DENMARK-EURO. Denmark could hold a plebiscite to join the
European Union's common currency system within two years, which is
earlier than now expected, Economy Minister Marianne Jelved said
Thursday.
	   PORTUGAL-EURO. Prime Minister Antonio Guterres says resurgent
national egoism among European Union member states could thwart
efforts to deepen European integration after the launch of the
euro.
	   GREECE-EURO DREAMS. At the birth of the euro, Greece is outside
looking in.
	   THE EURO-CHRONOLOGY. Key dates on the road to the euro.
	   THE EURO-RATES. European Union finance ministers on Thursday set
the irrevocable conversion rates between the euro and currencies
from the 11 nations participating in the shared currency.
	   TEL AVIV _ The U.S. ambassador closed the U.S. Embassy in Tel
Aviv on Thursday after receiving ``credible'' threats, an embassy
spokesman said. Israeli police posted extra security at the
Mediterranean beachfront building. ISRAEL-US EMBASSY.
	   ADEN _ When the shooting started, Margaret Whitehouse dropped to
her knees to try to help a fellow hostage who was wounded.
YEMEN-KIDNAPPING.
	   PRISTINA _ Despite a conciliatory New Year's message from the
president of Yugoslavia, his government allies vowed Thursday to
defend Kosovo ``with all means'' and fight against NATO if it
intervenes in the troubled Serbian province. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO.
	   BAGHDAD _ There will be no letup in Baghdad's defiance of
Western-patrolled ``no-fly'' zones in northern and southern Iraq,
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz says in remarks published
Thursday. IRAQ.
	   WITH:
	   EGYPT-JORDAN-IRAQ. Reflecting divided Arab opinions, a leading
Egyptian cleric harshly criticized Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
while Jordanian demonstrators urged lifting U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
	   US-IRAQ. The USS Enterprise battle group is set to leave the
Gulf by week's end as the Pentagon reduces its military force in
the region despite skirmishes between Iraqi air defense and U.S.
and British warplanes.
	   MOSCOW _ Russian inflation, which appeared under control until a
financial crisis hit last summer, reached 84 percent for all of
1998, the government said Thursday. RUSSIA-ECONOMY.
	   PARIS _ Jean-Claude Forest, who created the sultry sci-fi comic
strip character Barbarella and designed sets for the '60s cult
movie version starring Jane Fonda, has died, his publisher said
Thursday. He was 68. FRANCE-OBIT-FOREST.
	   BANJA LUKA _ In an effort to end a political deadlock, the
Bosnian Serb president Thursday named a moderate as the new
premier-designate, after a previous hardline candidate failed to
win parliamentary approval. BOSNIA-SERB PREMIER.
	   ALSO:
	   GREECE-IMMIGRANTS-SINKING. At least two people drowned and
another two were reportedly missing Thursday when a wooden boat
carrying illegal immigrants sank in the Aegean, rescue officials
said.
	   SINGAPORE-RECESSION. Singapore fell into recession as 1998
ended, according to figures in the prime minister's New Year's
message Thursday.
	   SKOREA-BANK. South Korea agrees Thursday to sell heavily
indebted Korea First Bank to an American financial consortium in a
bid to boost foreign confidence in its crisis-hit economy.
	   ANGOLA. The United Nations has started evacuating its staff from
Huambo, Angola's second largest city, after a rebel artillery
barrage that wounded at least 20 civilians, a diplomat said
Thursday.
