<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Cinema </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French film industry sinking, yearend figures show
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The French are going to the movies more than ever.
But they're choosing Hollywood blockbusters over the intimate,
human dramas in their native tongue, a French newspaper reported
Thursday.
	   According to the daily Le Figaro, attendances for French films
in 1998 were the worst for a decade, partly because of the
overwhelming success of ``Titanic,'' and also because a host of
French movies flopped.
	   ``Why French cinema is sinking,'' headlined the paper, with a
picture of a scene from ``Titanic.''
	   The newspaper quoted figures from the National Cinematogapahic
Center showing that French movies accounted for less than 30
percent of the 170 million national attendance figures.
	   James Cameron's ``Titanic'' alone grabbed 13 percent of viewers,
while Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' and Robert
Redford's ``The Horse Whisperer'' were word-of-mouth box-office
successes, the paper said.
	   Despite the huge success of three French comedies, ``Le Diner
des Cons,'' (The Dinner of Idiots) ``Les Couloirs du Temps'' (The
Halls of Time) and ``Taxi,'' the French cinema has ``run out of
steam,'' Le Figaro wrote.
	   The comedies attracted a total of 23 million viewers, the paper
said.
	   Industry officials blamed the disaster on the nation's economic
woes, not the quality of French movies.
	   They have high hopes for a feature-length version of the famed
comic book character ``Asterix,'' starring Gerard Depardieu in
France's most expensive production ever, to be released in
February.
	   (ma-ip)
</TEXT>
