<HEADER>
w2011 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MiddleEastBusinessBri     12-31 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan, Kuwait, Iraq.

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan's transport minister, Nasser Lawzi,
said Thursday that the country plans to set up a new railway
system.
	   Lawzi said that a feasibility study for the Light Rail System
has been completed. He said it will link the capital Amman with
Zarka, 30 kilometers (18 miles) to the north and Sweileh, 20
kilometers (15 miles) to the west.
	   He estimated the cost of the project at 50 million dinars (dlrs
70 million) and said it should be ready for operation early in the
year 2003.
	   If it proves popular, it could reduce road traffic by about 30
percent, he said.
	   Thirty international companies have expressed interest in
participating in the project, he said. A construction contract is
to be awarded in August 1999, Lawzi said.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The price index of the Kuwait Stock Exchange
closed at 1,582.7 points at the end of the trading week, down 3.83
percent from last week, the National Investments Co. said Thursday.
	   According to the company's weekly report, portfolio managers did
not move to support end-of-year closings, as was expected.
	   Instead, it said, they decided to ``close the page on this year
with its definite losses and start the coming one with low prices
that would help achieve better profits in 1999.''
	   Some 196.95 million shares were traded in the last week of the
year, down 38.11 percent from the week before, the report said. The
value of these shares dropped 22.25 percent, to 44.08 million
dinars (dlrs 145.96 million).
	   Of the market's 78 listed companies, 68 were traded, with 14
closing higher, 50 closing lower and the rest unchanged.
	   Trading on the Kuwait Stock Exchange is restricted to Kuwaitis
and nationals of the other Gulf states: Saudi Arabia, the United
Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Qatar and Oman.
 &UR; ___
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Trading levels slipped on the Baghdad Stock
Exchange following U.S. and British airstrikes on Iraq.
	   But the four-day bombing campaign, which ended Dec. 19, and the
subsequent skirmishes over the ``no-fly'' zones have had little
impact on the value of the Iraqi dinar, which has stayed at about
1,850 to the dollar.
	   The market bulletin released Thursday the number of shares
traded in the three business days ending Wednesday fell more than
50 percent to 13.7 million. The value of these shares was 178.6
million Iraqi dinars (dlrs 96,540), a decline of 47 percent from
the previous week.
	   Trading is to resume Jan. 2.
 &UR; ____
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Share prices and turnover rose on the Amman
stock exchange this week, a market report said Thursday.
	   Brokers attributed the rises to year-end trading and to a
sell-off from the country's second largest bank.
	   The Housing Bank sold its stake Tuesday in the Jordan Cement
Factories Company to investors from Morocco, netting ten million
dinars (dlrs 14 million).
	   The market report, reflecting activity for five business days
ending Wednesday, said that the 60-company General Share Prices
index nudged up 2.16 percent to 170.13 points.
	   Shares of commercial banks increased 2.58 percent, industrial
firms 0.82 percent, services sector 2.69 percent, and insurance
sector 1.03 percent.
	   Turnover soared 362 percent to 23.1 million Jordanian dinars
(dlrs 32.5 million), the report said.
	   It said stocks of 105 firms were traded during the week.
 &UR; buros-eap/jbm
</TEXT>
