<SLUG> BC-Austria-Anti-Euro </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rightwing party deplores Euro-euphoria
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) - While Austria joined other Europeans in
hailing the advent of the euro, the country's fast-growing
rightwing party Thursday said it would wait to see whether the
common currency actually brings stability and economic growth.
	   Peter Westenthaler, secretary-general of the Freedom Party,
criticized the ``Euro-euphoria'' of Austria's other parties, which
joined those across Europe in hailing the birth of the new
currency.
	   Westenthaler dismissed statements hailing the advent of the new
currency as simply ``reveling in exuberance for the euro.''
	   ``We will just be celebrating the New Year,'' he said.
	   Austria is among the 11 European nations which joined in
creating the common currency, which binding some of the world's
wealthiest nations in an economic giant.
	   ``The euro becomes the strong arm of the strongest economic
region of the world and through a coordinated economic policy, the
strong center of a common policy for growth and employment,''
Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima said. ``Today is an historic day
for Europe.''
	   The Freedom Party, led by Joerg Haider, has emerged in recent
years as Austria's third largest party, coming within a few
percentage points of overtaking the conservative People's Party as
the second strongest political force here behind the Socialists.
	   But the Freedom Party, which has campaigned on nationalist and
anti-foreign platforms, suffered a setback last year in trying to
muster opposition to the euro.
	   rr
</TEXT>
