<HEADLINE>
Caligiuri will return to Galaxy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PASADENA, California (AP) _ Former U.S. national team defender
Paul Caligiuri will return to the Los Angeles Galaxy for the 1999
season, after being waived by the Major League Soccer team Oct. 31
for salary-cap reasons, the league has announced.
	   The 34-year old was waived by the Galaxy as it was finalizing
its roster in preparation for the Nov. 2 waiver draft.
	   He signed a new contract with the league earlier this month with
MLS. Under the MLS' ``single-entity'' structure, all players sign
contracts with the league, with the marquee players assigned to
teams and most of the rest distributed by draft or trade.
	   Terms of Caligiuri's contract were not disclosed, but a source
within in the league who asked not to be identified said it was for
a lower amount than the original three-year contract Caligiuri
signed with the league in 1996.
	   The 34-year old Caligiuri played 18 matches for the Galaxy
during an injury-plagued 1998 season, starting 14. Foot and ankle
injuries forced him to miss 11 of Los Angeles' first 15 matches,
while a strained groin kept him out of one match in August and two
in September. Caligiuri returned to start in all four of the
Galaxy's playoff matches.
	   Caligiuri was selected by the Columbus Crew in the first round
of the 1996 supplmental draft but sued the league claiming he was
promised assignment to the Galaxy. An arbitrator ruled in his
favor, forcing the league to transfer him to Los Angeles before the
1997 season.
</TEXT>
