<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Milosevic's ally vows to defend Kosovo from NATO
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS; RECASTS; raises reference to attack on police. no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb leaders warned Thursday they
would use ``all means'' necessary to stamp out rebellion in Kosovo
after government media reported another attack by ethnic Albanians
on police in the troubled province.
	   ``We are obliged to use all means to oppose the rush of
terrorism and separatism'' in Kosovo, Yugoslav Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic said in an interview with Serbian television.
	   Those sentiments were echoed by Serbia's extreme nationalist
vice premier, Vojislav Seselj. He also warned that the government
was prepared to stand up against threats by NATO to intervene
militarily in the Kosovo conflict if fighting erupts on a major
scale.
	   Seselj denounced warnings by NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana, who said this week that the Western alliance would not
tolerate violence in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia's main
republic Serbia.
	   ``Warnings of Javier Solana remind me of one-time threats by
Adolf Hitler,'' Seselj told reporters. He said, ``NATO is an
aggressive military force threatening the whole mankind.''
	   Those warnings were issued after the government's Tanjug news
agency reported that a Serbian police patrol was attacked northwest
of Pristina late Wednesday by ethnic Albanian rebels. There were no
reported casualties.
	   Kosovo has been generally quiet since four days of fighting,
which erupted Christmas Eve near the northern Kosovo town of
Podujevo. At least 15 people were killed before international peace
verifiers managed to negotiate an end to the fighting.
	   About 1,000 people were killed and tens of thousands left
homeless during seven months of fighting between government forces
and the Kosovo Liberation Army. Widespread fighting was brought to
an end under an agreement signed Oct. 12 between Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke.
	   Tensions, however, remain high, stoking fears that the two sides
may be gearing up for a new round of bloodshed, possibly in the
spring.
	   In his New Year's message, Milosevic predicted a political
solution for the Kosovo conflict would come next year, including a
``multi-ethnic Kosovo, based on the principles of equality for
all.''
	   But he again ruled out independence for Kosovo, where ethnic
Albanians make up 90 percent of the population, saying any efforts
to secede would ``come up against the will of the people'' of
Yugoslavia.
	   Wide differences between the ethnic Albanians and the Serbs on
the future of the province have hampered American-led diplomatic
efforts to resolve the conflict.
	   rr
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
