<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Missiles </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish Cypriots reject calls for reduction of Turkish military
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash on
Thursday rejected calls for Turkey to reduce its military presence
on Cyprus now that the Greek Cypriots have decided not to deploy
missiles.
	   Germany, which assumes the presidency of the European Union
Friday, urged Turkey to decrease troop presence in the north of the
divided island a day after Greek Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
called off plans to install Russian-made antiaircraft missiles.
Turkey had threatened military action to prevent their deployment.
	   ``The cancellation of the missiles has avoided a crisis,''
Turkey's Anatolia news agency quoted Denktash as saying. ``But, it
cannot be made into a bargaining issue for the reduction of Turkish
soldiers.''
	   Cyprus has been divided since 1974, when Turkey sent in troops
following a short-lived coup by supporters of union with Greece.
Some 35,000 Turkish troops are stationed in the northern breakaway
state, which is recognized only by Ankara.
	   Germany said a reduction of military presence by Turkey would
help build trust on Cyprus.
	   Clerides has said he would negotiate with Russian officials to
put the missiles instead on the Greek island of Crete instead, but
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem warned Wednesday that Turkey
might use force to block that proposal if it deemed them a security
threat.
	   (sf-cph)
</TEXT>
