<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Euro Dreams,0564 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greek officials brace for rough ride in euro quest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-The Euro &QL; 
 &UR; By ELENA BECATOROS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ At the birth of the euro, Greece is
outside looking in.
	   Plagued by loss-making state companies and stubborn inflation,
Greece is the only member of the 15-nation bloc that wanted to be
part of the single currency but couldn't meet the fiscal standards.
Britain, Denmark and Sweden have opted out for now.
	   But Premier Costas Simitis has made qualification by 2001 the
cornerstone of his socialist government's policy.
	   ``I want to repeat the government's pledge for the drachma's
cooperation in the euro zone,'' Greece's Finance Minister Yannos
Papantoniou said in Brussels, Belgium, on Thursday during a meeting
to set parity rates with the euro.
	   Greece must meet all criteria by the end of 1999 if it is to
qualify by Jan. 1, 2001. Officials fear staying out would make the
country an economic backwater in the EU.
	   ``Participation in the euro zone will be the culmination of a
long and painful effort by the Greek people for the creation of
conditions of development, prosperity and social justice,''
Papantoniou said.
	   The Greek economy has improved dramatically over the past few
years.
	   The 1999 budget seeks to reduce the general deficit to 1.9
percent of gross domestic product from an expected 2.2 percent at
the end of this year _ well below the qualification mark of 3
percent.
	   But the Greek financial newspaper Imerisia recently quoted the
rating agency Moody's as saying Greece could fail to qualify
because of delays in important changes such as selling off state
industries, reforming labor laws and rolling back government
economic controls.
	   Greek Finance Undersecretary Nikos Christodoulakis described the
Moody's report as too cautious and didn't take into account the
declining trend in government debt.
	   Inflation also remains a major challenge. The government has
reduced prices on some consumer goods and has attempted to restrict
wage increases in an attempt to cut inflation, which stood at 4.2
percent in November.
	   EU single currency criteria set an inflation ceiling based on
the top performing countries, expected to be about 2.5 percent next
year.
	   The government's unwavering focus on austerity and reforms have
led to serious backlashes from labor groups and others _ accustomed
to the patronage and worker-friendly policies of previous Socialist
administrations.
	   Unions have fought back with strikes and anti-government rallies
that at times have crippled transportation and commerce around
Greece. Walkouts were so frequent at the state carrier Olympic
Airways earlier this year that it led Greece's foreign minister to
quip that ``no logical person'' would travel on it.
	   Opposition officials warn that joining the euro shouldn't be an
aim in itself.
	   Entering economic and monetary union ``could have very important
advantages for Greece,'' the daily Exousia quoted former
conservative government economic advisor Giorgos Alogoskoufis as
saying.
	   ``But if until then necessary, serious structural reforms have
not taken place, such as the modernization of public utilities,
extensive privatizations, the opening of markets to competition,
the country will not be able to reap the benefits,'' he added.
</TEXT>
