<SLUG> BC-Japan-Economy, HFR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's leader says government will work hard to meet 1999
</HEADLINE>
forecast &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: EMBARGOED by source for release at 2000 GMT Thursday &QL; 
 &UR; By TODD ZAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi expressed hope
on Thursday that the world's second-largest economy would meet a
modest government growth target next year as he reiterated a pledge
to engineer a more convincing recovery by 2000.
	   Japan has slipped into its deepest recession in decades and
unemployment has hit a postwar high. The government estimates the
economy will shrink 2.2 percent in fiscal 1998, which ends in
March.
	   Obuchi said the new fiscal year which begins in April would be
better, but stopped short of promising a full-fledged economic
recovery.
	   ``We are making every effort to achieve our target of 0.5
percent growth,'' Obuchi said in a New Year's press conference.
	   The government's official target of 0.5 percent economic growth
for fiscal 1999 is its lowest forecast since World War II.
	   The prime minister was more optimistic about 2000.
	   ``Through the efforts of our people and the policies of the
government, we will definitely see success, I am certain we will
see clearly positive growth next year,'' he said.
	   He called on Japanese people to have more faith in government
efforts to revive the ailing economy.
	   ``There is no doubt that Japan's economy will recover. I think
what is needed is for the Japanese people to have confidence in our
country _ confidence in Japan,'' he said.
	   To try to hasten recovery, Japan's Cabinet last week unveiled a
draft budget for 1999 that will double the size of the annual
deficit as it pays for efforts to kickstart the nation's moribund
economy.
	   Obuchi said bad-loan problems at the nation's banks remained
Japan's biggest problem as the new year begins, but said recent
steps to inject public funds into ailing banks would soon begin to
fix the troubles. 	   
</TEXT>
