<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Spanish Preview </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No. 1 Mallorca faces bottom Extremadura and pressure steams around
</HEADLINE>
crisis-ridden Barcelona &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHANNA TUCKMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Four points clear atop the table, euphoric
Mallorca travels to meet straggling Extremadura Sunday in the
Spanish soccer league, while FC Barcelona and Real Madrid look to
restore tarnished reputations.
	   With 15 rounds played, Mallorca owes its 29 points to an almost
impenetrable defense that has let in only six goals and permitted
maximum profit from the 16 the team has scored.
	   Meanwhile, last-placed Extremadura _ with just 12 points from
three wins, three draws and nine losses _ is under pressure to
prove it deserves first division status.
	   But while few expect great things from Extremadura, followers of
the country's soccer powerhouses FC Barcelona and Real Madrid are
demanding dramatic comebacks from disappointing starts to the
season.
	   Languishing at No. 9 in the table, Barcelona has won only one of
its last five league matches and is submerged in a major crisis
with Dutch coach Louis Van Gaal hanging onto his job despite his
unpopularity with the fans.
	   ``No one understands why, with so many great players, we are
losing matches,'' said Barcelona's Dutch striker Patrick Kluivert
Thursday in sports daily El Mundo Deportivo.
	   ``We must beat Alaves to start the year on a good footing,''
said defender Sergi Barjuan in the paper, referring to Sunday's
league match at home to the lowly division newcomer.
	   But despite Sergi's assurances that ``little by little things
are getting back to normal,'' the atmosphere clearly remains tense.
	   Earlier this week club chairman Josep Nunez blamed the players
for the season's disappointments, that included a humiliatingly
early exit from the European Champions League.
	   This charge was publicly refuted with scarcely veiled bitterness
by Brazilian star striker Rivaldo.
	   Meanwhile, the other perennial Spanish superteam Real Madrid
also plays Sunday, at home to second-to-last placed Tenerife.
	   Although Madrid is still gunning to win its eighth European
Champions League title, the club has failed to sparkle in the
domestic league and currently lies seven points behind the leader
at No.8.
	   Madrid's Dutch coach Guus Hiddink will remember that his German
predecessor German Juup Heynckes was sacked at the end of last
season for finishing at a disappointing No. 4. This despite having
lead the team to a record seventh European Champions title.
	   In other matches Sunday, No.2 Celta welcomes No. 5 Oviedo in the
round's most evenly matched game.
	   Meanwhile, fourth placed Deportivo La Coruna travels to No. 11
Zaragoza, N. 6 Atletico plays away against lower-half Racing de
Santander and Athletic Bilbao in seventh place hosts No.15
Valladolid.
	   The draw also provides two lower-half battles pitting Villarreal
against Betis, and Expanyol against Salamanca while Saturday's only
match sees third-place Valencia host third-from bottom Salamanca.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
