<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin toasts the new year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Taking a day off from politics, President Boris
Yeltsin on Thursday called on Russians to meet 1999 with optimism
and pride in their country.
	   The president's taped New Year's Eve message, which is broadcast
across the nation just before midnight, was first shown in Russia's
Far East _ nine time zones ahead of Moscow.
	   ``What can I say: The year was difficult for the country, for
many of you, and for me, too. But New Year's Eve is always about
new hopes, new dreams, new plans,'' Yeltsin said, according to a
transcript released by the Interfax news agency.
	   Yeltsin voiced hopes for the most defenseless members of
society, ``so that our children will be happy and those who need
attention and care so much now should feel it.'' And he expressed
hope that Russians would always feel the ``dignity and greatness''
of their country.
	   He noted that the new millennium was just around the corner.
	   ``What kind of country enters it depends on each of us _ on our
talent and industriousness, our persistence and will, unity and
togetherness,'' Yeltsin said.
	   ``Yes, we're very different, but together, we're Russia.''
	   (ji)
