<HEADER>
w2039 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-NuclearWeap     12-31 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Nuclear Weapons </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Documents show Australia considered building A-bombs in 1968
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia, which has become one of
the world's most vocal opponents of nuclear weapons proliferation,
considered building up to 30 atomic bombs a year as recently as
1968, according to government documents declassified on Friday.
	   The Cabinet papers, released by Australia's National Archives,
show the government of Prime Minister John Gorton continued to
flirt with the nuclear option even just prior to the long-awaited
United Nations debate on the nuclear non-proliferation treaty.
	   The Cabinet deliberations show the government supported the
principle of the treaty in halting worldwide proliferation of
nuclear weapons as long as it did not close off Australian options
to build a bomb at some stage.
	   A submission from the Defense Department, considered by Cabinet
on March 26, 1968 raises the prospect that Australia could have
placed itself squarely at odds with the United States, which
co-sponsored the treaty with the Soviet Union.
	   Refusal to sign would have raised the prospect of American
pressure and sanctions halting supply of defense equipment.
	   ``The former may not be so important. The latter could affect
our ability to develop and maintain an effective delivery system,''
it said.
	   At that time Australian had no means of delivering nuclear
weapons. But one was on the way, the new U.S. F-111 bombers ordered
in 1963 but delayed because of technical problems.
	   Australia's Defense Department said refusal to sign the treaty
would be interpreted as an intent to develop nuclear weapons no
matter what declarations of peaceful purposes were made.
	   It concluded that refusal to sign really was not a viable
option.
	   But annexes and attachments to the defense submission show the
nuclear weapon option remained very much alive.
	   A document prepared by the Department of Supply and the
Australian Atomic Energy Commission assessed what a nuclear weapons
program could involve.
	   ``For a capital outlay of 100 million dollars Australia could
equip itself with the capability to produce annually sufficient
plutonium for 30 nominal 20 kiloton weapons at a cost of 13 million
dollars per year,'' it said.
	   It put total bomb development costs at some dlrs 144 million,
but without consideration of a delivery system.
	   The Cabinet made no mention of the bomb option. But it was
skeptical about whether the non-proliferation treaty would really
work as nuclear powers France and China had declared they would not
sign.
	   Following consultations with U.S. Secretary of State Dean Rusk,
Australia was left with no doubts that Washington regarded the
treaty as vitally important.
	   When it came to a decision in the U.N., Australia voted in favor
of the treaty. Officials had queried whether it would even attract
the 40 signatures needed to become reality.
	   Any reservations were swept away by a worldwide groundswell of
support which saw the U.S., Britain, Soviet Union and 59 other
countries sign up on July 1, 1968, the first day the treaty opened
for signatures.
	   Australia signed in 1970. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Nuclear Weapons; CT:i; 
