<SLUG> BC-Republic of Congo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2,000 villagers held `hostage' in rebel retreat
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with witness accounts by civilians from Linzola. Edits
to conform, adds byline. No pickup.
 &UR; By LOUIS OKAMBA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRAZZAVILLE, Republic of Congo (AP) _ The Ninja militia group
battling the Republic of Congo's government has retreated into two
villages near the capital where civilians were being held hostage,
witnesses said Thursday.
	   About 2,000 villagers, including women and children, were being
forced to stay in their homes in Djoumouna and Linzola, between 15
and 30 kilometers (10 to 20 miles) south of the capital of
Brazzaville, a senior military officer said on condition of
anonymity.
	   ``We have the means and the equipment necessary to dislodge the
militia, but we don't want to risk the chance of a civilian
massacre,'' the military official said. ``The rebels know that and
they are holding the civilians hostage.''
	   Among the hostages were eight stewards from the multi-national
passenger airline Air Afrique who had taken refuge in Linzola
during fighting last week in Brazzaville, witnesses said. There was
no immediate confirmation of the reports and Ninja leaders were
unavailable for comment.
	   A group of Linzola residents who sneaked away during the night
told journalists that at least 13 people, including 10 foreigners _
three of whom are Lebanese businessmen _ had been killed. Their
identities were unknown.
	   The witnesses also gave accounts of Ninja militiamen torturing
their captives and said around 80 civilians were known to have
escaped to Brazzaville.
	   There has been no fighting between the two groups since last
weekend, when the government says it drove many of the Ninjas into
hiding in mountains and jungle southwest of the capital.
	   Hostilities flared in early December between the Ninjas, linked
to ex-Prime Minister Bernard Kolelas, and President Denis
Sassou-Nguesso's personal Cobra militia.
	   Human rights and aid groups say the fighting has prompted tens
of thousands of civilians to flee their homes from Brazzaville and
towns in the southwest.
	   Unarmed residents have been killed, women raped and homes
destroyed since fighting broke out.
	   The hostilities are a reversal of a civil war last year that
ravaged Brazzaville and resulted in up to 10,000 deaths when
Sassou-Nguesso captured the presidency from Pascal Lissouba, a
sometime ally of Kolelas.
	   Sassou-Nguesso, the Republic of Congo's longtime Marxist
dictator who is now advocating capitalist reform, was ousted in the
country's first multiparty elections in 1992.
	   (lo-gam/ids) 	   
</TEXT>
