<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Christian Attack,0500 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hindu-Christian peace meetings held on New Year's Eve
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Christian missionaries and Hindu social
workers held peace meetings on New Year's Eve in villages in a
western state where mobs damaged one dozen churches and at least
one Hindu temple in religious violence over the past week.
	   ``Our theme was that we need peace immediately,'' said Rev. T.
Gaikwad in a telephone interview Thursday from Ahwa, a village in
the state of Gujarat, where the first clash occurred Christmas Day.
	   ``There should be peace throughout'' the region, he said.
	   Gaikwad said he sent representatives to three villages in a
hilly and remote part of Gujarat where clashes took place.
	   Men, women and children of the villages met in an open farm
field with Christian missionaries and representatives of two
militant Hindu parties blamed for some of the attacks, he said.
Details of the meetings were not immediately available because of
poor communications in the area.
	   Late Wednesday, five people were injured in fresh clashes in
Charsod village, some 300 kilometers (185 miles) northeast of
Bombay, police said. Some 50 militant Hindus burned down a
mud-and-thatch building serving as church in the village, police
said. Details were not immediately available.
	   The recent attacks began Christmas Day with scuffles between
Hindus and Christians. In subsequent days, mobs armed with iron
rods, bicycle chains and axes broke into makeshift churches and
prayer halls. The World Hindu Council, which goes by the Hindi
language initials VHP, alleged that at least one Hindu temple and
several Hindu villagers had been attacked by Christians in recent
days.
	   Prayer meetings originally scheduled for New Year's Day in the
villages had been canceled, following tension.
	   On Thursday, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee again condemned
the attacks and said he has asked the Gujarat government to take
stern action against those responsible for the incidents.
	   Christian organizations welcomed Vajpayee's comments.
	   India's nearly 1 billion population is mostly Hindu, and
Christians account for less than 2 percent of the figure.
	   For more than 100 years, Hindus and Christians across India have
lived in harmony. But in recent weeks, two small right-wing Hindu
groups that share an ideology with Vajpayee's governing party have
targeted churches, saying Christian missionaries have stepped up
conversion of poor, often illiterate villagers to their faith with
promises of jobs or money.
	   Christian missionaries admit conversations do take place, but
they deny that people are coerced, or given money or other
inducements.
	   The missionaries mostly work in remote, often inhospitable areas
where corrupt or inefficient government officials fail to carry out
development work such as building hospitals, schools or irrigation
canals. Christian groups are also known for the top quality schools
they run in urban centers.
</TEXT>
