</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-IOC-Bribes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC vows to overcome corruption scandals
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) _ The IOC declared Thursday it was
``strong enough'' to overcome the worst corruption crisis in modern
Olympic history.
	   In its year-end news letter, the IOC addressed the allegations
of bribery and extortion involving the bidding and selection
process for Olympic host cities.
	   ``Since its foundation in 1894, the International Olympic
Committee has been faced with problems of every nature, and it has
always succeeded in overcoming them by taking the right
decisions,'' the statement said.
	   ``This will remain true in the future. The Olympic movement is
strong enough to take up the challenge.''
	   The IOC, facing the worst ethics scandal in its 104-year
history, is conducting a high-level investigation into allegations
of bribery during Salt Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter
Games.
	   Salt Lake officials have acknowledged that 13 people, including
six relatives of IOC members, received nearly dlrs 400,000 in
scholarship payments during the bid.
	   IOC members also were given thousands of dollars worth of guns
and skis, and some received free medical treatments, including
plastic surgery.
	   IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch has promised to oust any
members found guilty of corruption.
	   The IOC inquiry is one of four investigations into the Salt Lake
scandal. Also investigating are the Justice Department, the U.S.
Olympic Committee and the Salt Lake organizing committee's ethics
board.
	   In addition to the Salt Lake case, the IOC has been stung by
allegations from one of its own top officials _ executive board
member Marc Hodler _ that corruption is commonplace in Olympic bid
campaigns.
	   (sw) 	   
</TEXT>
