<SLUG> BC-PEOPLE-Seychelles-Blair </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British prime minister, family spend quiet holiday in Seychelles
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VICTORIA, Seychelles (AP) _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and his family are spending their second quiet New Year's Eve in a
row on a small island called La Digue in the middle of the Indian
Ocean.
	   ``It is good to see Mr. Blair and his family returning to
Seychelles for all the right reasons _ to enjoy a holiday in a
relaxing atmosphere where well-known people are able to be left
alone to enjoy their holidays in peace and quiet,'' government
spokesman Gilbert Pool said Friday.
	   Blair is one of a growing number of politicians and celebrities
who have chosen the 92-island archipelago as a place to relax out
of sight of the media.
	   For the second year running, Blair, his wife Cherie and their
three children are staying at L'Union Self-Catering Bungalows
located on a working coconut plantation on La Digue.
	   The holiday home of Seychelles President France-Albert Rene is
nearby.
	   Pool said the government has no plans to host or encourage any
large-scale end-of-century celebrations in Seychelles next New
Year's Eve.
	   (sc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
