r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NewYear'sWorldRoundup     12-31 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Year's World Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian nations kick off New Year's celebrations with fireworks,
</HEADLINE>
revelry

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ People throughout Asia welcomed the Year of the
Rabbit with with displays of fireworks, official speeches and late
night pilgrimages to sacred shrines and temples.
	   Millions of Australians bid farewell to 1998 late Thursday by
watching a U.S. dlrs 1.2 million fireworks extravaganza which
bathed the harborside Sydney Opera House in pulses of green, red
and blue light.
	   Sydney celebrates every major holiday and event with fireworks,
but New Year's Eve is a pyrotechnic orgy, and this year's barrage
was a dress rehearsal for upcoming sky shows to mark next year's
welcome for the year 2000, and the summer Olympic Games in
September 2000.
	   More than a million people saw Sydney's night sky light up in
person, and many of the city's other 2.5 million viewed live TV
coverage of the annual festival.
	   Crowds cried ``Ooooh'' and ``Aaaaah!'' as combinations of
fireworks, some formations bigger than most downtown buildings, lit
the sultry southern summer night sky under low clouds.
	   In central Tokyo, crowds thronged Zojoji temple just before
midnight, waiting for a Buddhist monk to strike the temple bell 108
times to dispel the evils of the past year and usher in good luck
for the new year.
	   Much of the rest of Tokyo was eerily empty Thursday night,
deserted by urbanites returning to hometowns in the countryside for
the New Year's celebrations, the most important event on the
Japanese calendar.
	   In much of Asia, 1999 is the Year of the Rabbit, and Tokyo's
department stores were well stocked with calendars, cards and
knickknacks bearing rabbit images.
	   Shoppers packed Japanese supermarket aisles before many closed
for the three-day holiday, to snap up red snappers, special
``year-crossing'' noodles, rice cakes and the sweet black beans
that are customary fare on New Year's day.
	   In a more modern tradition, families around Japan gathered in
front of their TVs to watch one of the most popular programs of the
year, a nationally-broadcast singing contest featuring the
country's top entertainers in dazzling costumes.
	   In Thailand, many Bangkok residents gathered for parties in
skyscrapers to enjoy the views of fireworks displays. The newest
attraction this year was Baiyoke tower, the city's tallest
building. A sold out dinner party for 750 baht (dlrs 20) a ticket
was held on the top floor _ one of the few parts of the 77-story
structure open due to a deep economic slump.
	   For many Chinese, New Year's Eve is not nearly as important an
occasion as the Lunar New Year on Feb. 16 when hundreds of millions
of people head home for family reunions.
	   Still, television and radio audiences were treated to a rare
live prime time address by China's president Jiang Zemin, who was
upbeat in summing up 1998 and urged his people to be confident
about the future.
	   Indonesian President B.J. Habibie also delivered a nationwide
broadcast to cheer citizens struggling amid the Southeast Asian
country's worst economic downturn in decades.
	   In the Philippines, rebels joined a government effort to bring
down the number of people hurt during New Year's revelry by
ordering their forces not to fire guns to celebrate the start of
1999 _ an often deadly local tradition.
	   Philippine President Joseph Estrada has urged soldiers,
policemen and civilians to refrain from firing weapons too.
	   Dozens of Filipinos have been killed or injured by stray bullets
in recent New Year's celebrations. 	   
</TEXT>
