<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Economy,0331 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
National debt rises to 91.2 percent of the GDP in latest fiscal
</HEADLINE>
year &QL; 
 &UR; By AMIR ZIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan's national debt rose to 91.2
of the gross domestic product in the latest fiscal year, compared
to 90.2 percent the previous year, the nation's central bank
reported Thursday.
	   In the period from July 1997 to June 1998, external debt rose
dlrs 1.9 billion to dlrs 29.7 billion, or 49.5 percent of the GDP.
	   The central bank suggested government should reduce the debt by
selling property and using privatization proceeds of the state-run
units. Also, direct foreign investment should be encouraged to
reduce dependence on foreign debt, the report said.
	   World economic powers sanctioned Pakistan in May after the
nation held nuclear tests. As sanctions ate away at the nation's
reserves, Pakistan scrambled to raise money from global donor
agencies to avoid defaulting on its obligations of external debt,
worth dlrs 32 billion at present.
	   The gross domestic product grew 5.4 percent, up from a meager
1.3 percent in the previous year. Solid growth in the agricultural
and industrial sectors helped boost the measure.
	   Inflation fell to 7.8 percent in the 1997-98 period, from 11.8
the previous year. The nation's foreign exchange reserves declined
by about dlrs 423 million.
	   The bank said poor revenue collection also increased
difficulties for the economy.
	   ``A narrow tax base, inefficient tax collection system, tax
evasion ... were all responsible for the inadequate revenue
performance,'' the report said.
	   On the expenditure side, Pakistan trimmed its development budget
to 3.2 percent of the GDP in 1997-98 from 3.4 percent the previous
year, while the defense budget fell to 4.9 percent from 5.1
percent.
	   The interest payment on debt increased to 6.9 percent of the GDP
compared to last year's 6.4 percent, the report said.
</TEXT>
