<HEADLINE>
After months of deadlock, Mexican Congress OKs 1999 budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to ADD final Congressional approval. Picks
up 6th graf pvs, ``At the...'' &QL; 
 &UR; By ADOLFO GARZA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ With only hours to spare, Mexico's Congress
finally approved the 1999 budget Thursday, narrowly saving the
nation from a constitutional crisis.
	   The months-old deadlock between the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party and four opposition groups was broken late
Wednesday when the opposition-led House of Deputies approved the
package's tax bill by a 349-131 vote.
	   The Senate, controlled by the ruling party, approved the bill
early today and, hours later, the Deputies approved the package's
spending bill. That bill does not need Senate approval.
	   The budget was a compromise between the ruling party, known as
the PRI, and the conservative National Action Party. The leftist
Democratic Revolution Party, the second-largest bloc in the House
of Deputies, voted against the tax bill along with the tiny Labor
and Green parties.
	   After 69 years, the PRI lost its House majority in mid-term
elections last year. The deadline for approving the budget was Dec.
31, but the constitution does not specify what would have happened
if it had not been approved.
