<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Press Freedom </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fewer journalists killed in 1998, says press watchdog
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Fewer journalists were killed in 1998 than in
recent years, a French press watchdog said Thursday. But it warned
that journalists investigating corruption were in danger in many
countries.
	   In 1998, 19 journalists were killed worldwide, the report by
Reporters without Borders said. It said 487 others were arrested
and that 697 were physically abused or threatened.
	   The drop in the number of deaths was attributed in part to a
drop in fatalities for reporters covering the former Yugoslavia,
Chechnya and Algeria.
	   The group said reporters investigating corruption by public
officials had been killed in Bangladesh, Brazil, Colombia, Mexico,
the Philippines, Russia and Thailand.
	   Since 1994, 103 journalists _ including 48 in Rwanda and 18 in
Algeria _ have been killed.
	   Some 93 journalists were currently in jail as a result of their
work, compared to 90 last year, the report said, highlighting cases
in Ethiopia, China, Syria, Burma. It also said torture was
commonplace in Turkish prisons.
	   Reporters Without Borders said the independent press was facing
increasing difficulties in Pakistan and Congo.
	   However, the report praised Indonesia, where it said no
reporters had been jailed since the fall of President Suharto, and
Nigeria, where it said the number of jailed reporters had fallen
from 13 to two since the death of dictator Gen. Sani Abacha in
June.
	   (ip-dgs)	   
</TEXT>
