<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 4th Ld-Writethru,0815 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Khmer Rouge leaders begin grand tour of country they destroyed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recasts, UPDATES with comments from human rights groups,
opposition leader &QL; 
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SIHANOUKVILLE, Cambodia (AP) _ Under government protection, two
former Khmer Rouge leaders started a luxurious tour Thursday of the
country they helped destroy in blood and terror in the 1970s, and
complained the media were ruining their New Year holiday.
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, members of the inner circle of the
late Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot, returned to mainstream society
this week after decades at jungle guerrilla bases and sealed a
defection deal with Prime Minister Hun Sen.
	   Ordinary Cambodians showed no sign of taking to the streets to
settle scores with their bloodstained former rulers, but VIP
treatment accorded them by the government fed growing, vocal anger
among human-rights and democracy groups.
	   ``It is a contempt for human life and a mockery of the memory
those million victims of Khmer Rouge atrocities,'' the Khmer
Institute for Democracy said in a statement.
	   Opposition leader Sam Rainsy praised King Norodom Sihanouk for
refusing to grant royal amnesty to the men, saying his move would
help ``end the culture of impunity that makes Cambodia a country of
`thieves, gangsters and assassins.'''
	   Hun Sen has assured the pair that he will not prosecute them for
crimes against humanity, saying the pardon would bring peace to the
country. But the Khmer Rouge civil war is already extinct. Many
Cambodians see the deal as pointless and want the pair tried for
genocide.
	   The pair have told a news conference that they were ``very
sorry'' but refused to take personal responsibility and invited
survivors to ``let bygones be bygones.''
	   For once fanatically rabid Maoist revolutionaries, they appeared
to revel in a bourgeois vacation.
	   After basking in VIP treatment in Phnom Penh for two days, they
traveled in luxury cars to the seaside resort of Sihanoukville,
first leg of a tour that will take them to the ancient Angkor
temples and their home provinces.
	   Along the roads are memorials stacked with bones and skulls of
thousands of their victims, irrigation ditches dug by hand under
the murderous eye of Khmer Rouge overseers and fields strewn with
mines from years of civil war.
	   They checked in at Sihanoukville's best hotel and took rooms
with a view of the Gulf of Thailand. Reporters staked out the hotel
and the pair kept to their rooms with the shades drawn, eating a
room-service lunch of crab and fish.
	   Long Norin, a spokesman, complained that the presence of
journalists was marring their stay and that as long as the press
remained, ``They will not leave their rooms.''
	   Khieu Samphan, 67, his hair dyed black during months on the run
in an attempt at disguise as Khmer Rouge territory fell under
government control, finally appeared with Nuon Chea to take a tour
with local officials.
	   ``Excuse me please, I would like to rest a little bit,'' Khieu
Samphan said. ``I have already said what needed to be said.''
	   A receptionist said the hotel was glad for their business.
Tourism had dried up after a shipment of toxic waste from a Taiwan
plastics factory was discovered in Sihanoukville a few weeks ago.
	   The deal the two men are receiving from Hun Sen has shaken hopes
that leaders of the bloody Khmer Rouge rule will ever face justice.
	   Dimming hopes for prosecution now seem to rest with the United
Nations, which can pass resolutions to try the Khmer Rouge leaders
overseas through an as-yet-uncreated international tribunal.
	   The United Nations recently sent experts to assess evidence
against senior Khmer Rouge members and offer recommendations for a
tribunal, either overseas or in Cambodia.
	   Thomas Hammarberg, the top U.N. human rights officer for
Cambodia, said the defections did not change the plans and that the
recomendations would soon be presented to the government.
	   Hammarberg expressed hope for a ``constructive discussion.
Considering the scale and the brutality of the Khmer Rouge crimes,
genuine healing in Cambodia will be extremely difficult without a
justice process.''
	   Denying Hun Sen a measure of legitimacy, King Norodom Sihanouk
has refused to provide amnesty because of ``undeniable discontent''
among a majority of Cambodians. Sihanouk said the international
community had ``the perfect right'' to judge the men.
	   No matter what the United Nations does, Hun Sen's cooperation
would be needed to arrest them.
	   The Khmer Rouge won a civil war in 1975 and forced the
population to toil in agricultural collectives. One Cambodian in
five died of overwork, starvation, disease and executions.
	   They were overthrown in 1979 by a Vietnamese invasion, but
fought a long guerrilla war.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
