<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Serb premier, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnian Serb president names new premier-designate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS comments from former President Biljana Plavsic,
Socialists
 &UR; By IRENA GAJIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ In an effort to end a
political deadlock, the Bosnian Serb president Thursday named a
moderate as the new premier-designate, after a previous hardline
candidate failed to win parliamentary approval.
	   But only hours after the candidacy of Brane Miljus was
announced, his own Party of Independent Social-Democrats rejected
the selection, saying the president made the decision without
consulting party leaders.
	   Miljus had accepted the selection by President Nikola Poplasen,
who named him in an apparent effort to find a compromise after
months of political dispute between Bosnian Serb moderates and
hard-liners over the premier's post.
	   The Social-Democrats are run by current pro-Western Premier
Milorad Dodik and are part of a wider coalition of moderate
parties. In a statement faxed to The Associated Press, the party
said Miljus must turn down the mandate or face unspecified
consequences.
	   But the selection of the 47-year-old Miljus, a native of
Sarajevo, might be welcomed by international officials, who have
sought to maintain a moderate government in the Serb-controlled
half of the country. There was no immediate reaction from
international officials in Bosnia.
	   Miljus' appointment still must be approved by parliament. No
date for the vote has been set and it was not clear whether Miljus
could win. Neither of the two bitterly opposed camps gained a
majority in parliament following September general elections.
	   Poplasen, a hard-liner, first named Dragan Kalinic as premier,
but Kalinic failed to win parliamentary approval. Kalinic is a
close aide of Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb wartime leader
indicted by the international war crimes tribunal.
	   Moderates insisted that Dodik remain premier, which the
hard-liners refused. Miljus' selection is seen as a compromise, but
the reaction by Social-Democrats indicated it was not the result of
an agreement between the two sides.
	   Former President Biljana Plavsic, a moderate, told the SRNA news
agency she was ``shocked'' by Miljus' candidacy. She claimed his
selection was masterminded by Serbia, where President Slobodan
Milosevic remains in power after fomenting the Bosnian war.
	   The Socialist Party, the Bosnian Serb branch of Milosevic's
Socialists, cautiously welcomed Miljus' candidacy. While Poplasen's
decision was a surprise, it was ``a step ahead,'' the party said in
a statement.
	   The hardline Serb Democratic Party, formerly run by Karadzic,
has announced its support of Miljus.
	   International officials have threatened to cut financial aid to
Bosnian Serbs if a hard-liner becomes premier.
	   Miljus pledged in a statement Thursday to maintain close ties
with the international community and honor the US-brokered Dayton
peace agreements for Bosnia, signed in 1995.
	   The peace accords, which ended more than three years of
fighting, divided Bosnia roughly in two, with Serbs controlling one
half and the Muslim-Croat controlling the other. The country has
joint central institutions.
	   (ig/jg/scl)
</TEXT>
