<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Paramilitary Chief,0299 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top Colombian paramilitary leader survived rebel attack, politician
</HEADLINE>
says &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Colombia's top paramilitary leader is
alive, a politician close to the feared rightist militias said
Thursday, following unconfirmed reports that the militia chief had
been killed in an attack by leftist rebels.
	   Carlos Castano survived the attack this week on his tightly
guarded mountain hideout in northern Cordoba state, said Max
Alberto Morales, a longtime intermediary between the militias and
the government.
	   ``It's been confirmed that he's alive...that he's still in the
area and that he hasn't spoken for security reasons,'' Morales told
The Associated Press in a telephone interview.
	   Morales said his information came from sources ``very close'' to
Castano, who is wanted by prosecutors in death squad killings of
human rights activists and leftist politicians.
	   Castano, 34, heads the United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia,
an umbrella grouping of the militias originally formed by drug
traffickers and landowers to combat guerrilla extortion and
kidnappings.
	   In a radio interview earlier in the week, Morales said Castano
had ``disappeared'' and had not been heard from for 24 hours. The
comments sparked rampant speculation that Castano was killed by the
rebels during the attack on his base, known as Nudo del Paramillo.
	   In two days of cruel fighting in the area beginning Monday, at
least three men were beheaded, their mutilated bodies shown in
gruesome television reports.
	   The army and local officials charge the guerrillas massacred
dozens of civilians, accusing them of supporting the paramilitary
groups. The burned and disemembered bodies of 14 victims, including
three young girls, have been found.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
