<SLUG> BC-India-Clashes,0143 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police clamp curfew in southern Indian town following Hindu-Muslim
</HEADLINE>
clashes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGALORE, India (AP) _ Police clamped an overnight curfew
Thursday in a city in southwestern India following Hindu-Muslim
clashes that killed five people and were sparked by an incident in
which Muslim men teased a Hindu woman.
	   At least 50 people were injured since violence broke out Tuesday
night in Suratkal, a coastal town in Karnataka state, police said.
	   Tension spread Thursday night to the nearby city of Mangalore
and state police chief T. Srinivasulu imposed a curfew there until
dawn.
	   Since Tuesday, mobs have attacked Hindus and Muslims in their
houses. Three Muslims and one Hindu have been stabbed to death in
the fighting. Police fired bullets on Wednesday to disperse
rioters, killing one Hindu protester in Suratkal.
</TEXT>
