w2128 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy 4thLd-Writethru   12-31 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's inflation hits 84 percent for 1998
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS, ADDS additional economic indicators. Trims.
CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By JUDITH INGRAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government pinned a number Thursday to the
weakening ruble, announcing that its value had dropped almost 70
percent over the last four months in relation to the U.S. dollar.
	   And it announced that annual inflation, which appeared under
control until the financial crisis hit in August, reached 84.4
percent in 1998.
	   Russia is caught in the worst economic slide since the Soviet
collapse seven years ago, sparked by the Asian financial crisis,
falling world prices for oil _ Russia's biggest export earner _ and
successive governments' chronic inability to finance expenditures.
	   In 1998, the country's gross domestic product shrank 5 percent
and industrial production by 5.5 percent, the Economy Ministry said
Thursday, according to the Interfax news agency. Foreign trade
declined by 13.6 percent in the first 11 months of the year, and
exports to countries outside the former Soviet Union dropped 17.6
percent from last year, reaching dlrs 57.7 billion, the ministry
said.
	   Imports dropped by a quarter in 1998, the State Customs
Committee estimated.
	   After the government of Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko devalued
the ruble in August, its value dropped from about 6 to the U.S.
dollar to more than 20 to the dollar _ almost a 70 percent drop,
the Economy Ministry said.
	   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov warned government workers that
their salaries would not be increased until the incomes of the
country's poorest citizens began rising.
	   ``I don't think ... it would be correct to raise salaries for
ourselves without raising the salaries of the poorest citizens,''
Primakov said.
	   ``We cannot turn Russia into an economically prosperous country
in just a few months, but it's our duty to do as much as
possible,'' he was quoted as saying by Interfax.
	   Nearly one-third of Russia's 150 million people are living below
the official poverty line, the government said recently.
	   Meanwhile, a Russian court has declared bankrupt what was one of
the country's largest banks, clearing the way for the first
liquidation of a major bank since the crisis broke in August.
	   The Moscow Arbitration Court ruled this week that Tokobank was
bankrupt and that its assets should be distributed among creditors,
The Moscow Times reported.
	   The bank was once among the 20 largest in Russia, but now has
debts of 7.5 billion rubles (dlrs 363 million) and assets of just
3.4 billion rubles (dlrs 165 million), the newspaper reported.
	   Many of Russia's approximately 1,500 banks have been hard hit by
the financial crisis and have either closed or are providing only
limited services.
	   In another development, the Central Bank said Russia's hard
currency reserves stood at dlrs 12.3 billion as of Dec. 25.
	   (pvs/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
