<HEADLINE>
Slovak official seeks talks on NATO integration
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ Slovakia's new government is
interested in opening talks with NATO that will ultimately lead to
alliance membership for the Central European nation, the foreign
minister said Thursday.
	   Eduard Kukan acknowledged to journalists that NATO is unlikely
to invite new countries to begin accession talks at the April
summit at which the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland gain
membership.
	   But the foreign minister said he hopes for such talks in the
nearest future, the Czech news agency CTK reported.
	   Slovakia's chances of joining both NATO and the European Union
improved significantly when September parliamentary elections
resulted in a pro-Western government ousting that of authoritarian
Vladimir Meciar.
	   However, Defense Minister Pavol Kanis admitted that the new
government has yet to stabilize the country's internal political
situation _ a condition of NATO entry _ CTK reported.
	   He said that despite a lack of financial resources, the Slovak
army has kept high standards, and plans a reorganization next year.
