<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Mandela Message </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mandela sends last New Year's message as SAfrican president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: EMBARGOED for use until 1800GMT &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ In his last New Year's message
before leaving office, President Nelson Mandela on Thursday
challenged South Africans to continue working together to solve the
problems of poverty and corruption that are the legacy of decades
of apartheid.
	   Mandela, 80, will step down after national elections in 1999,
when Deputy President Thabo Mbeki is expected to succeed him. The
ruling party, African National Congress, is supported by most black
voters.
	   ``The New Year will bring many changes,'' Mandela said in the
four-minute broadcast message. ``They will depend on our working
together to realize our dream.''
	   He also sounded a warning that the elections _ the country's
second democratic vote since 1994 _ should not divide the country.
	   ``However robust the coming election campaign, we must emerge
still more united,'' he said.
	   The message was prerecorded. Mandela is on holiday in Mozambique
with his new wife, Graca Machel, who is Mozambican.
	   A date has not yet been set for the election, expected to be
held between May and July 1999.
	   The task started by Mandela, to redress the imbalances created
by more than four decades of apartheid, will fall to Mbeki.
	   Mbeki, 56, spent more than 30 years in exile, leaving South
Africa before his father, Govan Mbeki, was jailed for life with
Mandela in 1964.
	   Last weekend Mandela and Govan Mbeki were guests of honour at a
gathering at the Mbeki village of Ngcingwane in the Eastern Cape
for a traditional cleansing ceremony by his MaZizi clan to prepare
the younger Mbeki to lead the country.
	   More academic and less relaxed than Mandela, Mbeki is expected
to work towards an ``African Renaissance'' _ an effort to encourage
the continent to move away from war, poverty and dictatorship and
towards democracy and development.
	   Leaders of other political parties painted bleak pictures for
the New Year.
	   The leader of the conservative white Freedom Front, General
Constand Viljoen, slammed the ANc for being obsessed with power and
unable to curb crime and unemployment.
	   The liberal Democratic Party urged South Africans to vote in the
election and to vote on the basis of the track records of the
various parties.
	   The National Party which created apartheid and ruled South
Africa for more than 40 years urged citizens to unite against crime
and poverty and to vote to ensure effective multi-party democracy.
	   (pr)
</TEXT>
