w2167 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-EuroStamp     12-31 0198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Euro Stamp </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
France prints its first euro stamp
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ France printed its first postage stamp denominated
in euros on Friday several minutes after the official exchange rate
between the new single currency and the franc was announced.
	   The new stamp, worth 3 francs or .46 euros, still has the
picture of Marianne, the symbol of the French republic, on the
front.
	   But on the red background, the ``e'' that symbolizes the euro is
also present in white on the new stamp with the euro value. The
value in French francs is now printed in blue.
	   The new stamps were to be delivered Thursday evening to France's
main post offices. The stamp will be on sale New Year's day at the
Postal Museum in Paris.
	   The rest of the country will have to wait until Saturday when
the post office reopens after the New Year's holiday to purchase
their first stamps in euros.
	   During 1999, the French post office plans to stop making stamps
denominated only in francs and introduce stamps with both the franc
and the euro value.
	   In the year 2002, when the franc disappears altogether, stamps
will be denominated only in euros.
	   (parf-dgs)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
