<SLUG> BC-The Euro, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Euro seen boosting unity as well as, economy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS; UPDATES with fresh quotes, details
 &UR; AP photos, graphics available
 &UR; By PAUL AMES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Europe's leaders proclaimed a new era
Thursday as 11 nations, including the continent's biggest economic
powers, merged currencies to create the euro, a shared money they
say will boost business, underpin unity and strengthen their role
in world affairs.
	   ``If the postwar era ended nine years ago with the fall of the
Berlin Wall, then our future begins on Jan. 1, 1999,'' German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder wrote in the Handelsblatt business
daily.
	   At the stroke of midnight on New Year's Eve, after years of
preparation, the euro becomes the common currency of Germany,
France, Italy, Spain, the Netherlands, Belgium, Austria, Portugal,
Finland, Ireland and Luxembourg.
	   The event was hailed as a historic turning point, creating a
powerful new force in the world economy and fulfilling the post-war
dreams of union among nations whose divisions twice this century
dragged the planet into it's bloodiest wars.
	   ``Europe is finishing the century by sending a message of
peace,'' said Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Ciampi. ``The
conflicts that have so often gripped our continent are a thing of
the past.''
	   Finance ministers from the 11 nations gathered at European Union
headquarters in Brussels to fix the parities at which their
currencies were irreversibly locked to form the euro.
	   The new currency is worth worth 1.95583 German marks, 6.55957
French francs, 1936.27 Italian lire, 166.386 Spanish pesetas. When
markets open after the long holiday weekend, the euro is expected
to start trading at about dlrs 1.17, 133 Japanese yen and 70
British pence.
	   The ministers celebrated by popping corks shaped like the euro's
``e'' symbol from nine-liter (18.9-pint) champagne bottles, then
schoolchildren launched 3,000 blue balloons into the gray skies
above Brussels.
	   Although euro notes and coins won't be issued to replace Irish
pounds, Portuguese escudos, Austrian schillings and the rest until
2002, the new currency will immediately come into use for non-cash
transactions ranging from government bond issues to simple credit
card purchases.
	   Thousands of financial sector workers were set to spend the New
Year's break adapting computer systems and trading floors to the
new currency and converting stocks, bonds and bank accounts into
euros.
	   From Thursday, francs, marks and the rest will no longer be
traded in foreign exchange markets. Equities and bonds will be
quoted in euros. Bank transfers and business deals will
increasingly be in the new money.
	   Participating nations say that all that will give a boost to
business by creating a seamless market of 292 million citizens were
companies can operate without exchange costs or currency jitters.
	   Representing 20 percent of world economic output and 18 percent
of world trade, the euro-zone will be a powerful player in the
world economy. For the first time in decades, the U.S. dollar will
have a rival as the currency of choice for world trade and
government reserves.
	   ``The euro becomes the strong arm of the strongest economic
region of the world,'' Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima said in
Vienna.
	   Euroland governments stressed the currency was about more than
just economics.
	   ``From Lisbon to Helsinki, from Paris to Vienna, the euro is a
remarkable symbol of our common identity,'' said French Finance
Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn. ``Tomorrow I won't be any less
French ... but we will all be a little more European.''
	   Although citizens will only fill their purses and pocketbooks
with euros in three years, they'll start to become familiar with
the new currency immediately. Euro figures will appear alongside
national currencies on pay checks, phone bills and bank statements.
	   The latest EU polls published in September showed 66 percent of
citizens in the euro-zone supporting the common currency.
	   ``This is a good moment, the future is with the euro,'' said
schoolteacher Blandine Barnier in the French city of Lyon, adding
that her 10-year-old pupils already know what to expect. ``The
children are really aware of the euro, they travel a lot around
Europe and know what it's about.''
	   From Jan. 1, consumers will see prices marked in euros making it
easier to shop across frontiers, and they'll be able to buy in
euros using checks or credit cards. But they'll still have to
change money for cross-border cash purchases.
	   Ministers stressed that the currency union needed to be backed
up quickly with progress to secure still greater European
cooperation in other fields such as foreign affairs and defense.
	   Such talk of closer political integration, will fuel
euro-skeptic opinion in those countries that have stayed out of the
monetary union through fears of loosing national independence.
	   ``Britain must stay clear of this great fiasco,'' said Teddy
Taylor, a veteran lawmaker with Britain's opposition Conservative
Party.
	   Britain's Labor government has said it will try to persuade
voters to back joining the euro, probably early next decade.
Denmark's Finance Minister Marianne Jelved went a step further
Thursday, saying her country will likely hold a referendum on
joining before 2001.
	   Her Greek counterpart repeated his government's determination to
to join by Jan. 1, 2001.
	   ``Participation in the euro area will be the crowning of many
years of effort by the Greek people,'' said Finance Minister Yannos
Papantoniou.
 &UR; (pa-ju)
</TEXT>
