<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Wenger-Cheat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arsenal manager rips Charlton player over red card
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger has accused Charlton
midfielder Neil Redfearn of cheating to get Gunners' midfielder
Patrick Vieira sent off in a Premier League game last Monday.
	   Vieira received a red card at The Valley after Redfearn fell
down clutching his face after an apparent elbow by the Arsenal
midfielder.
	   Wenger said Thursday he is convinced after viewing replays that
Vieira only elbowed his opponent in the chest and that Redfearn
should be punished for play-acting and committing the initial foul,
a tackle from behind.
	   ``My thought is that Patrick didn't deserve to be sent off and
that Neil Redfearn cheated the referee,'' Wenger said. ``Usually I
think Redfearn is an honest type but on that occasion maybe
Charlton wanted so much to win the game that he was ready for
everything to get him sent off. I don't think his behavior was
fair.''
	   Wenger admitted that Vieira should have been shown the yellow
card for using his elbow to ``push back'' Redfearn, even though he
insists that the combative Frenchman is targeted by officials due
to his reputation.
	   ``If one of them should have had the red card, it is Redfearn,''
the French manager said. ``If the conclusion from that incident is
that Patrick has the red card and Redfearn the yellow, I don't see
the justice.
	   ``The first foul was from Redfearn and it was a very bad one as
it was from the back. The second thing is that he went down without
being touched.
	   ``This happened because it is Patrick but he's an honest player.
He's said he didn't want to hurt him, he just reacted to push the
arm away and he doesn't know what to do any more in a game.''
	   It was Vieira's fourth red card since joining Arsenal. He
received an automatic three-match ban for the offense.
	   Arsenal has asked referee Uriah Rennie to review the red card,
but Wenger said, ``He just seems not to care and thinks that he's
right.''
	   Redfearn insisted Thursday that his conscience was clear and
that he was not play-acting to get Vieira sent off during
Charlton's 1-0 defeat.
	   ``I didn't want Patrick to be sent off,'' he said. ``I would
never want to do that to a fellow professional. I think he's a
fantastic player and I'm disappointed how it's turned out.
	   ``I went down but I actually got straight back up, I didn't want
the lad to get sent off, no way. I actually got booked and I don't
know what for.''
	   Wenger condemned the growing number of incidents of diving and
feigning injury in the Premiership.
	   ``It's growing in England,'' he said. ``It's not huge compared
to other countries but it's becoming bigger and bigger, and there's
already more cases in the Premier League than in Division One.
	   ``Maybe some foreign players have brought more diving into the
country but some English players have picked it up very quickly.
	   ``I don't like it, whether it's an English player or a foreign
player. I like people who put their foot in and are aggressive on
the field but who don't behave like cheats.''
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
