<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fighting near capital reported in Sierra Leone
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with ECOMOG saying rebels driven back from hills. ADDS
denial that rebels had taken Lunsar town. Edits to conform. No
pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Loyalist forces exchanged
artillery fire with rebel fighters near Sierra Leone's capital on
Thursday, amid reports the insurgents were advancing on the city
from the east.
	   Diplomats and Defense Ministry officials who spoke on condition
of anonymity said heavy shelling rocked the hills south of Freetown
near the Hastings military airfield.
	   An senior commander with the West African defense force known as
ECOMOG said the coalition force had driven the rebels back from
their positions in the hills.
	   There were no immediate reports of casualties, but thousands of
civilians in the area fled to Freetown, about 20 kilometers (12
miles) to the north.
	   Rebel fighters from the Revolutionary United Front infiltrated
the hills in recent weeks and have been warning of an imminent
attack on the city itself.
	   The shelling comes as RUF rebels continued to push toward
Freetown from the east, where on Wednesday they reportedly overran
the town of Lunsar, about 65 kilometers (40 miles) from the
capital.
	   The ECOMOG commander denied Lunsar was under rebel control, but
said insurgent forces were in the area. The capital has been cut
off from large portions of Sierra Leone's east and north, where
rebel ambushes have made travel on the roads very hazardous.
	   The RUF has been making swift advances in recent days,
recapturing ground lost to ECOMOG since February, when they were
driven from Freetown after the ouster of Sierra Leone's military
junta.
	   The Nigerian-led West African force have been withdrawing from
positions in the countryside to consolidate defensive positions
around Freetown, a second ECOMOG official told The Associated Press
on condition he not be named.
	   ECOMOG troops were hailed as heroes in 10 months ago when they
drove the rebels and the junta from power. The coalition defense
force successfully battled the rebels away from the city and helped
restore the country's elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
	   Kabbah was deposed in a military coup in May 1997, but returned
to power in March of this year.
	   The rebel, waging an intermittent guerrilla war in the
countryside for the past seven years have been accused a widespread
atrocities. Countless villagers have been maimed, tortured or
murdered by the rebels, relief workers and missionaries say.
	   The rebels have demanded Kabbah resign and are calling for
mediation with the government through the Organization of African
Unity.
	   (var/ids)
</TEXT>
