<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/31/1998 13:34:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2233 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EditorialRoundup     12-31 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Editorial Roundup,0913 </SLUG>

 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Here are excerpts from editorials in publications in various
countries:
	   -0-
	   La Repubblica, Rome, on the introduction of the euro:
	   A long and patient work process comes to an end with the launch
the Euro. With the arrival of the new money comes a fresh symbol of
European unity. For the eleven countries involved, it will also
represent a new political structure.
	   The assembling of the strength of these countries improves the
economic situation of Europe and makes life easier for all European
citizens. With a population of 290 million and representing
one-fifth of the planet's production, this new ``Euro Zone'' will
be an international economic focal point. ...
	   Since any decision made by one member-state will effect the
entire financial European market, each country will have justified
interests in the actions of the other members. This need for trust
will also help to harmonize Europe. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   Giornale del Popolo, Lugano, Switzerland, on Clinton
impeachment:
	   The long-term consequences of the crisis in the U.S. presidency
and the final phase of the euro's introduction will probably be the
most important elements of world news in 1999.
	   John Kennedy, to give an illustrious example, was no less
unfaithful to his wife and no less given to amorous adventures than
Bill Clinton.
	   However, this disorder in his private life had no effect
whatsoever on his political career. ...
	   Clinton, in contrast, risks spending the last year of his
presidency fighting his impeachment, brought about by a legal
ambush launched by his Republican enemies. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   The Mirror, London, on rescue attempt in Yemen:
	   Why did it end so tragically? In the bloody wake of the Yemeni
kidnapping catastrophe, that is the question crying out for an
answer. The region has been plagued by kidnappings but they have
invariably been resolved peacefully. The authorities in the past
acted with tact, and the kidnappers appeared almost moderate in
their demands. Sometimes they called for nothing more outrageous
than better schools and hospitals. Early yesterday, Britain's
ambassador in the Yemen said he expected the hostages to be
well-treated. So what went so terribly wrong? Was outside pressure
put on the authorities to take swift action? ... Was this a
courageous rescue attempt that averted greater loss of life, or a
terrible and avoidable blunder? For the moment the families of the
victims will be too stunned to ask such questions. But sooner
rather than later they will be asked. Then they must be answered.
	    &UR; ___
	   The Express, London, on rescue attempt in Yemen:
	   Neither the British nor the Yemeni governments come out of
yesterday's tragedy in the Middle East well. The Foreign Office
seemed to be in the dark about the events which led to the killing
of the tourists and left it up to the tour company which arranged
their visit to contact the relatives of those held hostage. As
events went horribly wrong, officials were unable to shed any light
on what had happened.
	   For their part, the Yemenis gave muddled accounts. ... The
families of those murdered deserve at the very least a clear
account of what happened. It would be better if it came from the
Yemeni or British government rather than, belatedly, the released
hostages.
	    &UR; ___
	   The Daily Telegraph, London, on the Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race:
	   The news from Australia for British sportsmen encompassed the
extremes of triumph and tragedy yesterday. In Melbourne, the
England (cricket) team snatched a glorious Test victory from what
had seemed certain defeat. In Tasmania, meanwhile, the death toll
in the Sydney-Hobart yacht race was officially declared to have
reached six, including one Briton, the Olympic sailor Glyn Charles.
	   That the race turned into a tragedy should not be allowed to
obscure the bravery both of those who took part and those who
mounted one of the most extensive and professional air-sea rescue
operations ever when the storm struck. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   The Guardian, London, on Iraq:
	   The bombing of Iraq has shattered more than anti-aircraft
batteries, Republican Guards barracks, and tank repair shops. It
has shattered the established policies of the U.S. and of Iraq.
America's policy of containment through inspection lies in ruins.
Iraq's policy of breaking out of sanctions through cooperation and
concealment is a thing of the past. Its demands have grown to the
point where it seems about to repudiate the legitimacy of any
constraints on its behavior at all. Its decision to fire on U.S.
and British planes patrolling the no-fly zones shows Baghdad in a
confrontation which can only undermine its diplomatic objectives.
...
	    &UR; ___
	   Frankfurter Rundschau, Frankfurt, Germany, on Iraq:
	   No goal, nothing. At least not a political one, and still
continuously new targets are sighted in on. The war in the Gulf
continues as a military skirmish. Iraq's President Saddam Hussein
makes good on his threats not to stick any longer to rules laid on
by the United Nations or the (NATO) alliance. ... He anticipates
that (the sanctions) will never be lifted _ at least not as long as
he sits at the lever of power, if the United States has its way.
... Politically strengthened through operation ``Desert Fox,''
which was supposed to punish him, he no longer recognizes the
no-flight zones in north and south Iraq and sees the flight patrols
as acts of espionage. And the United States? They let themselves
become so upset by him that they immediately hit back _ just as
Saddam wanted. Now he can again advertise for himself, not only in
his own country, but also amongst the neighbors, who watch the U.S.
action in Iraq with astonishment and recognize no political policy,
but only blind revenge.
	    &UR; ___
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Editorial Roundup; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
