<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Editorial Roundup, 1st Add,0865 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: blind revenge.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Algemeen Dagblad, Rotterdam, Netherlands, on Cambodia:
	   It is unacceptable that the Cambodian mass murderers Khieu
Samphan and Nuon Chea can enjoy their old age without punishment.
These associates of the bloodthirsty Pol Pot, who masterminded the
killings of almost 2 million Cambodians in the 1970s, must not be
allowed to escape with their empty apology. ... The Cambodian
premier Hun Sen actually embraced these representatives of one of
the most gruesome regimes in history and promised them amnesty. ...
The international community must not accept Hun Sen's indulgence of
these villains. The government in Phnom Penh, which cannot survive
without foreign aid, must be pressed to punish Pol Pot's cronies
for their insane crimes.
	    &UR; ___
	   South China Morning Post, Hong Kong, on Khmer Rouge defection:
	   With the defection of its two remaining political leaders, Khieu
Samphan and Nuon Chea, the Khmer Rouge is dead. The question now,
for both Cambodia and the world community, is whether to let it
rest in peace or to exhume its old crimes before an international
tribunal. Should a group of old men be allowed to live out their
days in peace for the sake of national reconciliation, or be tried
for genocide and crimes against humanity? ...
	   National reconciliation may not be possible without putting a
few Khmer Rouge leaders on trial. Too many Cambodians suffered at
their hands to allow them to get away scot free. But the trials
must be conducted with a certain humility, and with the recognition
that this is the victor's justice, in which not all those
responsible will ever come to trial.
	    &UR; ____
	   Yomiuri Shimbun, Tokyo, on missile defense scheme:
	   The government has formally decided to launch Japan-U.S. joint
research and development on the theater missile defense (TMD)
scheme.
	   The introduction of the TMD system, which is meant to shoot down
an enemy's ballistic missiles after being launched, for example,
from ships equipped with the AEGIS air-defense system, should be
considered for the country to establish an airtight defense system.
	   In light of the uncertain security situation in areas
surrounding our nation, including the Korean Peninsula, Japan needs
to quickly proceed with the TMD system. ...
	   The launching of the joint Japan-U.S. technological research
itself indicates clearly both at home and abroad the strong will of
Japan and the United States in stopping the development and
proliferation of missiles. And the system itself should deter the
development and possession of missiles by other countries.
	    &UR; ___
	   La Nacion, Buenos Aires, on U.S. armed forces pay:
	   Bidding to avert the loss of its most talented U.S. servicemen,
the Pentagon has sent the ... government a proposal to raise wages
of officers, junior officers and enlisted personnel. The proposed
increase is on the order of 9.9 percent. If the proposal were to be
adopted, it would represent the greatest increase since president
Ronald Reagan decided in 1982 to raise salaries 14.3 percent for
officers and junior officers, and 17 percent for enlisted
personnel. The intention ... is to make careers in the armed forces
attractive to the most qualified in the population and allow
selectivity in recruiting. ... Argentine society, which still has
not resolved key questions in relation with its armed forces,
should take note of the decision making at the Pentagon ... as one
more point of reference on the road to restructuring its military
institutions.
	    &UR; ___
	   The Bangkok Post, Bangkok, Thailand, on the death of Islamic
extremist:
	   Abdurajak Abubakar Janjalani has been the most wanted man in the
Philippines for more than four years. He and his followers have
killed, injured or disrupted the lives of thousands of fellow
Filipinos since Janjalani returned to the Philippines from the
Middle East about nine years ago. He died in what appeared to be a
routine police patrol in the southern Philippines.
	   Janjalani led Abu Sayyaf _ Bearer of The Sword. ... It has
surely received aid from Libya and has had direct relations with
members of the Osama bin Laden group based in Afghanistan. Abu
Sayyaf also is believed by the Philippines military to have
provided aid to Ramzi Yousef, the Pakistani who planned to kill the
Pope and blow up 12 U.S. civilian airliners in one day from his
Manila base.
	   President (Jose) Estrada came to office in May with a promise to
coordinate closely with southern Filipinos. He has shown sympathy
for their demands for more home rule, although he has so far
implemented few of his election promises, such as more scholarships
for Muslim youths.
	   The death of Janjalani is a new opportunity for the government.
Mr. Estrada and his administration should move quickly as deeply
into the southern areas as possible. The government is fortunate to
have a recent record of accommodation with Muslim community leaders
with which to appeal to the southerners. Janjalani's death provides
a window of time to start to marginalize the violent Abu Sayyaf and
blunt its appeal to disillusioned people.
	    &UR; ___
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
