<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Year's World Roundup, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian nations kick off New Year's celebrations with fireworks,
</HEADLINE>
revelry &QL; 
 &UR; Precedes TOKYO
 &UR; Eds: For AMs; UPDATES throughout with European events, leaders'
messages &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By ROBERT SEELY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Europe geared up Thursday night for a
high-spirited welcome to the last year of the second millennium, as
partygoers took to the streets of their capital cities.
	   In Scotland, where New Year's is called Hogmanay and is
raucously celebrated, Edinburgh laid on pop concerts, a bagpipe
player and fireworks.
	   ``It is going to be really, really busy. Everything is sold out,
and everybody is going to party, whatever the weather,'' said Liz
Smith, from the city's New Year's organizing committee.
	   More than 6,000 cheerleaders and bandsmen have flown in from the
United States for London's New Year's Day parade on Friday.
	   Cardiff, Wales, organized a three-day Celtic event reviving the
tradition of giving gifts at New Year's. The event includes a
funfair, a lantern procession, live bands and a fireworks display.
	   In Vienna on Thursday, 2,600 runners turned out for the city's
annual 5.4 kilometer (3.3 mile) run along the city's
``ringstrasse,'' the street that encircles the heart of the city.
	   In taped messages, some of the world's political leaders urged
their peoples to end sectarian strike, and to have hope in the
future.
	   In his last New Year's message before leaving office, President
Nelson Mandela on Thursday challenged South Africans to continue
working together to solve the problems of poverty and corruption,
legacies of the apartheid decades.
	   ``The New Year will bring many changes,'' Mandela said in the
four-minute broadcast message. ``They will depend on our working
together to realize our dream.''
	   In a message broadcast across nine time zones, Russia's
President Boris Yeltsin called on Russians to meet 1999 with
optimism and pride in their country.
	   ``What can I say: The year was difficult for the country, for
many of you, and for me, too. But New Year's Eve is always about
new hopes, new dreams, new plans,'' Yeltsin said, according to a
transcript released by the Interfax news agency.
	   In Dublin, Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern spoke of the Good
Friday peace agreement in British-ruled Northern Ireland.
	   ``The fantastic support of people .. for an agreed Ireland of
dialogue, mutual respect and common endeavor is the surest
guarantee yet that we will succeed in making this an island of
peace and prosperity for all - especially for our children,'' Ahern
said.
	   A continent away and hours earlier, Asians welcomed the Year of
the Rabbit with displays of fireworks, official speeches and late
night pilgrimages to sacred shrines and temples.
	   Millions of Australians bid farewell to 1998 by watching a U.S.
dlrs 1.2 million fireworks extravaganza that bathed the harborside
Sydney Opera House in pulses of green, red and blue light.
	   Sydney celebrates every major holiday and event with fireworks,
but New Year's Eve is a pyrotechnic orgy, and this year's barrage
was a dress rehearsal for upcoming sky shows to mark next year's
welcome for the year 2000, and the summer Olympic Games in
September 2000.
	   In central Tokyo, crowds thronged Zojoji temple just before
midnight, waiting for a Buddhist monk to strike the temple bell 108
times to dispel the evils of the past year and usher in good luck
for the new year.
	   In much of Asia, 1999 is the Year of the Rabbit, and Tokyo's
department stores were well stocked with calendars, cards and
knickknacks bearing rabbit images.
	   For many Chinese, New Year's Eve is not nearly as important an
occasion as the Lunar New Year on Feb. 16 when hundreds of millions
of people head home for family reunions.
	   Still, television and radio audiences heard a rare live prime
time address by China's President Jiang Zemin, who was upbeat in
summing up 1998 and urged his people to be confident about the
future.
	   (rs-acw)
</TEXT>
