<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Prison Breaks, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0337 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chiapas officials investigate guards in prison breaks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with guards being questioned, CORRECTS that 17 sted 16
inmates escaped &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEJANDRO RUIZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Twelve prison guards
were being questioned Thursday by state authorities investigating
three separate prison breaks in southern Chiapas state.
	   Of the 17 inmates who escaped Wednesday in the towns of
Simojovel, Playas de Catazaja and Ocosingo, 12 remained at large.
All the fleeing inmates were serving time for homicide and other
major felonies.
	   State Attorney General Eduardo Montoya blamed negligence or
possible complicity by guards in the three prisons.
	   The first break occurred early Wednesday when two inmates
serving time for murder fled the jail in Simojovel, in the northern
part of the state.
	   Montoya said the guards there told investigators 10 armed men
wearing ski masks, like those used by Zapatista National Liberation
Army rebels, freed the two prisoners. Montoya said he doubted the
account, but the daily Reforma reported that witnesses confirmed
seeing the masked men.
	   Officials have assigned an additional 100 police officers to
each of the state's 23 prisons, fearing further violence on Jan. 1,
the fifth anniversary of the Zapatista uprising.
	   The Zapatista National Liberation Army began a brief uprising
Jan. 1, 1994, demanding more democracy and better conditions for
the state's poverty-ridden indigenous population. Peace
negotiations have been stalled since 1996.
	   Also Wednesday, nine convicts escaped during a prison mutiny in
Playas de Catazaja. The prisoners rioted to protest the lack of
drinking water. Guards opened fire and captured five of the
inmates, four of whom were wounded.
	   At about the same time, five inmates walked out of the prison in
Ososingo, a town in the jungle in the southern part of the state,
without anyone doing anything to stop them, he said.
</TEXT>
