<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pope-New Year's Eve </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pope: New Year a countdown to Christianity's 2000 Jubilee
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Pope John Paul II was counting down to 2000 _ not
1999 _ on his New Year's Eve, reminding Rome and the Roman Catholic
Church they had one year left to get ready for Christianity's
millennium jubilee.
	   John Paul delivered his year-end hymn of thanksgiving in Rome's
sumptuous rococo Church of St. Ignatius, looking ahead to what the
visiting millions would find in their jubilee-year pilgrimages
here.
	   ``In a year's time, we will already be in the holy year and
numerous pilgrims will be starting to arrive from every corner of
the Earth,'' he said.
	   ``I wish from my heart that they will be welcomed by a church
alive and rich in religious fervor; a church generous and sensible
toward the needs of mankind, especially the poor and those in
need.''
	   As is traditional, John Paul's listeners for the year-end
vespers service were a black-tie-and-fur crowd made up of many of
the church and civic leaders of Rome, including Mayor Francesco
Rutelli.
	   Much of their city is now shrouded in scaffolding and road-work
barriers in preparation for the 20 million or more pilgrims
expected for the jubilee year.
	   Speaking to _ and for _ them, John Paul said, ``I make a pledge
that our city will make its jubilee appointment fundamentally
renovated in all dimensions of spiritual and social life.''
	   John Paul is to inaugurate the jubilee on Christmas Eve 1999 and
close it on Epiphany, Jan. 6, 2000.
	   Although more stooped by the day, the 78-year-old pontiff seemed
to have no problems during Thursday's more than hourlong service.
Crowds greeted him outside, yelling out ``Happy New Year!'' and
``Best Wishes!'' to the pope, who stopped to press the hands of a
few.
	   The service followed days of rest after Christmas services. John
Paul's holiday schedule continues Friday with a New Year's
appearance at St. Peter's Basilica.
	   (ek) 	   
</TEXT>
