<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Chirac </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chirac salutes euro in New Year's address
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Europe's new currency has opened a new era that
offers France a chance for a better standard of living, President
Jacques Chirac told his nation in a New Year's address Thursday.
	   ``Europe already has a long history. And it has a long road
ahead. More and more, it will be our everyday life,'' Chirac said.
``The euro will change Europe and above all people's mentalities.''
	   Chirac's New Year's address was broadcast on French television
on Thursday night following the announcement earlier in Brussels of
the rate that fixed the franc and 10 other currencies to the euro.
	   The euro becomes reality at midnight, uniting the currencies of
the 11 participating countries. It will be used for cashless
transactions until 2002 when it will replace national currencies.
	   ``For us French, it's a chance,'' said Chirac, speaking of the
new currency. ``The euro will give us more choice in our purchases,
lower prices and new markets, new possibilities of investment and
therefore jobs. It will bring us more stability in an uncertain
world.''
	   Chirac, who was once one of France's most prominent
euroskeptics, has now become a firm backer of the new currency that
could one day rival the dollar.
	   ``It will bring us more stability in an uncertain world. More
force in the face of great economic poles that are developing on
the planet,'' Chirac said.
	   To take advantage of the new opportunities offered by the euro,
Chirac called on his countrymen to be more innovative, told them
that taxes would have to be lowered, and focus on high technology.
	   ``That is how we should construct our future. It's a great
ambition, a reasonable ambition and it's mine.''
	   (dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
