<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-South Africa-Nonwhites,0363 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South African team's racial make-up again sparks criticism
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Stands as 1st Ld-Writethru to some lines to CLARIFY in lead
that Tshwete met with South Africa's top cricket official; CORRECT
coding. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Outspoken Sports Minister
Steve Tshwete met with the South African cricket federation's top
official for an hour Thursday, after repeating past denunciations
that the national team doesn't have enough non-whites.
	   Ali Bacher, managing director of the United Cricket Board, said
in a telephone interview that he met with Tshwete at Fort Beaufort,
150 kilometers (90 miles) north east of Port Elizabeth in the
Eastern Cape Province.
	   But he refused to give details, saying he will release a
statement Friday.
	   Tshwete could not be reached for comment.
	   Bacher stood firm on Wednesday after both Tshwete and National
Sports Council president Mluleki George castigated the board for
choosing a team with only three players of color, a daily newspaper
in Johannesburg, Business Day, reported Thursday.
	   The team was announced after South Africa won the third of its
five test matches against West Indies on Tuesday and clinched the
series. It includes as non-whites Paul Adams, Herschelle Gibbs and
Ashwell Prince.
	   ``Once I have spoken to (Tshwete), I am sure he will feel
happier about the direction we are taking,'' Bacher was quoted as
saying in Business Day. ``The minister has been very good to
cricket over the years and I want to reassure him that we have no
intention of letting him down in terms of our transformation.''
	   Earlier this month, the governing African National Congress
threw its weight behind charges that racism was keeping non-whites
off national sports teams, and promised legislation to rectify the
problem.
	   The ANC charged that both the cricket and rugby federations were
not trying hard enough to promote talented players of other races.
	   The attack followed similar pronouncements by the National
Sports Council and Tshwete, who has announced the creation of a
special commission to explore integration efforts.
</TEXT>
