<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Venezuela-Inflation,0187 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Venezuelan inflation lowest in 12 years
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ Venezuela's inflation rate in 1998 was
about 30 percent, the lowest in 12 years but still one of the
highest in Latin America.
	   The December consumer price index rose 29.9 percent from
December 1997, the Central Bank reported Thursday. That was the
lowest since 1986's inflation rate of 12.7, according to
calculations by Dow Jones Newswires.
	   Annual inflation was 37.6 percent in 1997 and 103.2 percent in
1996.
	   This year's relatively low inflation came at the cost of an
economic tailspin. After failing to control inflation earlier in
the year, the Central Bank sharply increased interest rates and put
the breaks on the economy.
	   According to preliminary figures, gross domestic product will
contract 0.7 percent this year versus 5.9 percent growth in 1997.
	   Venezuela's oil-based economy has been hit hard this year by
falling world petroleum prices and uncertainty surrounding this
month's election of former coup leader Hugo Chavez as president. He
takes office on Feb. 2.
</TEXT>
