w2280 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-FemaleFighterP     12-31 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Female Fighter Pilot </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel's first female fighter pilot gets her wings
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DANA BUDEIRI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HATZERIM, Israel (AP) _ Israel's first woman fighter pilot got
her wings Thursday, to the cheers of a crowd that had leapt to its
feet in congratulations.
	   Second Lt. Sari, 21, a native of the well-appointed Tel Aviv
suburb of Raanana, will fly F-16 planes and operate sophisticated
airborne weapons systems, army officials said. It is army policy
not to release the last names of combat pilots.
	   ``Today, Sari begins a historic and very important road for the
women of Israel,'' Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said at the
courtyard of the air force museum where the pilots' graduation
ceremony was held.
	   While 18 year old Israeli women are routinely drafted for 21
months of military service, they do not serve as fighters. Sari is
the first woman to serve in a combat position, following a Supreme
Court decision last year ordering the air force to reverse the ban
on women in its pilot course.
	   As a military band played, air force commander Eitan Ben-Eliyahu
pinned symbolic wings on the graduating pilots. Sari, dressed in a
uniform of light blue shirt and dark blue trousers, stood
considerably shorter than her male colleagues. Her light brown hair
was tied back in a single braid.
	   ``We receive you with great happiness and love and we hope that
you will be an integral part of the air force for many years to
come,'' Ben-Eliyahu said in a personal congratulations message to
Sari. At the mention of her name, the crowd cheered and clapped.
	   After the graduation ceremony, the pilots broke out of their
rows and threw their caps in the air. Five planes put on an air
show overhead.
	   Sari will spend the next few months learning to use laser-guided
and other weapons while flying F-16's. Army officials said it was
routine for graduating pilots to train for an additional month or
two before engaging in active combat.
	   She would be the first woman in the history of the state of
Israel to do so.
	   Women and men fought side-by-side both in guerrilla battles
before and during the 1948 war for statehood but were banned from
combat positions once the Israeli state was established.
	   ``You need to give credit to those same wonderful women who were
already flying in the (pre-state) air force in the 1930's,'' said
Yael Rom, who was a reserve pilot and instructor in the air force
until the 1950's.
	   She also credited Sari for overcoming sexism _ repeating a
phrase often attributed to Israeli President Ezer Weizman, in the
days when he was an air force commander: ``The good men to flying,
and the good women to the flyers.''
	   Weizman has said he disagrees with the Supreme Court's decision
allowing women to be fighter pilots.
	   Earlier this week, an air force commander reportedly said it was
``not natural'' for women to be fighter pilots.
	   On Thursday, Mordechai said that he supports women flying in the
air force but that Israeli society needs to decide if women should
serve behind enemy lines.
 &UR; sb-rk
</TEXT>
