<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinian minister says he hopes state will come through talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Arafat quote, 3rd graf

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ A top Palestinian official said Thursday that
he expected a Palestinian state to be formed in 1999, but that he
hoped it would be as a result of negotiations with Israel.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has made contradictory
statements in recent months about whether he would unilaterally
declare a state on May 4, the deadline for reaching a permanent
Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement.
	   On Thursday, Arafat called upon supporters to ``continue until
we achieve a Palestinian state with its capital in holy
Jerusalem.''
	   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has threatened to walk
away from the peace talks and annex parts of the West Bank if
Arafat goes ahead with a unilateral declaration of statehood.
	   Israeli elections are scheduled for May 17, and it is believed
that a Palestinian declaration of statehood on May 4 would give a
boost to Netanyahu over his dovish challengers.
	   Palestinian Planning Minister Nabil Shaath suggested Thursday
that the Palestinians might be willing to hold off for a while on
declaring a state.
	   ``The sovereign state of Palestine will be declared in 1999, I
have no doubt,'' Shaath told Israel army radio.
	   ``But I still say that our preference is that we will finish
together the permanent status negotiations,'' he added.
	   Shaath said he did not want the declaration of a Palestinian
state to become the source of problems between the two people.
	   The Haaretz newspaper reported Thursday that Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak asked Arafat during recent talks to delay a
declaration of a state so as not to interfere in the Israeli
elections.
 &UR; sb 	   
</TEXT>
