w2307 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-UnfriendlyFire     12-31 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Unfriendly Fire,0668 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hasty blame in friendly fire incident angers Israelis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RON KAMPEAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Hours after a recruit was killed by friendly
fire, senior Israeli army officers announced their conclusion: his
immediate commander was to blame.
	   For an army that once prided itself on extended soul-searching
each time one of its troops fell, the haste was astonishing for
some _ but not surprising, given reports of the erosion of military
values after 16 years in Lebanon.
	   ``We have gone from being a small but clever army to a small but
stupid army,'' First Sgt. Ohad Zach's mother, Naomi, said in
remarks widely repeated in the media on Thursday.
	   On Wednesday afternoon, less than 18 hours after the incident,
Brig. Gen. Effi Eitam called a press conference.
	   Using diagrams, he explained that the rear section of an ambush
force opened fire on the forward section. And then he concluded:
``The main reason for this chain of professional mistakes was the
(squad) commander.''
	   Other soldiers in the unit, shocked at what they saw as Eitam's
unseemly hastiness, asked their relatives to tell the media that
the problem ran much deeper. Soldiers are barred from addressing
the media directly.
	   Efraim Nisim _ whose son, Guy, lost an eye _ said that soldiers
in the unit blamed the system more than they did the commander,
2nd. Lt. Assaf Lapid.
	   Nisim said that the recruits had warned Lapid's superiors in the
past that he had made navigational errors _ but they had failed to
heed their warnings.
	   ``I heard from my son and his friends that they didn't trust
Lapid, that they passed it on,'' he told Channel Two.
	   Ohad Zach's sister, Adva, said he had told her of similar
concerns that had been tossed aside. When she confronted the
brigade commander on Wednesday, she said, he offered her more of
the same, saying such incidents were not uncommon in the army.
	   She told Channel Two she found his demeanor frightening.
	   ``He was so sure of himself,'' she said. ``One must not let
yourself arrive at that level of self confidence. I see in this a
problem, perhaps one of erosion'' of military values.
	   Israeli doves have long charged that the occupation of south
Lebanon _ meant to contain guerrilla attacks on Israel's northern
borders _ has led to a series of failures that have crippled morale
and set up a hierarchy of blame.
	   ``Eitam blamed the company commander before he even
investigated,'' columnist Ofer Shelah wrote in Thursday's Maariv, .
``He just tossed him to the wolves: that's the backing the army
gives its commanders.''
	   Israel's security Cabinet was discussing Lebanon policy Thursday
night, a meeting planned long before the incident. Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's spokesman said the friendly fire incident was
not representative.
	   ``One soldier killed by friendly fire, if that was indeed the
case, doesn't indicate anything except that in one incident it was
a case of negligence,'' David Bar-Illan said Wednesday.
	   Second Lt. Lapid _ who Zach wounded in the hand in the incident
_ was willing to take responsibility, his father Herut said. But
Lapid wanted accountability higher up.
	   ``Our forces fired at each other, our children fired at each
other, and someone, in order to cover his rear end, would put Assaf
in jail,'' Herut Lapid told Channel One.
	   The incident was especially painful for the elder Lapid _ a hero
to many Israelis for his often successful efforts to get Israelis
and Jews out of prisons throughout the world. He was instrumental
in reducing the caning sentence handed to American teenager Michael
Fay in 1994.
	   Lapid's motto is the Talmudic injunction, ``All Israel must
guarantee one another,'' a value he learned a generation ago in an
Israeli army once famous for its officer's motto: ``Follow Me.''
	   After Wednesday's incident, he told Maariv, ``I'm in shock that
the army would place this disaster on my son's soldiers.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Israel-Unfriendly Fire; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
