u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Libya-Airlines     12-31 0245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Libya-Airlines </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Libya closes down foreign airline offices
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Libya ordered Thursday all foreign airlines
to close their offices in the country, Egypt's official news agency
reported.
	   The government said the closure would last until the United
States and Britain accepted that the World Court should settle the
dispute arising from the indictment of two Libyans charged with
blowing up a Pan Am airliner over the Scottish town of Lockerbie in
1988, killing 270 people, the Middle East News Agency reported from
the Libyan capital, Tripoli.
	   The Hague-based International Court of Justice, known as the
World Court, had ruled in February that it has the authority to
settle the dispute. The United Sates and Britain rejected any
intervention by the court, but later offered to try the two
suspects in The Netherlands before a panel of Scottish judges.
	   Airlines have been forbidden to fly to Libya since 1992 under
U.N. sanctions designed to force Tripoli to hand over the two
suspects.
	   However, foreign airline offices in Tripoli sell tickets for
travelers leaving Libya by road who plan to take flights from
neighboring countries.
	   Libya initially accepted in principle the U.S.-British offer of
a trial in The Netherlands, but has subsequently insisted that, if
convicted, the suspects should serve their sentences in Libya. The
Western plan is for the sentences to be served in Britain.
 &UR; my-jbm
</TEXT>
