<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Powerful PRI,0444 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican opposition parties struggle to define themselves
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo MO101 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARK STEVENSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexico's opposition parties ended the ruling
Insitutional Revolutionary Party's 68-year majority in Congress in
the 1997 elections. But for the second straight year, a split over
the budget has allowed the governing party, known as the PRI, to
push through most of its own proposal.
	   PRI legislators voted with lawmakers from the center-right
National Action Party to approve a dlrs 103 billion budget, with
new taxes and spending cuts intended to offset a dlrs 2.86 billion
shortfall caused by falling oil prices.
	   National Action, known as PAN, forced President Ernesto
Zedillo's party to give up plans for a 15 percent telephone usage
tax _ which would have been on top of an existing 15 percent tax.
	   But by voting with the PRI _ not only on the budgets, but also
on a dlrs 67 billion bank bailout proposal in December _ the PAN
may find it harder to attack the governing party as it campaigns
for seven governorships in 1999 and the presidency in 2000.
	   ``It's awfully hard to keep your cutting edge as the party of
protest and be responsible (on budget issues) at the same time,''
said Delal Baer, a researcher at the Washington-based Center for
Strategic and International Studies.
	   The other major party, the center-left Democratic Revolution
Party, was left powerless. It didn't participate in budget
negotiations and could do little but watch it get passed over its
objections. The Democratic Revolution had rejected the basic tenets
of both the budget _ which it claimed would soak already
impoverished taxpayers _ and the bank bailout, which it called
illegal.
	   The PAN's failure to establish itself as a clear alternative to
the PRI may have been partly responsible for its poor showing in
1998 state elections, in which it won only one of 10 races.
	   On Wednesday, PAN president Felipe Calderon announced he would
not seek re-election. Although he cited ``personal reasons,'' he
said in his resignation letter that ``the party needs an effort
toward renovation and new impulses from its leaders.''
	   For many PAN members, that means a return to the party's image
as a strong opposition, anti-corruption voice.
	   The PAN-PRI alliance has also made some members of the governing
party uncomfortable, and some have attacked the government's
market-oriented policies.
	   ``The PRI has origins in the left, not the right, that's why we
should make alliances with the left to meet social needs,'' said
Genaro Morales, spokesman for Critical Current.
</TEXT>
