<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-AP All-Pro,0537 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Five Vikings highlight All-Pro team
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BARRY WILNER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Football Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Five players for the Minnesota Vikings _ Randy,
Randle, two Randalls and a perfect placekicker _ were selected for
The Associated Press' NFL All-Pro team released Thursday.
	   Wide receiver Randy Moss, the first rookie on the team since
Jerome Bettis in 1993, was joined by quarterback Randall
Cunningham, guard Randall McDaniel, defensive tackle John Randle
and kicker Gary Anderson.
	   Moss, who made one of the biggest impacts of any rookie in
league history, was one vote short of being a unanimous choice.
Only Denver running back Terrell Davis received votes from all 47
members of a nationwide panel of sports writers and broadcasters.
	   ``I just go out there and try to do my job,'' said Moss, who
averaged 19 yards per reception for 69 catches and had a
league-high 17 TDs.
	   Cunningham led the NFL with a 106.0 passer rating, completing
60.9 percent of his passes for 3,704 yards and 34 touchdowns. A
backup at the start of the season, he replaced injured Brad Johnson
and guided the Vikings to a league-record 556 points.
	   The Vikings' 15-1 record was the best in the NFL this season.
	   ``You look around this locker room and see all the guys I get to
play with, they're the ones who really allowed us to achieve those
goals,'' Cunningham said.
	   McDaniel, the most dominant guard in the game, made the All-Pro
squad for the seventh time. He was joined at guard by Tennessee's
Bruce Matthews, 37, who made his 16th season one of his best.
Matthews has been an All-Pro five times, twice as a center.
	   Randle was a dynamo on Minnesota's defense, playing both tackle
and end. He is the kind of defender around whom game plans are
built.
	   ``It's a good honor,'' Randle said. ``Not the greatest one,
though. The Super Bowl is the greatest honor.''
	   Anderson had the first perfect year for an NFL kicker, hitting
all 35 field goals and all 59 extra points for a league mark of 164
points.
	   Three Green Bay Packers were selected: defensive end Reggie
White, safety LeRoy Butler and receiver Antonio Freeman.
	   Teams that had two players selected included Denver (Davis and
tight end Shannon Sharpe); Dallas (cornerback Deion Sanders and
tackle Larry Allen); San Diego (inside linebacker Junior Seau and
safety Rodney Harrison); and Tennessee (Matthews and punter Craig
Hentrich, who led the league with a 47.2 gross average and 39.2
net).
	   Also chosen on offense were Jacksonville tackle Tony Boselli,
Buffalo guard Ruben Brown and Pittsburgh center Dermontti Dawson,
who made it for the fifth consecutive year.
	   Joining White and Randle on the defensive line were the Giants'
Michael Strahan and Oakland's Darrell Russell.
	   At linebacker were Seattle's Chad Brown and the Jets' Mo Lewis
on the outside, with Miami's Zach Thomas and Seau inside.
	   Sanders and Ty Law of New England were the cornerbacks, with
Harrison and Butler at safety.
	   Fourteen AFC players and 13 from the NFC made the team.
Repeaters from last year were Sharpe, Boselli, Allen (at guard in
'97), Dawson, Davis, Alstott, Strahan, Randle, Sanders and Butler.
</TEXT>
