<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Slain Reporter,0227 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Suspects held for trial for murder of U.S. journalist
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Two Mexican suspects accused of killing
American reporter Philip True were ordered held for trial Thursday,
officials said.
	   Juan Chivarras de la Cruz, 28, and Miguel Hernandez de la Cruz,
24, have been charged with homicide and robbery, the Jalisco state
attorney general's office said.
	   True, 50, Mexico City correspondent for the San Antonio
Express-News, disappeared while hiking alone through a remote
region of the Sierra Madre in western Mexico, where he was pursuing
a story on the Huichol Indian culture. His body was found Dec. 16
in a shallow grave in west-central Jalisco state.
	   The suspects, both Huichol Indians, have confessed to the
killing.
	   Authorities said the suspects had told them they killed True
because he was trying to take their photographs without permission.
But in a court appearance and in interviews with reporters, the two
said Hernandez killed True after the reporter had kicked Hernandez
and forced his way into his house.
	   The state human rights commission is looking into the suspects'
claims that they had been tortured and that they were held for
several days before being presented before a judge. Under Mexican
law, suspects must appear before a judge within 48 hours of their
arrest.
</TEXT>
