<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-NFL Playoffs,0669 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Can a wild-card game participant equal Denver's 1997 feat?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAVE GOLDBERG &QC; 
 &UR; AP Football Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Arizona Cardinals are in a playoff game for
the first time in 16 years.
	   Dallas, Green Bay and San Francisco are back as usual, and so
are New England and Miami.
	   Four-year-old Jacksonville is in for the third time and
Buffalo's back with Doug Flutie.
	   But can any of those teams in this weekend's wild-card games
make it to the Super Bowl?
	   Only with a lot of luck.
	   Give Green Bay, which opens in San Francisco, the best shot,
largely because it's getting back some of the injured players that
made this such an up-and-down season. Also, most of the current
Packers have been through the playoff grind many times before. San
Francisco and Dallas have the experience, but too many holes to
likely advance beyond the second round.
	   So the four teams with byes _ Minnesota, Denver, the New York
Jets and Atlanta _ have the best shot at being in Pro Player
Stadium on Jan. 31.
	   The wild-card round starts Saturday with Buffalo at Miami,
followed by Arizona at Dallas. On Sunday, New England is at
Jacksonville, followed by Green Bay at San Francisco.
	   Next weekend, the home teams will be Atlanta, Denver, the Jets
and Minnesota in that order.
	   Minnesota and Denver, the top seeds, will play the lower of the
winning seeds, while the Falcons and Jets, each No. 2, will play
the higher seeds.
	   In the NFC, Dallas is seeded third, San Francisco fourth, Green
Bay fifth and Arizona six.
	   In the AFC, Jacksonville is three, Miami four, Buffalo five and
Miami six.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Green Bay (11-5) at San Francisco (12-4) &QC; 
	   This was the NFC championship game last season, but both teams
have slipped badly despite their records. Neither would consider
the season a success unless they get at least as far as the NFC
title game and probably to the Super Bowl.
	   The Packers won 36-22 in Green Bay on Nov. 1, giving them five
straight wins over the 49ers, three in the playoffs. This week,
they welcomed back Robert Brooks, Vonnie Holliday, Mark Chmura and
Craig Newsome from injuries of varying degrees.
 &UR; Buffalo (10-6) at Miami (10-6) &QC; 
	   Doug Flutie vs. Dan Marino in the city that made Dougie famous,
site of the ``Hail Mary'' in 1984 that beat the University of Miami
for Boston College.
	   Flutie didn't play in the first Bills-Dolphins game, a 13-7
Miami win. But he helped rally Buffalo to a 30-24 win at home.
	   Miami was 7-1 at home and allowed only 82 points there. But this
game might have turned when defensive end Jason Taylor, one of the
most important players in Jimmy Johnson's defense, broke his
collarbone in Atlanta last Sunday.
	   Because the Super Bowl is in Miami, this has been a target year
for the Dolphins, although their chances now look marginal.
 &UR; Arizona (9-7) at Dallas (10-6) &QC; 
	   Will the Cardinals, who won seven games by three points or less,
just be happy to be here, or are they anxious to erase another blot
on the franchise's escutcheon _ 51 years without a playoff win?
	   The Cardinals could have a shot because of another Sanders,
Deion, who will probably rest his injured toe again.
	   This could be high scoring. The Cowboys, who have beaten Arizona
nine straight times at Texas Stadium and 16 of 17 times overall,
won both regular-season games, 38-10 at home and 35-28 on the road.
 &UR; New England (9-7) at Jacksonville (11-5) &QC; 
	   Which quarterbacks show up? Scott Zolak for New England against
Jonathan Quinn or Mark Brunell. The decision won't be made until
late, but it's already clear that Drew Bledsoe (broken finger)
won't play for the Patriots and Brunell (high ankle sprain) will
try.
	   It that happens, it's a big edge for the Jaguars, who looked
good beating a listless Pittsburgh team 21-3 in a meaningless game
Monday night.
	   If Quinn starts, the Pats have a decent shot, because Zolak is
by far the more experienced and poised.
</TEXT>
