<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Boxing-Foreman-Holmes,0247 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Old-timers fight may be on borrowed time
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HOUSTON (AP) _ Promoter Roger Levitt remained upbeat Thursday
about the prospects for the George Foreman-Larry Holmes fight set
for Jan. 23, although it was unclear whether he had met financial
deadlines.
	   ``The fight is doing fine,'' Levitt said at midday. ``We believe
the fight is 100 percent on. We're doing some financial
machinations with George and Larry. We're confident by the close of
business Monday, we'll be OK.''
	   Foreman is to receive dlrs 10 million and Holmes dlrs 4 million
and both have said they would not take less for the fight. The
status of the bout was clouded when one of its major backers pulled
out last week. Levitt said a replacement backer had been located
this week. So far, Foreman has received dlrs 1 million and Holmes
dlrs 400,000 _ both nonrefundable.
	   The promoter was supposed to file letters of credit assuring the
purses of the two ex-heavyweight champions by the close of business
Thursday.
	   ``We had an extension for the letters of credit until the close
of business Los Angeles time,'' he said. ``We might need another
extension.
	   ``There's been amazing good will by the fighters. Everybody
wants this fight to take place. In my honest opinion, it will. I
believe the fight will happen because they want it to happen.''
	   Levitt was unavailable late Thursday afternoon to say whether he
had the letters of credit in place.
</TEXT>
