</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0794 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Blue-chip stocks slid into the close of 1998,
but the Nasdaq market set another record as investors sought out
better values among smaller-company stocks. The Dow Jones
industrial average dropped 93.21 points _ or by 1 percent _ at
9,181.43, about 200 points below the Nov. 23 record of 9,374.27,
but a still impressive gain of 16.2 percent for the year.
(US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Europe's leaders proclaimed a new era
Thursday as 11 nations, including the continent's biggest economic
powers, merged currencies to create the euro, a shared money they
say will boost business, underpin unity and strengthen their role
in world affairs. ``If the postwar era ended nine years ago with
the fall of the Berlin Wall, then our future begins on Jan. 1,
1999,'' German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder wrote in the
Handelsblatt business daily. At the stroke of midnight on New
Year's Eve, after years of preparation, the euro becomes the common
currency of Germany, France, Italy, Spain, the Netherlands,
Belgium, Austria, Portugal, Finland, Ireland and Luxembourg. (THE
EURO)
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Returning to a pet theme, German Finance
Minister Oskar Lafontaine hinted he favors further interest rate
cuts by the European Central Bank on Thursday, just hours before
the launch of the euro. In an article published in Germany's
business daily Handelsblatt, Lafontaine said interest rate cuts in
early December in the 11 countries joining the euro were ``a right
step.'' The coordinated cuts on Dec. 3 lowered the ECB's key
interest rate to 3 percent. ``With a stability-oriented financial
and wage policy, the ECB has more room for a monetary policy that
supports growth and employment,'' Lafontaine wrote. Since taking
office in October, Lafontaine has stirred controversy with repeated
calls for lower rates to help Europe's governments fight
chronically high unemployment and flagging growth.
(GERMANY-INTEREST RATES)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government pinned a number Thursday to the
weakening ruble, announcing that its value had dropped almost 70
percent over the last four months in relation to the U.S. dollar.
And it announced that annual inflation, which appeared under
control until the financial crisis hit in August, reached 84.4
percent in 1998. Russia is caught in the worst economic slide since
the Soviet collapse seven years ago, sparked by the Asian financial
crisis, falling world prices for oil _ Russia's biggest export
earner _ and successive governments' chronic inability to finance
expenditures. In 1998, the country's gross domestic product shrank
5 percent and industrial production by 5.5 percent, the Economy
Ministry said Thursday. Foreign trade declined by 13.6 percent in
the first 11 months of the year, and exports to countries outside
the former Soviet Union dropped 17.6 percent from last year,
reaching dlrs 57.7 billion, the ministry said. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Analysts say it's too soon to tell if last
week's unexpectedly big jump in unemployment claims is a sign that
tough times abroad are hitting U.S. companies harder. ``I wouldn't
read too much into it,'' said Mark M. Zandi an economist with
Regional Financial Associates. ``We'll have to see early next year
if these high unemployment claims are maintained.'' The number of
Americans filing for unemployment benefits during the week ending
the day after Christmas rose by 79,000 to a seasonally adjusted
368,000, the Labor Department said Thursday. That's the biggest
weekly increase since July of 1992. It pushed claims to their
highest level since summer, when a General Motors strike
temporarily boosted unemployment. (US-JOBLESS CLAIMS)
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ Venezuela's inflation rate in 1998 was
about 30 percent, the lowest in 12 years but still one of the
highest in Latin America. The December consumer price index rose
29.9 percent from December 1997, the Central Bank reported
Thursday. That was the lowest since 1986's inflation rate of 12.7,
according to calculations by Dow Jones Newswires. Annual inflation
was 37.6 percent in 1997 and 103.2 percent in 1996. This year's
relatively low inflation came at the cost of an economic tailspin.
After failing to control inflation earlier in the year, the Central
Bank sharply increased interest rates and put the breaks on the
economy. According to preliminary figures, gross domestic product
will contract 0.7 percent this year versus 5.9 percent growth in
1997. (VENEZUELA-INFLATION)
</TEXT>
