<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0599 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   NEW YORK _ The world offered a high-spirited welcome to the last
year of the second millennium, with fireworks in Scotland,
pilgrimages to shrines and temples in Asia, and the gathering of
hundreds of thousands of revelers in New York for the annual
descent of a 500-pound (227-kilo) aluminum ball. Partygoers took to
the streets in Europe's capitals Thursday night to welcome the last
year of the second millennium, while Asia greeted 1999 with
fireworks and temple bells. Pope John Paul II reminded Roman
Catholics to prepare for Christianity's millennium jubilee only a
year away. And in many countries, leaders spoke to their countrymen
and women of hope for a better future. (NEW YEAR'S WORLD ROUNDUP)
	   LUANDA, Angola _ The Angolan government offered the United
Nations its full cooperation in trying to reach the site of a
downed U.N.-chartered plane to determine the fate of the 14 people
on board. The government announced the decision Thursday after
repeated appeals from the United Nations following last Saturday's
crash near the central highland city of Huambo. The offer of help
came hours before the Security Council held an emergency meeting in
New York to pass a resolution condemning inaction on the part of
the government and the rebel UNITA group in reaching the crash
victims. (ANGOLA)
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ The coalition of West African troops
protecting Sierra Leone's elected president exchange artillery fire
near the capital with insurgents who have been advancing toward
Freetown in recent days. Diplomats and Defense Ministry officials
who spoke on condition of anonymity say heavy shelling rocked the
hills south of Freetown. A senior commander with the West African
defense force, known as ECOMOG, said troops had driven the rebels
back from their positions in the hills. There were no immediate
reports of casualties, but thousands of civilians in the area fled
to Freetown, about 20 kilometers (12 miles) to the north. (SIERRA
LEONE-FIGHTING)
	   SIHANOUKVILLE, Cambodia (AP) _ Two former Khmer Rouge leaders
and their well-dressed wives, children and grandchildren received a
government-arranged pleasure tour of the country they ravaged in
the 1970s, a trip that is expected to take them through the killing
fields of their murderous rule. High-level officials and soldiers
armed with assault rifles escorted the motorcade of
chauffeur-driven Toyota Land Cruisers Thursday to the seaside
resort of Sihanoukville, 110 miles (180 kilometers) southwest of
the capital. The beneficial treatment of Khieu Samphan and Nuon
Chea is feeding growing anger among human rights and democracy
groups. (CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE)
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexico's Congress has approved a budget that
leaves new taxes and spending cuts. It also leaves opposition
parties searching for their identity. Mexico's opposition parties
ended the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party's 68-year
majority in Congress in the 1997 elections. But for the second
straight year, the two major opposition parties split over the
budget, allowing the governing party, known as the PRI, to push
through most of its own proposal. PRI legislators voted Thursday
with lawmakers from the center-right National Action Party to
approve a dlrs 103 billion budget, with new taxes and spending cuts
intended to offset a dlrs 2.86 billion shortfall caused by falling
oil prices. (MEXICO-POWERFUL PRI)
</TEXT>
