<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0300 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from El Salvador and Nicaragua. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) _ Fires destroyed thousands of
stalls at two markets in El Salvador, killing three children and
leaving 18 people injured.
	   The larger fire destroyed half of the central market of San
Salvador, the capital, affecting more than 10,000 merchants in
2,500 small businesses selling clothing, food and other items.
	   The fire, believed to have been started by a short circuit,
burned for 10 hours Wednesday before firefighters brought it under
control. Losses were estimated at more than dlrs 1.3 million.
	   The other fire destroyed a market and three businesses Wednesday
in Apopa, a city north of the capital. Three children _ ages 3, 7
and 9 _ who were sleeping in a nearby house were killed.
	   ___
	   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) _ The death toll in an explosion last
week at a sugar processing plant reached 11 on Thursday, when the
sole survivor of the blast died of burns from scalding sugar cane
juice.
	   Marco Antonio Mejia, 42, died of third-degree burns over 95
percent of his body he suffered during the Dec. 26 explosion in a
boiler at the Ingenio San Antonio plant in the northwestern
province of Chinandega.
	   Doctors at a Managua's Roberto Huembes Medical Center were
surprised that Mejia held on as long as he did. ``Only God's will
and Marco Antonio Mejia's supernatural resistance keep him alive,''
Dr. Larry Ubeda told reporters Tuesday.
	   The blast occurred when workers tried to fix a broken pump on
the boiler, and were sprayed with boiling cane juice. The 10 other
victims, all employees of the sugar mill, died within 48 hours of
the blast.
	   Labor Ministry investigators are expected to issue a report on
the accident in early January.
</TEXT>
