<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Cave-Rescue </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rescuers seek to recover injured spelunker deep underground
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RAY LILLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ A rescue team on Friday reached a
cave explorer lying injured with a broken arm and leg some 3 1/2
miles (5.5 km) underground in one of the Southern Hemisphere's
deepest cave systems.
	   It will take two doctors who are joining the rescue more than a
day just to reach the man.
	   Authorities first received word on Thursday, a day after Kieran
McKay slipped from a descent rope and fell 50 feet (15 meters) down
a rock face to the floor below.
	   A doctor and initial rescue team entered the Bulmer cave system
near Murchison, New Zealand, 125 miles (200 km) south of the
capital, Wellington, on Thursday night, New Year's Eve.
	   Police said it could be days before rescuers can bring
experienced spelunker McKay, 30, back to the surface.
	   ``If you measure the distance out and crawl on your hands and
knees for that far under a line of cars, that's what we're up
against,'' said Senior Constable John Haynes, the police spokesman.
	   ``The rescue could take anything between two and four days.''
	   Experienced spelunker from throughout New Zealand were being
rushed to the remote area for the deepest rescue effort made here.
	   McKay was with a team of 11 others mapping an unexplored section
of the Bulmer caves when the fall occurred.
	   The cave system, only discovered in 1985, has been mapped for
more than 25 miles (40km) and is the second-deepest known system in
the Southern Hemisphere with depths up to 2,600 feet (800 meters).
	   The first rescue team reached McKay on Friday, Haynes said.
	   He said McKay was conscious and ``quite chirpy. They're a tough
bunch, these cavers.''
	   Rescue training in the Bulmer caves early in 1998 had been so
difficult the ``patient'' had to get off his stretcher and climb a
140 foot (43-meter) cliff on his own after rescuers decided
carrying him up it was too dangerous.
</TEXT>
