w2579 &Cx1f; wstm-
u m &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-Obit-JohnnyMo     12-31 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Obit-Johnny Moore </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report Drifters lead singer Johnny Moore dies at 64
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Johnny Moore, lead singer of the American pop
group The Drifters in the 1960s, has died in London, news reports
said Friday. He was 64.
	   Moore, whose high tenor voice was heard most famously in ``Under
the Boardwalk,'' had moved to England after the group had a string
of hits in Britain in the mid-1970s, The Daily Telegraph said.
	   He died Wednesday while on his way to a hospital in London, The
Guardian reported. No cause of death was given.
	   The Drifters were formed in 1953 and still tour, but there have
been a number of changes in the composition of the group.
	   John Darrel Moore, born in Selma, Alabama, joined in November
1954, a year after the group was formed around the tenor vocals of
Clyde McPhatter. McPhatter was drafted in 1954 and Moore won a
place in the band.
	   ``Steamboat'' was one of their 1950s hits.
	   In 1958, after growing tension between manager George Treadwell
and the band, Treadwell fired them all and hired another group to
be The Drifters.
	   In 1961, after a stint of military service, Moore was invited to
rejoin The Drifters.
	   At the time, Rudy Lewis was lead singer, and Moore sang with him
on ``Sweets for the Sweet,'' ``Up on The Roof'' and ``On Broaway.''
	   When Lewis died in 1964, Moore became lead singer with ``Under
the Boardwalk,'' the group's last Top Ten hit.
	   When their American success declined in the 1970s, The Drifters
found popularity in Britain. Among their hits from 1973 to 1976
were ``Kissing in the Back Row of the Movies,'' and ``You're More
than a Number in My Little Red Book.''
	   Moore married and settled in Britain. He is survived by his
wife, Jennifer, and three sons.
	   Funeral plans were not announced.
	   (acw)
</TEXT>
