<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India wants a winning start to 1999
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IHITHISHAM KAMARDEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HAMILTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Although 1-0 down and beset with
problems, Indian skipper Mohammed Azharuddin is convinced his side
can turn the tables on New Zealand in the third and final cricket
test beginning Saturday.
	   India is tagged as a team that can't win tests outside the
subcontinent, and Azharuddin wants to put that notion to rest at
least by leveling the three-match series with a win.
	   ``This series is reasonably within our hands,'' Azharuddin said
Friday. ``We can't win it, but at least we can square it.''
	   India squandered a great opportunity in the second test and was
eventually beaten by a rejuvenated New Zealand team by four
wickets.
	   ``It is our bowling and fielding. And if we get things together
here I think we can look forward to a promising 1999,'' Azharuddin
added.
	   ``The only way we could do it is by reflecting on the positives
in the last test and play this as a separate one.''
	   Azharuddin is looking for a team performance.
	   ``I think confidence-wise individuals might be a bit low, but I
think mentally everybody realizes that we've got to be together and
we've got to try to win this test match,'' he said.
	   ``I'd like to get the monkey off our back with a win here. A win
outside India is long overdue.''
	   India's main area of concern is the fielding and bowling _ to
support match-winners like medium paceman Javagal Srinath and leg
spinner Anil Kumble.
	   Coach Aunshuman Gaekwad said his fielders had a ``bad one'' in
the second test, dropping as many as seven catches.
	   ``We are not that bad a fielding side,'' said Gaekwad. ``We
normally don't drop that many catches and misfield. It hasn't
happened before and it will not happen in the future.''
	   ``From the time I took over the boys have fielded brilliantly at
times, like any other international sides.''
	   New Zealand captain Stephen Fleming expects India to come back
strongly and said his side will have to play better to carry on
with the good win in Wellington.
	   ``It is a new test and they are a very good side and will come
back strongly,'' said Fleming. ``We will have to play better to
stop them.''
	   Both teams have put off naming the side until a final look at
the relaid strip that sports a fair tinge of green and is expected
to suit the seamers.
	   India will decide between left-arm spinner Sunil Joshi and
Debashish Mohanty while New Zealand will weigh its options between
off spinner Paul Wiseman and left-arm seamer Geoff Allott.
	   Teams:
	   NEW ZEALAND (from): Stephen Fleming (captain), Matthew Bell,
Matthew Horne, Roger Twose, Craig McMillan, Adam Parore, Chris
Cairns, Dion Nash, Daniel Vettori, Simon Doull, Paul Wiseman and
Geoff Allott.
	   INDIA (from): Mohammed Azharuddin (captain), Navjot Sidhu, Ajay
Jadeja, Rahul Dravid, Saurav Ganguly, Sachin Tendulkar, Nayan
Mongia, Anil Kumble, Javagal Srinath, Venkatesh Prasad, Sunil
Joshi, Debashish Mohanty and Harbhajan Singh.
	   Umpire: Doug Cowie (New Zealand) and Rudy Koertzen (South
Africa). TV umpire: Brent Bowden.
	   Match referee: Barry Jarman (Australia).
 &UR; (ik/djp) 	   
</TEXT>
