<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Bahrain-Changed Society,0756 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gulf's changes reflected in Bahrain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY332 &QL; 
 &UR; By ADNAN MALIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) _ The women are draped in exquisite green,
red or purple silk robes, their sleeves and bodices embroidered
with gold. In their braided hair are garlands of flowers.
	   Nearby, men in traditional dishdashas are hard at work _
tinsmiths and tailors, fishermen and pearl divers.
	   In these scenes at the Bahrain National Museum, the costumed
mannequins portray an idealized past when most people in this Gulf
nation made their living from farms or from the sea and typically
ate a diet of dates, rice and fish.
	   Stepping outside into a city of international banks, high-rise
buildings and Western fast-food restaurants, it's startling to see
how much _ and how quickly _ life has changed in Bahrain and other
gulf states.
	   A new world was made by oil, which pumped big money into
Bahrain's economy, and now it is being remade as the oil runs out.
But it's not yet 70 years since Bahrain became the first Arab gulf
state where oil was discovered in commercial quantities.
	   Oil production came later to other Gulf countries _ in the late
1930s in Saudi Arabia, the '40s in Kuwait, and the '60s, '70s and
even '80s in some of the tiny states of the United Arab Emirates.
	   In the region's deserts, the influx of oil money ended the
trading caravans of thousands of camels and the tradition of
``ghazu,'' or tribal raiding. In Bahrain, a small island nation,
the simple seashore life disappeared.
	   Pearling was dying as Bahrain's economic mainstay _ killed by
Japanese cultured pearls _ even before the discovery of oil. Now,
there are precious few pearl divers and builders of dhows, the
wooden sailboats of the gulf.
	   ``People rarely do the kind of things their ancestors did,''
said Essa Amin, president of Bahrain's Historical and
Archaeological Society. ``Someone whose ancestor was a farmer,
fisherman or a pearl merchant is now a businessman, banker, doctor
or an engineer.''
	   The change brought by oil money can be seen everywhere.
	   Until the 1950s, donkeys were used to haul up water from wells;
it now is pumped from desalination plants.
	   Graceful old Bahraini houses had tall wind towers that drew cool
ocean breezes inside. Today, most homes are air-conditioned, and
shoppers go to vast, icy-cool malls instead of the old downtown
souk, or marketplace.
	   The souk still exists _ with its gold, bolts of fabric and
delicious smell of spices _ but now it also offers Cokes,
battery-operated Japanese toy cars and goods from almost
everywhere.
	   Amin notes another change from the days when Bahraini men all
wore dishdashas and women draped themselves in the robe-like
``aba'' on the street.
	   ``These days, most of those Bahraini women who wear abas ...
wear Western outfits like tight-fitting jeans or short skirts
underneath,'' he said.
	   For men, typical dress can be jeans when going out to the
Mexican restaurant or a three-piece suit for work.
	   The business suit signals another new world for Bahrain and the
gulf.
	   As it led the way with oil, Bahrain is ahead in facing the day
when oil runs out. Its reserves are expected to dry up by 2000, and
it has become a leading center for banking and finance.
	   The change is not without its problems for the region.
	   In Kuwait, people are resisting a dismantling of the
cradle-to-grave welfare system financed by oil. In Bahrain, the
government has had to come up with training programs to give its
young people skills for the new business and service economy.
	   At 85, businessman Rashid al-Zayani has a foot in both the old
and new Bahrain.
	   His commercial empire includes banking, a car dealership,
plastics and high-tension cables. He won't reveal his net worth but
recalls his first job in the 1930s paid the equivalent of dlrs 13 a
month, ``a good salary in the old days.''
	   ``People are more educated and earn much better salaries than in
the past,'' he said, sitting in his air-conditioned office.
	   On the wall are photos showing the span of his life. Recent
color shots show him in a tuxedo. In an old, black-and-white
picture, he is starting school at age 4 in traditional robe and
headdress, standing with the Egyptian headmaster who opened the
first modern school in Bahrain, then a British protectorate. The
year was 1917.
	   ``The society is rapidly changing,'' said Amin, the historian.
``But the future looks definitely brighter.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Bahrain-Changed Society; CT:i; 
