w2608 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-BalloonQues     12-31 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Balloon Quest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Winds continue to cause problems for balloon team
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Tentative launch time is 5 a.m. local time on Jan. 2 (1930 GMT
Jan. 1)
 &UR; AP Photos ASP101-102
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALICE SPRINGS, Australia (AP) _ Buffeted by 40-knot (75-kph)
winds, the U.S.-Australian team making the latest bid to be the
first to fly around the world in a balloon canceled some equipment
tests Friday.
	   In last minute tests ahead of Saturday's scheduled launch,
engineers planned to bring the spaceship-like crew's capsule out of
its hanger and fit it with solar panels, which will provide power
to run life support and other systems during the flight.
	   But mission control director Dan Pedersen canceled the operation
because of concerns about dust being blown up from the desert
launch zone.
	   ``We don't want the gondola to get blown around,'' said
Pedersen.
	   Strong winds and equipment problems have twice delayed the
launch.
	   At another hanger at mission control _ a collection of tin sheds
near the central Australian town of Alice Springs _ pilot Bob
Martin worked with team members on the harness systems joining the
capsule, which will carry the three crew members, to the huge
balloon and a parachute.
	   Playing a waiting game with the weather, team members were also
considering a ``live-firing'' test of the explosive bolts that are
designed to cut the capsule free of the balloon in an emergency.
	   ``We definitely could have gone this morning,'' said Pedersen, a
former U.S. Navy captain and fighter pilot.
	   ``But we can't control the weather.''
	   The team's own forecaster will brief Pedersen and pilots Martin,
Denver real estate magnate Dave Liniger and Australian balloonist
John Wallington later Friday on the latest weather conditions.
	   The team will make a decision then whether to start the more
than 12-hour countdown clock for the new scheduled launch time of 5
a.m. Saturday, Jan. 2 local time (1930 Jan. 1 GMT).
	   Pedersen canceled Thursday's launch after the team decided winds
forecast for New Year's Day were too strong at 900 ft. _ the height
reached by the top of the balloon as it fills with helium.
	   Liniger said he and his copilots are anxious to get off the
ground.
	   ``We want to go,'' Liniger said. ``It's possible that the longer
we wait, the worse the weather will get, and we will end up wasting
millions of dollars and a lot of people's time.''
	   Weather conditions give the Re/Max International team a window
for take off that lasts until mid-January.
	   After that, the high altitude winds now blowing east to west
will shift direction until next December.
	   The team expects to succeed where other around-the-world balloon
attempts have failed by rising to the edge of the atmosphere and
harnessing those winds on a route that almost exactly follows the
Tropic of Capricorn.
	   The pilots will hang below a balloon made of lunch-wrap-thin
polyethylene plastic in a 7-feet-by-8-feet (2.1-meter-by-2.4-meter)
capsule packed with life-support systems, scientific equipment,
food, waste disposal units and cameras and communications gear.
	   When fully inflated, the balloon is 460 feet (138 meters) in
diameter and 700 feet (210 meters) high _ large enough to envelope
the Houston Astrodome or two 747 jet liners nose-to-nose.
	   It will rise 1,000 feet (300 meters) a minute during takeoff
until it reaches the stratosphere and a cruising altitude of about
24 miles (39 kilometers) above sea level.
	   That's higher than any previous manned balloon flight.
	   The pilots will wear Russian-built space suits during parts of
the journey, where the atmosphere outside will be less than 1
percent of that at sea level.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Balloon Quest; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
