<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Divorces,0195 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese divorce rate tops France's
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A record number of Japanese married couples called
it quits in 1998, according to a government report that showed
divorce rates here catching up with those in the West.
	   There were an estimated 243,000 divorces in Japan last year,
almost 10 percent more than the year before and the largest number
since officials started keeping records a century ago, the Health
and Welfare Ministry said in a report released Thursday.
	   One couple was divorced about every two minutes, the report
said.
	   Japan's divorce rate rose to 1.94 per every 1,000 people,
pushing it above France's rate of 1.90 and close to Germany's 2.07,
according to the report. The United States still has the highest
divorce rate among major nations with 4.44 per 1,000.
	   The report expressed alarm that Japan's divorce rate had
quadrupled since World War II, bringing it up to the levels of
Western countries.
	   Japanese politicians in the past have viewed the trend with
alarm, calling Japan's traditionally cohesive families the key to
the country's low crime rates and high levels of education.
</TEXT>
