<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-NHL Roundup,0391 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Maple Leafs 4, Red Wings 2
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DETROIT (AP) _ Curtis Joseph made 36 saves and Mats Sundin had
two assists as the Toronto Maple Leafs beat Detroit 4-2 Thursday
night, extending the Red Wings' winless streak to seven games.
	   Igor Korolev, Steve Thomas, Fredrik Modin and Derek King scored
goals for the Maple Leafs, who moved a point ahead of idle Buffalo
atop the Northeast Division. Toronto, which won all three of its
games against the Red Wings this season, is 12-5 in its last 17
games.
	   Martin Lapointe and Darren McCarty scored for the Red Wings, who
closed out a 4-7-2 December. The seven-game winless streak is
Detroit's longest since a seven-game losing streak in January
1991.
 &UR; Stars 6, Bruins 1 &QC; 
	   At Dallas, Pat Verbeek scored two goals and Mike Keane got the
tiebreaker early in the second period as the Dallas extended its
unbeaten string to a franchise-record 13 games.
	   Keane snapped a 1-1 tie and Sergei Zubov extended the lead to
3-1 late in the second period to help the Stars extend their
unbeaten run to 10-0-3. The previous club record was a 9-0-3 streak
by the Minnesota North Stars in 1982.
	   Ray Bourque notched his 379th career goal for Boston's only
score. The Bruins are 1-4 in their last five games and haven't won
in Dallas since Feb. 16, 1994.
 &UR; Blackhawks 1, Islanders 0 &QC; 
	   At Chicago, Bob Probert scored his second goal of the season and
Jocelyn Thibault stopped 28 shots for his first shutout with
Chicago.
	   The Islanders, blanked for a second straight game, have lost
three in a row. Chicago's victory was just its second in the last
eight games.
	   Probert chased down a rebound off a shot from newly acquired
Nelson Emerson and his follow from the goal line deflected off
Marcel Cousineau's skate and into the net with 2:40 left in the
second.
 &UR; Canadiens 2, Flames 1 &QC; 
	   At Calgary, Alberta, Montreal defenseman Eric Weinrich scored
one goal and assisted on another as Montreal won its third straight
game.
	   Weinrich's power-play goal 22 seconds into the second period
stood up as the winner for the Canadiens, who have beaten Toronto,
Edmonton and Calgary since ending an 11-game winless stretch.
	   Michael Nylander scored for the Flames, who lost their fifth
straight game overall and franchise-record sixth straight at home.
	    &UR; MORE 	   
</TEXT>
